<FIRST>r a AM-SharkAttack 1stLd-Writethru a0798 08-10 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shark Attack, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0798,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Attacked by Shark in Bahamas</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to CORRECT that hand was lost in shark attack,
sted amputated at hospital; UPDATES with quotes from trauma center nurse.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman spearfishing off the Bahamas lost her right
hand Wednesday in an apparent shark attack when she was surfacing
with a speared fish in her hand, authorities said.
   Judy St. Clair, 31, a diving instructor from Marathon, was
attacked while snorkeling with friends and her parents off Highborn
Cay near Great Exuma Island, about 220 miles southeast of Miami,
said Coast Guard Petty Officer Steven Sapp.
   Ms. St. Clair was treated on the scene by a Miami plastic
surgeon who was boating nearby and heard the group's distress call.
She then was airlifted by the Coast Guard to Nassau and on to Miami
for more extensive medical treatment.
   Officials at Miami's Jackson Memorial Hospital said they didn't
know until Ms. St. Clair arrived that her hand had actually been
bitten off in the attack.
   ``The hand is gone,'' said nurse Jeanne Eckes, Jackson's trauma
center coordinator. ``It's an amputation above the wrist. The
injury itself actually goes to the wrist and encompasses the
wrist.''
   ``From the looks of her hand, it was a big animal that did
this,'' Ms. Eckes said. ``We can presume it was a shark attack.''
   Ms. St. Clair underwent surgery Wednesday night to clean the
wound and was listed in stable condition. She will have to undergo
future surgery for ``extensive repair,'' said the nurse, adding
that the severed hand was not recovered.
   ``I think she's in good spirits for what she's been through,
absolutely,'' Ms. Eckes said.
   Authorities said Ms. St. Clair was surfacing by the boat with a
grouper in her hand when a shark grabbed at the fish and her hand,
pulling her down into the water.
</TEXT>
