<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 0123EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Sevastopol     08-10 0779</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sevastopol,0799</SECOND>
<HEAD>In Sevastopol, Closed Borders Protect Sausage, Not Secrets</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAREY GOLDBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEVASTOPOL, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Now that hundreds of U.S. Navy
sailors have roamed its streets, this restricted Black Sea port
seems to have little left to hide.
   But some residents want Sevastopol kept off-limits anyway _ not
to preserve military secrets, but to keep its supplies of sausage
and other foodstuffs out of the hands of other Soviets.
   ``To talk about military secrets after this visit is absurd,''
said Sergei Koshkin, deputy editor in chief of the local newspaper,
The Glory of Sevastopol. ``But to tell the truth, the population
doesn't want the city opened for purely practical reasons.''
   Sevastopol is one of a number of Soviet cities that remain
off-limits for most Soviet citizens as well as foreigners.
Sometimes the Kremlin's rationale for closing them is unclear, but
in this case, it's obvious: Sevastopol is the home port for the
Soviet navy's Black Sea fleet.
   On Friday, the Americans sailed into Sevastopol to a hero's
welcome, but ordinary Soviets must pass through checkpoints if they
enter by car or have their documents scanned by patrols if they
come by bus or train.
   Officially, only close relatives of residents are allowed in to
visit, and then only for limited periods.
   Residents say the restrictions limit the flow of tourists that
might flood the southern Crimean city of nearly 400,000 people,
and, like vacationers in Yalta and other coastal cities, sweep up
what remains on store shelves.
   Meat, butter and sugar already are rationed in Sevastopol, but
by Soviet standards, things could be much worse. Koshkin said he
was recently in Vladivostok, a strategic port in the Soviet Far
East that was recently opened up, ``and in terms of produce,
there's nothing there _ nothing.''
   As President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reforms change the way
Soviet farmers and industries do business, the country is suffering
from worsening shortages of food and such basic items as
toothpaste, soap, detergent and medicine. Official statistics say
meat is now rationed in 24 regions of the Russian republic alone,
soap in 30 regions and sugar virtually everywhere.
   Stores in Sevastopol are relatively well-stocked, with shorter
lines than in Moscow, where an estimated 1 million out-of-towners
come daily to shop, swelling store queues and bringing grumbles
from natives.
   Other closed Soviet cities are also reluctant to take down their
walls despite the Kremlin's policy of greater openness, according
to a report Wednesday in the newspaper Socialist Industry.
   In an unidentified space-industry city in Siberia, retirees
offered to pay themselves for patrols to guard the city rather than
allow it to be opened, it said.
   ``It's not hard to understand people,'' the newspaper said.
``It's the psychological comfort that has accumulated over the
years, the stability, the extra defense that's guaranteed by that
high fence.''
   In Sevastopol, residents say that despite existing restrictions,
the summer sunshine brings a surge of tourists who come to enjoy
the hilly city's fresh air, classical architecture, roses and
seaside promenades. They also explore the city's history _ its
record of invaders ranging from the ancient Scythians to the
Germans, and its prolonged sieges during the Crimean War in the
mid-1850s and World War II.
   ``In the winter, you can buy milk freely, but in the summer,
it's all snatched up in the morning,'' said former navy Lt. Valery
Karyakin, who had been based in Sevastopol during his tour of duty
and was preparing to leave.
   Still, Karyakin said, he would have preferred the city be opened
so he could freely invite friends to visit.
   One Sevastopol woman said her parents, who lived two hours away
in Simferopol, were allowed to visit for only one month in summer.
``If they want to visit for even one day in December, they can't,''
she said.
   The restrictions, already somewhat archaic in the face of
modern-day satellite photography, seemed even more pointless after
Western correspondents were given a free rein to wander about and
take pictures during the five-day visit of the U.S. warships. The
cruiser USS Thomas S. Gates and the frigate USS Kauffman left
Sevastopol on Tuesday.
   A picturesque promenade built along the edge of downtown
Sevastopol looks down on inlets where dozens of Soviet submarines,
warships and research vessels are at rest or under repair.
   As two Western photographers focused their long-range lenses on
the display of naval hardware, Soviet passers-by stared
suspiciously and clucked in disapproval, but did not move to stop
them.
   A policeman who checked the journalists' documents let them go
with the mild reprimand that ``it is not desirable to photograph
here.''
</TEXT>
