<FIRST>r a AM-Prison-Hostages     08-10 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Prison-Hostages,0403</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inmate Slays Self After 9{-hour Standoff</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRIP DuBARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>McCORMICK, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A convicted murderer upset at prison
conditions held another inmate and a prison worker at gunpoint for
9{ hours Wednesday, but released them unharmed and killed himself,
officials said.
   Thomas Walden, 42, fatally shot himself in the neck at 10:26
p.m., about 30 minutes after talking by telephone with his brother,
state Department of Corrections Commissioner Parker Evatt said,
   Walden was armed with a .25-caliber automatic when he
overpowered a guard shortly before his schedule transfer from
McCormick Correctional Institution to another state prison,
Corrections spokesman Francis X. Archibald said.
   Prison officials could not account for how Walden acquired the
pistol, but said they would investigate how it got into the prison.
   Walden took the two hostages around 11:30 a.m. in the prison's
furniture-manufacturing building, Archibald said. He had asked for
his attorney, his prison file and to make a phone call to his wife,
the spokesman said.
   Walden released the inmate hostage at 4:25 p.m. and freed the
prison worker shortly before 9 p.m. after negotiators agreed to let
him telephone members of his family, Archibald said.
   After talking with his brother, Evatt said Walden continued to
speak by telephone with corrections officials, but then walked to
the other end of the and shot himself.
   Although Walden was upset at his impending transfer to Perry
Correctional Institution near Pelzer, Evatt said he never asked to
remain in McCormick and appeared to accept the move later in the
evening.
   Department officials said Walden and another inmate were
reportedly at odds and that in the routine procedure to separate
such prisoners, Walden happened to be the inmate that had to be
moved.
   Archibald said Walden was particularly incensed that he was to
be transferred to what would have been his fourth prison since
November 1984, when he began serving a sentence of life and 24
years for murder and armed robbery.
   Prison officials locked the other prisoners in their cells while
officials negotiated with Walden.
   McCormick, near the Georgia state line about 70 miles west of
Columbia, is a medium- to maximum-security prison that was built as
an 808-bed prison, but has been allowed by the courts to
double-cell some inmates and is at its maximum capacity of 1,100,
Archibald said.
</TEXT>
