<DOCNO> AP890810-0009 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 0154EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ButchyDoe     08-10 0760</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Butchy Doe,0781</SECOND>
<HEAD>In This Neighborhood, Everybody Says They Know Who Shot Butchy Doe</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONNI EFRON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They shot Butchy Doe again, and nobody is
surprised.
   He's a convicted bank robber who just got out of jail on a
firearms charge and is a suspect in at least three slayings. Police
say they think this is the fourth attempt to kill him _ and there
may be more they don't know about.
   In May, Arthur L. ``Butchy'' Doe Jr., 30, took three bullets
when armed men stormed his girlfriend's apartment in Charlestown.
She died.
   Somebody called the hospital where Doe was recovering. ``Don't
bother stitching him up because when he gets out we're gonna shoot
him again,'' the man said.
   On Tuesday, Doe was ambushed leaving a deli and carrying a
sandwich and a can of soda. He took a bullet in the chest, but is
expected to live _ for a while.
   On Wednesday, the Boston detective who oversees Charlestown said
police already have everything they need on who is trying to kill
Butchy Doe. Except a witness who will testify.
   ``We know who did it. We know who dunnit last time,'' said Lt.
Detective Edward J. McNelley. ``You gonna come forward and say it's
him? The problem is what we know and what we can prove. The whole
town knows who did it.''
   The people behind the counter at Collier's Meat Deli, where at
least three shots were fired, said they had never heard of Butchy
Doe.
   But a group of 13- and 14-year-old boys hanging around the stoop
next door were happy to point out the spot where Doe dropped his
sandwich on the sidewalk and clutched the center of his chest. The
boys and four other neighbors, all speaking on condition of
anonymity, said they knew who did it.
   Asked why nobody would help the police, one 14-year-old boy
replied, ``If they don't want to look like Butchy Doe, they don't
tell.''
   Busing battles, soaring real estate prices and even
gentrification have done nothing to weaken the old code of loyalty
in Charlestown, a tough Irish neighborhood surrounding Bunker Hill
that McNelley described as ``probably the bank robbery capital of
the world.''
   For years the tight hilly streets have sheltered 50 to 70
professional bank robbers, many of whom were never caught, McNelley
said.
   In the early 1960s, two groups of stickup men got into a fight
over a woman. The story has it that one man spit in the face of
another's girlfriend. McNelley said the resulting gang war lasted
several years and killed at least 56 people.
   ``With these guys, getting shot is just a way of life,''
McNelley said.
   McNelley said he didn't know the trigger for the latest round of
shooting and retaliation, but cocaine, heroin and angel dust are
believed to be a factor.
   Neighbors, speaking on condition of anonymity, offered a number
of other explanations.
   One theory has it that both attacks on Doe are the fallout from
the armed robbery of $254,000 from a bank inside Massachusetts
General Hospital in early May. The person who wouldn't allow
himself to be identified and who claimed to be a relative of Doe,
said the hard feelings began when Doe drove away in the getaway car
and later refused to share the money. The robbery has not been
solved and Doe was never charged.
   Another story has it that 10 years ago Doe was blamed for a
murder. ``Rather than going to the police, they took the law into
their own hands. They beat him up, real bad, yeah. He's always had
kind of a resentment about that.''
   A taxi driver described Doe as homely man with dirty blond hair
and deep-set eyes who favors high-top sneakers, football shirts and
always wears a cap. He's been seen often near a housing project
carrying a bag that some believe contains a gun.
   ``He's a very vicious person,'' the driver said. ``He's been in
so much trouble over the years. The cops don't really care if he
gets killed. In fact, the cops probably would like to see him
killed.''
   A boy who identified himself as Doe's nephew, 13-year-old Richie
Doe, said his uncle told family members he expected to be out of
the hospital within two weeks.
   Neighbors unanimously predicted the vendetta will be settled
soon after _ in the old Charlestown way.
   ``They're going to get him till he dies _ if he don't get them
first,'' said one.
</TEXT>
