<FIRST>r a AM-Steelers-Symphony 1stLd-Writethru a0799 08-10 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Steelers-Symphony, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0799,0244</SECOND>
<HEAD>Steelers Coach Conducts Symphony</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 7-8, `At the ..., to CORRECT spelling of Delfs; a
longer version is moving on some sports circuits.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LATROBE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pittsburgh Steelers Coach Chuck Noll led a
new team on the practice field Wednesday night, but this time he
was the nervous rookie as conductor of the Pittsburgh Symphony
Orchestra.
   Noll conducted the 101-member orchestra in John Philip Sousa's
``The Stars and Stripes Forever.''
   The orchestra played before about 5,000 people at the Steelers'
summer camp at St. Vincent College as a tribute to Steelers founder
Arthur J. Rooney Sr., who died Aug. 25, 1988, at age 87.
   Noll, 57, who won four Super Bowls in the 1970s, quickly relaxed
as he led the orchestra to the rousing march, delicately handling
his baton, making faces at the violinists and occasionally
imitating the trombonists.
   Noll, who wore his game attire _ a white Steelers's golf shirt
and black trousers _ said the experience was easier than coaching
his other team.
   ``That's what happens when you have a good team,'' he said.
``There was nothing to it. It was good fun.''
   At the intermission of the outdoor concert, Noll was seen
backstage taking lessons on waving the baton from the symphony's
conductor, Andreas Delfs.
   ``He did wonderfully,'' Delfs said after Noll's performance.
``He's very musical, perfect tempo. He's a real American, so he hit
the real tempo.''
</TEXT>
