<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 0235EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Test-TubeBabies Bjt   08-10 0665</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Test-Tube Babies, Bjt,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Test-Tube Babies Found to Develop Normally, Study Finds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Babies conceived in laboratories with the
high-tech help of fertility experts are just as likely to be normal
as babies made by amateurs in the traditional way, researchers say.
   The study was conducted to determine if infants conceived by in
vitro fertilization _ the so-called test-tube babies _ are more apt
to develop physical or mental abnormalities than other children,
said Dr. James L. Mills, a National Institute of Child Health and
Human Development researcher.
   ``The original question was, `are these children going to be
developmentally delayed?' The answer to that is very clearly not,''
Mills said Wednesday in a telephone interview. ``They did extremely
well.''
   In a study published this month in the Journal of Pediatrics,
Mills and a team of scientists from Eastern Virginia Medical School
compared the development of 83 children born as a result of in
vitro fertilization, or IVF, with 93 children born from normal
conception. The children were matched by age, sex, race, age of the
mother and other factors. They were all between 12 months and 30
months old.
   All of the IVF children were conceived at the Eastern Virginia
Medical School in Norfolk, Va., and the infants in the other group
were randomly selected from among children born within 100 miles of
Norfolk.
   Mills said the children in both groups were subjected to ``an
extremely complete job of looking for malformations,'' or birth
defects. The tests included a variety of imaging techniques, such
as ultrasound, that could detect physical abnormalities of internal
organs.
   The children also were assessed individually using tests that
measure mental development of the very young.
   No statistically important difference was found between the
groups.
   Two of the IVF children had major malformations, compared to one
such case among the non-IVF infants, Mills said, but the difference
is not considered significant.
   He said that since the number of children examined for the study
was small, there remains some statistical question about the minor
differences in the frequency of malformations. But Mills added that
``when you take our paper, along with other data, such as (IVF)
records from Australia, it's very reassuring.''
   In tests of mental development, the IVF children did slightly
better than the other group.
   ``We feel very comfortable about the intellectual development
... because they did very, very well,'' said Mills. He said that
even though there was a careful effort to match the two groups of
children on a basis of parental income and educational level, ``the
IVF children still did better.''
   This finding may reflect the fact that the parents of the IVF
children ``went to a tremendous amount of trouble to have these
children and they were going to make sure that these children got
the best in terms of stimulation and care.''
   Though children conceived by the IVF procedure popularly are
called ``test tube babies,'' conception actually takes place in a
laboratory petri dish, not a test tube.
   The dish is filled with chemicals designed to mimic the
environment of the maternal reproductive system. Sperm from the
father and eggs recovered surgically from the mother are united in
the dish and allowed to form embryos. Selected embryos then are
implanted into the mother's uterus and development can then proceed
to a normal birth.
   ``No one knows exactly what the effect (might be) of starting
the embryonic period in media (chemicals) instead of in the uterus.
There's no way they can make that exactly like the normal
situation,'' said Mills. ``There was that basis for wondering if
these kids would turn out all right.''
   IVF techniques were first successful in England, but the
procedure is now common in the United States, Australia and other
countries. Mills said thousands of children worldwide have been
born through the IVF procedure.
   The Eastern Virginia Medical School team that conducted the
study with Mills was led by Dr. Norma C. Morin.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890810-0015 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 0239EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Bloch Bjt   08-10 0693</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bloch, Bjt,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>World's Best-Known Spy Suspect Leads Media on a Merry Chase</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People in Felix Bloch's position often put a
coat over their heads or run the other way whenever a news camera
is pointed at them. But Bloch, the most visible spy suspect ever,
uses a different approach.
   He makes himself available to every lens and microphone.
   ``I've developed a real symbiotic relationship with the media,''
said Bloch, who has _ not by choice _ been leading a caravan of FBI
and news people since it was revealed he is suspected of spying for
the Soviet Union.
   Bloch's walks around Washington are attracting attention the way
Harry Truman's used to. Bloch made a trip to the cleaners Wednesday
and it was recorded by cameras. He went for a 22-mile hike Tuesday
and caused a coterie of Bloch watchers to go huffing and puffing
along.
   Wednesday was an easier day. Bloch sat on a park bench for two
hours enjoying the cool, bright day as much as anyone can with
microphones brushing his lips.
   He reached down to pet his poodle, Mephisto, and a dozen cameras
whirred. He stretched back, hands behind his head, and microphones
stretched out, too. People stared, but Bloch paid them no mind.
   ``It's lovely,'' Bloch said. ``I assure you that were it 95
degrees and 70 percent relative humidity, I would not be out here.''
   But: ``I won't say anything about the allegations.''
   Will there come a time when he will?
   ``Possibly.''
   It's that possibility and the summer doldrums that causes TV
networks and other news organization to continue the expensive
stakeouts.
   The circus atmosphere around Bloch attracted a persistent
heckler and he finally said, ``I'm not saying another word as long
as you are here.'' The FBI agents who were keeping an eye on this
year's best-known spy suspect finally felt compelled to tell the
man to back off.
   The government has brought no charges, and Bloch is free to do
what and when he pleases.
   ``I'm amazed that people have nothing better to do,'' he said to
a reporter who was doing what his editors expected him to do.
   Bloch, a high-ranking diplomat at the U.S. Embassy in Vienna for
much of the decade, is on leave from the diplomatic service while
the government investigates his conduct.
   His new bond with news people was cemented Tuesday when he hiked
into the Maryland countryside, trailed by his entourage.
   ``I normally don't take walks like that, but I had the time and
the weather was propitious,'' Bloch said. ``I had the inclination.
It was time to prove to myself perhaps that I could outlast the
media and the FBI.
   ``But they cheated. They rode part of the way. They rented
bikes, they brung in other teams. They may even have been in a
helicopter overhead.''
   Ultimately, he said: ``I was disappointed because I had to break
down and accept a ride from CBS News. I had a funny question on the
way home. They were in communication with their offices by radio
and said, `Can we take you in to the bureau.' I said, `What, the
FBI?'''
   He didn't go to CBS. The news crew, he said, ``were men and
women of their word. They dropped me off at my home.''
   What did his walk accomplish?
   ``I never asked myself that question, whether it accomplishes
anything or not,'' said Bloch. ``If I have time on my hands, I like
to mix it up. I read, I cook, I clean the house, I write, I work on
this or that and I want to get my fresh air.''
   Does he have any idea when there will be any kind of resolution
of his case.
   ``You are going to have to speak with people other than myself.''
   Was he being kept twisting in the wind, to use John Ehrlichman's
famous phrase?
   ``Well, I think I'm sitting pretty firmly on the bench,'' he
said. ``Now, unless the Fourth Estate will buy me lunch, I'm going
home.''
   The offer was made, but Bloch declined and took Mephisto home.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
