<FIRST>r w PM-GovernmentCharity     08-10 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Government Charity,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Gives 389 Groups a Shot at Federal Charity Dollars</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government is giving 389 groups, including
a homosexual rights organization, the chance to benefit from
federal payroll deductions that raise about $160 million a year for
charity.
   ``Frankly, it is a thrilling prospect for us,'' Thomas Stoddard,
executive director of the Lambda Legal Defense and Education Fund,
said Wednesday. ``Being listed helps fulfill our mission.''
   The fund, established in 1972 to defend homosexuals and
homosexual rights in court, was one of 19 groups that received
last-minute approval for inclusion. It is the first overtly
homosexual organization to be included in the government list.
   ``I assume, frankly, that there was simply a desire to keep
Lambda out of the circle by virtue of its mission,'' Stoddard said
about the earlier rejection.
   The drive, the Combined Federal Campaign, is the nation's
largest single fundraising campaign.
   Getting listed can bring large amounts to an organization at
virtually no cost. But it also can bring nothing if federal
employees don't specifically designate the charity.
   Workers are allowed to choose up to five charities from a list
that, including local charities, may number more than 1,000.
   Other participants in this year's drive are anti-abortion and
pro-abortion rights groups; Ralph Nader's Center for Auto Safety;
Phyllis Schlafly's Eagle Forum Educational &amp; Legal Defense Fund;
the liberal People for the American Way and the American Civil
Liberties Union Foundation.
   Among those rejected were the Red River Valley Fighter Pilots
Association, Trout Unlimited and Cultural Survival Inc.
   Former President Reagan issued a 1983 executive order
restricting the federal drive to traditional health and welfare
charities. After protests and lawsuits by advocacy groups, Congress
enacted legislation in 1986 broadening the grounds for admission
but left discretion in the hands of the director of the Office of
Personnel Management.
   OPM Director Constance Newman reviewed rejected applications and
reversed the decision on Lambda and 18 others, OPM said Wednesday
in announcing the list.
   She gave qualified approval to eight more, left six pending and
denied approval to 55 _ of which 33 had not complied with requests
for additional information.
   Approval went to a range of causes, some potentially
controversial.
   Among them were the Firearms Civil Rights Legal Defense Fund,
the United Palestinian Appeal, Human Life International, the
National Association of Black Law Enforcement Executives, United
States Military Sports Association, the Living Bank and Operation
California.
   The National Right to Life Educational Trust Fund, the Religious
Coalition for Abortion Rights Education Fund and Planned
Parenthood-World Population already were listed. So was the
National Right to Work Legal Defense Foundation Inc., a
conservative group.
   The fund drive raises about $160 million annually from 4 million
federal employees, including military people and postal workers,
with the average giving $60.68.
   It is the largest employee solicitation in the country, OPM
said, although it collects just a fraction of what Americans
individually give to church or charity _ $87 billion in 1988,
according to the American Association of Fund-Raising Counsel.
   About 80 percent of the gifts are designated. Of the rest, 82
percent goes to local United Way campaigns, 7 percent to a group of
33 international service agencies, 7 percent to national health
agencies and 4 percent to local groups, according to OPM.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
