<FIRST>r i PM-HongKong-Citicorp     08-10 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hong Kong-Citicorp,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Citicorp Announces Involvement in Real Estate Deal</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: A version of this appeared on financial wires</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Citicorp has agreed on a preliminary basis to
buy and lease about 20 floors of a new office tower in Hong Kong in
a move described by a bank official as a vote of confidence in the
territory's future.
   New York-based Citicorp also will arrange $667 million in loans
to help finance construction of the twin-tower complex, project
leader Great Eagle Co. announced Wednesday.
   The British colony reverts to Chinese sovereignty in 1997. The
military suppression of pro-democracy demonstrators in Beijing in
early June and the subsequent crackdown on dissent in China has
damaged confidence in the territory's future.
   Securities analysts praised the news, saying that providing
space to Citicorp would help set a base for rents in the downtown
building and lock in a well-known anchor tenant to help fill the
complex.
   Citicorp also would benefit by acquiring a significantly higher
profile in Hong Kong. Its local headquarters now is far from
downtown.
   Preliminary work on the construction site has begun and the
complex is expected to be completed in less than four years.
   Steven Baker, Citicorp's division executive for East Asia, said
the bank had been looking for a downtown location for three years.
The bank plans to take about 400,000 square feet, or one-quarter,
of the new complex.
   ``Our commitment to finance this enormous office complex and our
serious negotiations to both anchor the space and invest as an
equity participant reflect our confidence in Hong Kong and our
determination to play an increasingly important role in the
community,'' he said.
</TEXT>
