<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 0336EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Powell-Profile     08-10 0627</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Powell-Profile,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gen. Colin L. Powell `Never Gets Rattled,' Associates Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Colin L. Powell, in line to become the
first black chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, is a man of
exceptional judgment who ``never gets rattled,'' associates say.
   Bush administration sources said the president was expected to
nominate Powell today to become the nation's top military officer.
The position would require Senate confirmation.
   Powell, 52, the former White House national security adviser, is
credited with helping restructure the National Security Council
following the Iran-Contra scandal. He now heads the U.S. Army
Forces Command at Fort MacPherson Ga., which is charged with
keeping U.S. troops ready for combat.
   The son of Jamaican immigrants, Powell is the fourth black to
achieve the rank of four-star general.
   ``He is a person of exceptional judgment and intellect,'' said
Charles Duncan, deputy defense secretary under President Carter,
said in November 1987 when Powell was named to succeed Frank
Carlucci as national security adviser.
   Gen. P.X. Kelley, who worked with Powell in the Pentagon before
retiring as Commandant of the Marine Corps, once described him as
``a very extraordinary guy.''
   ``He can handle stress extremely well. He never gets rattled. He
was always a cool head,'' Kelley said.
   And Carlucci has said, ``I think he should go to the very top of
the military establishment _ up to and including chairman of the
Joint Chiefs of Staff.''
   A tall, husky man, Powell collects and repairs old Volvos in his
spare time. He also visits groups of young blacks to tell them of
their duty to help others and to protect the gains of the civil
rights movement.
   ``Don't squander the blood, sweat and tears of those who paved
the way for you,'' he told Clark Atlanta University graduates this
spring. ``The greatest danger ... is complacency.''
   He speaks without bitterness of the occasional racial harassment
he suffered during the mid-1960s as a young officer at Fort
Benning, Ga., friends say. He distinguished himself as the best
infantry instructor at Benning, and in Vietnam won a Bronze Star
and a Purple Heart. He also has received the Distinguished Service
Medal and the Legion of Merit.
   The watershed in his career may have been a White House
fellowship he won in 1972. He was assigned to the Office of
Management and Budget where he worked for Caspar Weinberger and
Carlucci.
   Later, as military assistant to Defense Secretary Weinberger,
Powell was intimately involved in the 1983 Grenada invasion and the
Libyan bombing of 1986.
   Powell then commanded a corps in Germany and refused several
requests to become Carlucci's deputy national security adviser. He
finally gave in to a personal appeal by President Reagan and
explained in January 1987, ``I'm a serviceman, a soldier, and it
looked like my service might be of greater use here.''
   Powell came under scrutiny in the Iran-Contra affair because he
was one of the few people who knew about the secret sale of arms to
Iran. However, it did not hurt his reputation and he was never
accused of wrongdoing.
   A congressional source, who spoke in 1987 on condition of
anonymity, said Powell opposed the arms sales, ``but when the
decision was made by the president (Reagan), he executed it.''
   In a speech last November, Powell was cautious about prospects
for change in the Soviet Union, arguing against a ``help
Gorbachev'' policy at a conference organized by the American Stock
Exchange.
   ``Will perestroika ... lead to a kinder, gentler Soviet Union?''
he said. ``...We cannot forget that our overall relationship
continues to be both competitive and adversarial. This is unlikely
to change within our lifetimes.''
   Powell met his wife, Alma, on a blind date in 1962, and they
have two daughters and a son.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890810-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 0342EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-PeaceInstitute Bjt   08-10 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Peace Institute, Bjt,0664</SECOND>
<HEAD>WWII Conscientious Objector Leads Plan For Peace Institute</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANICA KIRKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREENSBORO, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Peter Watson resisted war when it was
neither chic nor acceptable. He thought World War II was a terrible
mistake and became a conscientious objector.
   Now, he's attacking war by financing peace.
   The 64-year-old real estate investor has pledged $1 million to
the University of Rochester in New York to establish a center to
study peace.
   ``We have three good academies teaching people how to wage
war,'' Watson said, referring to West Point, Annapolis and the Air
Force Academy. ``We need to have institutions of higher learning
teaching people how to wage peace.''
   America was already at war when Watson entered Harvard
University as a freshman. He saw many of his classmates and his two
brothers go off to fight, but he simply believed war was
meaningless and wrong.
   So, after being drafted in 1942, he opted for alternative
service. He eventually volunteered for the ``guinea pig unit,'' a
group of conscientious objectors who were used to test the body's
tolerance to high altitude, extreme temperature and different
proteins.
   One of his duties was to test the limits of his body under
desertlike conditions. He rode a stationary bicycle in a room
heated to a sweltering 120 to 130 degrees for eight hours without
water. The salt water solution he was given at the end of the day
was ``delicious.''
   Watson said his guinea pig years were fulfilling, so he thinks
it only fitting to give the money to the Rochester, N.Y.,
university _ the site of the experiments.
   Dr. Carl Honig, a researcher at the University of Rochester,
said the work in respiratory study saved the lives of soldiers
stationed in the Aleutian Islands and North Africa, and thousands
of others since then.
   ``Those studies have prolonged the life and added to comfort of
patients with any type of respiratory disease, whether it's
emphysema, or asthma or lung cancer,'' Honig said.
   No one died during any of the Rochester experiments, but at
least two men perished during ``guinea pig'' exercises elsewhere,
Watson said.
   ``It's important for every generation to have some (people),
however visionary and impractical at the time, stand for something,
stand for the abolition of war,'' Honig said. ``Those people did it
at great risk.''
   Watson got a medical discharge after developing ulcers during
nutritional experiments aimed at trying to avert starvation
following the war. He went back to Harvard's medical school for two
years before dropping out to volunteer for more research, and to
conduct research himself.
   In 1962, seeing an opportunity, he moved to Vermont and invested
in real estate when land could be had for $1 an acre.
   But after suffering a stroke in 1979, Watson found himself with
time on his hands. He sought information on the results of his
unit's wartime research and eventually talked to Honig about a
center that could unite various academic disciplines _ including
history, philosophy and political science _ in the study of peace.
   ``Peace is breaking out all over the world,'' he said. ``Let's
nudge it along a little bit.''
   Rochester officials proposed the Peter D. Watson Center for The
Study of International Peace and Cooperation and agreed to raise $5
million for it.
   Watson seems more the successful capitalist than the long-haired
peacenik. A prominent stained-glass window with an American eagle
motif hangs beside the balcony of his home overlooking Greensboro's
Caspian Lake, and he keeps rifles that have been in a family that
has gone to war since the American Revolution.
   But Watson said the window is not there to show patriotism. He
just liked the design. And the weapons, well, they seem to serve as
reminders of a history that need not be repeated.
   ``Peace has to be made reputable and war disreputable,'' Watson
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890810-0027 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 0242EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Soviet-LostAmericans     08-10 0736</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Lost Americans,0756</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Passport Not Necessarily The Ticket Out of Soviet Union</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the dozen or so people who have dual
U.S.-Soviet citizenship, their American passports have not
necessarily been a ticket out of the Soviet Union.
   Yuri Semenenko, for example, took a five-year detour through
Soviet prison camps.
   In the era of glasnost, the U.S. Embassy in Moscow is besieged
by tens of thousands of Soviets who want to become Americans. In
their midst is a much smaller group _ 12 or so _ who can claim to
be dual citizens.
   Semenenko, the son of a Soviet military officer on assignment
during World War II, is an American citizen by virtue of his birth
in Wilcox Memorial Hospital in Portland, Ore., on Feb. 10, 1945.
   All he wants to do is go back to Portland with his wife Elena, a
young dancer who is to due to give birth to their first child in
mid-September.
   ``I'd like it very much if my child was born in Portland, but I
see that it won't happen,'' said the Leningrad resident, a tanned,
tennis fanatic who also was a ranking Soviet motocross racer as a
teena-ger.
   ``It's simply a fact of life that he's here,'' said an embassy
official familiar with Semenenko's case. ``You can't claim U.S.
constitutional protection when you're in a foreign country.''
   Other dual citizens also were born in the United States and
emigrated with their parents to Czechoslovakia, Poland or the
Baltic republics during the Depression, said the officials, who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The areas they lived in were absorbed by the Soviet Union after
World War II, and during the Cold War they hid their American
birthright. A handful of dual citizens, mostly in their 60's and
70's, came forward only recently.
   Semenenko's saga was different. His father, Capt. 3rd Rank
Mikhail Semenenko, was in the United States in 1943 to inspect a
ship being sent to the Soviet Union under a lend-lease program. His
wife, Tatyana, went with him.
   Near the end of their tour, Yuri was born. Several months later,
the family got on a boat for the Soviet Far East.
   All the family brought back was perhaps 100 postcards of
Portland, New York, Washington, D.C., Chicago, and other cities, as
well as a few other souvenirs. Little remains.
   ``When I was a boy, I liked giving them to my friends,'
Semenenko said ruefully. ``I sold some of them, too. We were poor
when I was growing up.''
   But under U.S. law, since his parents did not have diplomatic
status in the United States, Semenenko was entitled to American
citizenship. It took until 1980, when Jewish emigration to the
United States had peaked, for him to figure that out.
   When he approached the U.S. Consulate in Leningrad, Soviet
guards arrested him at the entrance. He was convicted of bribery
and hooliganism, charges Semenenko said police concocted to punish
him for seeking his U.S. passport.
   Semenenko was sentenced to 6{ years in a prison camp above the
Arctic Circle, where he said inside temperatures rarely exceeded 50
degrees.
   Five years later, in spring 1988, Semenenko was released. In a
period of reform, he again applied for his U.S. passport and
received it last March.
   But officials told him that to leave he had to send a letter to
the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet renouncing his Soviet
citizenship. He did that in April and is awaiting a reply.
   U.S. officials say they bring up cases like Semenenko's every
time they meet with representatives of the Soviet Foreign
Ministry's office of humanitarian affairs. But visa offices are
under another ministry, and it's slow going through the bureacracy.
   The Soviets have promised such cases will be resolved
immediately under new regulations that have been expected for
months but still have not been implemented.
   Meanwhile, Semenenko contemplates life in the United States.
   ``People ask me what what I'll do over there. I tell them I'll
wash dishes,'' said Semenenko, who can sprinkle his Russian
conversation with English. ``I know that if I go to America I'll
live worse than I do now. I won't have my own house, and I'll have
to work several times harder.''
   But he said he does not have confidence in the Soviet reforms
and will never feel comfortable living in the Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
