<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     08-10 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALTON, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Tennessee woman caught speeding on
Interstate 75 got even with the Whitfield County police department.
She paid her $55 fine by mailing in 5,500 pennies.
   Jeanette Lord even enclosed a little note with her payment.
   ``Enclosed you will find $55 for my traffic citation. I had to
rob my piggy bank, but it is all there. I have learned my lesson
and will obey all traffic laws. Have a nice day,'' she wrote, along
with a drawing of a smiling face.
   Herman Hansird, Whitfield County probate judge, said he had
received payment in coins before, but this was the first time they
had been mailed.
   ``She's a very pleasant lady to talk with, but she was a little
upset about the fine,'' he said.
   Hansird said a bank will count the pennies, and if they don't
total $55 he will make up the difference. ``I'm sure not going to
call her back and tell her she shortchanged me,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The organizer of what is being billed
as the largest rubber duck race ever is miffed that Rhode Island
won't allow the ducks in its waters.
   Great American Duck Races predicts up to 50,000 people will turn
out to watch 70,000 rubber ducks race down a Salt River Project
Canal in Scottsdale Nov. 4.
   The Phoenix-based group has organized ``ducks for bucks'' races
in more than 40 states since May 1988, with nary a quack of
protest, says Eric Schechter, the organization's president. The
average race raises about $100,000 for charities, with companies
and individuals paying to sponsor ducks, he said. But the ducks
won't be racing down any Rhode Island rivers anytime soon.
   The state's Department of Environmental Management has banned
the races, claiming they violate the federal Clean Water Act and in
Rhode Island's Freshwater Wetlands laws.
   ``There is no way in the world you can collect all these little
pieces of plastic, no matter how well organized you are,'' said
Stephanie Powell, a department spokeswoman. Officials also say the
races attract large crowds that trample the riverbanks.
   Schechter dismisses the concerns, though. The buoyant rubber
ducks are checked for toxicity before being used in races or sold
as souvenirs, and people in kayaks scoop up all the ducks when the
contests are over, he says.
   ``We take this seriously because we are concerned about the
environment also,'' Schechter said. ``Rhode Island is the only
state we've had trouble organizing races in.''
</TEXT>
