<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     08-10 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington In Brief,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panel Focuses on Health Care Financing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Social Security advisory panel has targeted
the financing of a health care system as its first mission.
   Deborah Steelman, head of the Advisory Council on Social
Security, said the current health care system ``overlaps,
duplicates, omits, confuses'' and leaves many needy people without
adequate care. She said the panel must ``develop recommendations
for a sound, sustainable health care financing system'' to face new
strains with the aging of the Baby Boom generation.
   Ms. Steelman said the current Medicare system ``is projected to
be insolvent by early in the next century, before the Baby Boom has
even begun to enter retirement.''
   The 13-member advisory council holds its opening meeting on
Thursday and Friday. Such a panel is appointed every four years to
examine issues affecting the Social Security, Medicare and Medicaid
programs.
   Ms. Steelman said the council hopes to issue a draft report on
health care financing by July 1990 and recommendations on the
financing and role of Social Security benefits by December 1990. A
final report to Congress and the Department of Health and Human
Services is due in January 1991.
</TEXT>
