<NOTE>Judge Gives Commerce Until Friday To Answer New Petition</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Commerce Department has until Friday to
answer claims by the National Wildlife Federation that the
government is not protecting endangered sea turtles from extinction.
   The federation contends that the government's own studies show
restricted shrimp-fishing tow times are ineffective.
   An order Wednesday by a U.S. District Court judge also asks
Commerce to respond to the federation's request that the agency
enforce a law that requires shrimper to equip their nets with
devices that let sea turtles escape.
   Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher, under an order by federal
Judge Thomas Hogan to protect sea turtles, this week required
shrimpers to either use the turtle excluder devices, which they
loathe, or limit trawl times to 105 minutes.
   The same day those rules took effect, the wildlife federation
filed its petition with the court seeking access to government
documents that it claims indicate tow times jeopardize the
endangered sea turtle.
