<HEAD>Dollar Up, Nikkei Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar edged upward against the yen Thursday,
while stock prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange fell.
   The dollar, which opened at 138.70 yen, finished the afternoon
session at 139.05 yen. It moved between 138.55 and 139.25 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 99.79-point
gainer on Wednesday, lost 139.47 points or 0.40 percent, to close
at 34,719.80.
   Yasuo Miyakawa of Sumitomo Bank said there was hardly any
activity on the foreign exchange market.
   ``There was almost no market-affecting news,'' he said.
   On Wednesday, Toshiki Kaifu was voted in as the new prime
minister to replace Uno Sousuke, who resigned to take
responsibility for a huge electoral defeat in which Japan's ruling
Liberal Democratic Party lost the majority of the upper house of
parliament.
   But the foreign exchange market did not have any particular
reaction, Miyakawa said.
   Stock traders also had no reaction to the new administration.
   ``The Tokyo market did not judge the selection as either good or
bad,'' said a dealer with Okasan Securities who asked not to be
identified.
   Many traders are taking their summer vacations, he said, and
players are waiting for the announcement of the U.S. wholesale
price index Friday.
