<FIRST>r w PM-Leland-Vigil     08-10 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Leland-Vigil,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black Caucus Members Not Giving Up Hope Leland Will Be Found Alive</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Leland-Search, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmitting a0458 to CORRECT category code.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dawn was breaking in Ethiopia as dozens of
people gathered on the steps of the Capitol early today for a
midnight vigil to pray that Rep. Mickey Leland is found alive.
   ``Tonight we speak with a sense of hope, for it is midnight
here,'' said the Rev. Jesse Jackson. ``Beyond midnight there is
daylight. And we've been taught that weeping may endure for a
night, but hold on and hold out. Joy cometh in the morning.''
   The search for the chairman of the House Select Committee on
Hunger entered its third day. The plane carrying the Texas Democrat
and 13 others from Addis Ababa to a refugee camp near the Sudanese
border 480 miles away disappeared Monday.
   ``We have not had any sign of the plane,'' Jackson said. ``There
is not the bad news of the crash, thus there is a margin of hope.
   ``All we do now is hope against hope,'' Jackson said in a quiet
voice, the dome of Capitol behind him ivory against the cool night
sky.
   ``Tonight we cannot hear his voice and yet we can. Tonight we
cannot see his face and yet we can,'' Rep. Floyd Flake, D-N.Y.,
told the crowd, which held green florescent ``Lightsticks.''
   ``We pray thee thou would not let his voice go unheard nor let
his pleas go unheeded. Truly our hearts are heavy for this brother
of ours and they who have gone with him.''
   Among the 13 others aboard the turboprop Twin Otter aircraft
were three congressional staff members.
   President Bush said Wednesday that Ethiopia is ```going to get
all the cooperation we can give them'' in the search.
   State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler said Marxist
Ethiopia agreed to an overflight of the area by a U-2
photo-reconnaissance plane.
   An Air Force C-141 Starlifter medical evacuation plane was sent
from West Germany on Bush's authority carrying a 20-member medical
team and search and rescue, weather and communications personnel,
she said. The Defense Department also is dispatching several
aircraft.
   Wednesday night, Democratic Reps. Gary Ackerman of New York and
Al Wheat of Missouri left Washington for Ethiopia. House Speaker
Thomas S. Foley asked them to represent the House in the search for
Leland, said Howard Doyle, a spokesman for Ackerman.
   ``I believe at this moment to a moral certainty that everything
that can be done is being done,'' said Rep. Ronald V. Dellums,
D-Calif., chairman of the Congressional Black Caucus, which
sponsored the vigil.
   Dellums and other members of the caucus said they were
optimistic they would again see Leland, a member and former
chairman of the group.
   ``Mickey's a fighter, he's a survivor,'' said Rep. John Lewis,
D-Ga.
   Flake said he was not prepared to give up.
   ``I don't think anybody's giving up hope,'' he said.
</TEXT>
