<FIRST>r a PM-SpenceArrest     08-10 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spence Arrest,0443</SECOND>
<HEAD>Washington Sex-Scandal Target Arrested in New York City</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A once powerful lobbyist linked to a Washington
sex scandal was arrested for gun and drug possession after calling
police to say he'd been robbed in his hotel room by a man he met in
Times Square.
   Craig J. Spence, 48, was scheduled to appear at an Aug. 28
hearing on charges of criminal possession of a weapon and
misdemeanor possession of cocaine, said Gerald McKelvey, a
spokesman for the district attorney's office, on Wednesday.
   Spence, 48, was identified this summer by The Washington Times
as a major client of a homosexual escort service that is being
investigated by the Secret Service, District of Columbia police and
the U.S. Attorney's Office for possible credit card fraud,
authorities said.
   He has admitted using such escort services but blamed his
accountant for allowing his credit card charges to be illegally
inflated.
   Spence was arrested July 31 after calling police to the Barbizon
Hotel, McKelvey said. He spent two days in jail before pleading
innocent and being released Aug. 2.
   He told police he met Casey Regan, 22, on 42nd Street and
brought him back to his hotel room, whereupon Regan took Spence's
pistol and robbed him of $6,000 in cash and travelers checks,
McKelvey said.
   Regan told officials Spence ``had given him the money and that
he was just holding the gun to see how it felt,'' McKelvey said.
   Regan was charged with robbery, criminal possession of a weapon
and criminal possession of a controlled substance, cocaine. He was
released in his own custody.
   The Washington Times and The Washington Post characterized Regan
as a male prostitute.
   Once a Vietnam correspondent for ABC News, Spence became a
high-profile lobbyist representing Japanese clients before his
business declined in recent years.
   The Washington Times said frequent party guests at his home
included former CIA Director William Casey, conservative activist
Phyllis Schlafly and James Lilley, ambassador to China and formerly
to Korea.
   ``I had the world at my house and now they don't know who I
am,'' Spence told the newspaper Monday in an interview.
   Besides the escort service disclosures, a White House guard
allegedly accepted a Rolex watch from Spence, gave him a piece of
presidential china and allowed Spence and some friends to take
midnight tours of White House public areas last year.
   Jane Vezeris, a spokeswoman for the Secret Service, said a
subpoena has been served for Spence to testify early next week
before a grand jury in Washington.
</TEXT>
