<SECOND>PM-Ohio Casino,0240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gambling Proposal Comes Up Short</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An auto dealer conceded defeat in an
attempt to put a casino gambling referendum before Ohio voters this
fall, but he promised to get the proposal on the ballot in 1990.
   Alan Spitzer, spokesman for a group of casino backers and a
potential casino owner, said the group failed to get the 306,661
signatures required by midnight Wednesday to put its initiative on
the Nov. 7 ballot. But he said he expected a new petition drive
aimed at next year's elections would succeed.
   The group began circulating petitions in June after the Ohio
Senate rejected a bill authorizing a casino in Lorain, despite
passage by the House.
   Its proposal would have permitted casinos in seven districts,
generally surrounding and including Ohio's biggest cities, subject
to approval by local voters.
   Spitzer said the plan would create jobs and boost tourism. He
has talked of building a $300 million to $400 million resort
complex and casino on an abandoned shipyard in Lorain, which he
said would breathe new life into the northern Ohio steel town.
   The LUV Ohio Committee _ LUV stands for let us vote _ fell about
40,000 signatures short of the number needed, backers said.
   Spitzer blamed a late start and a lack of people to circulate
petitions. ``Time and people _ we didn't have enough of either,''
he said.
