<FIRST>r a PM-WedtechAttorney     08-10 0188</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wedtech Attorney,0193</SECOND>
<HEAD>California State Bar To Move To Suspend Wallach</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The California State Bar said it will move
for the immediate suspension of lawyer E. Robert Wallach, who was
convicted of fraud and racketeering charges in the Wedtech case.
   ``We believe that there are elements of moral turpitude in Mr.
Wallach's conviction,'' James Bascue, chief trial counsel for the
bar's disciplinary division, said Wednesday.
   Moral turpitide covers such crimes as fraud, corruption and
perjury.
   Suspension would revoke Wallach's license pending the outcome of
his appeal. If his conviction is upheld, he could move be disbarred
permanently.
   Wallach, 55, of San Francisco, was convicted Tuesday of
illegally receiving $425,000 from Wedtech to influence his longtime
friend Edwin Meese III, then attorney general, and other government
officials in an attempt to win government contracts for the South
Bronx company.
   After a three-month trial, a federal jury in Manhattan rejected
Wallach's claim that he earned the money as legal and consulting
fees. He faces up to 45 years in prison and $250,000 in fines.
   Wallach was president of the San Francisco Bar Association in
1975.
</TEXT>
