<FIRST>r i PM-Israel-Hostages     08-10 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Hostages,0486</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shamir, Bush Agree to Coordinate on Hostage Issue</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Hostages, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir and President
Bush agreed to coordinate efforts to release foreign hostages and
Israeli prisoners held in Lebanon, a Shamir aide said today.
   The decision came in a 10-minute telephone call by Shamir to
Bush on Wednesday night. Avi Pazner, a top aide to Shamir,
described the talk as ``warm and friendly.''
   It was the first time the two leaders had talked since the
hostage crisis flared following Israel's kidnapping of Moslem
cleric Sheikh Abdel Karim Obeid from southern Lebanon on July 28,
Israeli reports said.
   A spokeswoman in Pazner's office said said Bush made no mention
of Obeid's abduction, which the United States has criticized, but
that the two leaders decided it was best to join forces on the
hostage-prisoner issue.
   Shamir assured Bush that Israel would include the eight American
hostages in any deal to trade Obeid and other Shiite prisoners in
Israel's hands for three Israeli soldiers held by the pro-Iranian
Hezbollah movement in Lebanon, Pazner said.
   The conversation came the same day a Shiite suicide attacker set
off a car bomb near the Israeli border in southern Lebanon,
wounding five Israeli soldiers and one Lebanese militiaman.
   Hezbollah, the shadowy pro-Iranian group, claimed responsiblity
for the assault.
   One of the wounded Israelis was in critical condition today, on
a respirator at Rambam Hospital in the northern port of Haifa. The
others were reported recovering.
   Israel's policy coordinator for southern Lebanon, Uri Lubrani,
warned Israel would retaliate for the attack.
   ``Israel will deal with the Hezbollah as it deals with all the
organizations which threaten the normal life of the security
zone,'' Lubrani said. He was referring to a strip north of Israel's
border patrolled by Israeli soldiers and its allies, the South
Lebanon Army militia.
   ``Violence has two edges and Israel will retaliate in one way or
another,'' Lubrani said. ``In due time, in a place it will choose.''
   Ron Ben-Ishai, a well-known commentator on defense issues, said
the government was caught in a dilemma over whether to stage a
reprisal at a time when there may be hope for hostage negotiations.
   ``The negotiations are at initial states and Israel will be
blamed by the United States for torpedoing them, or runs such a
risk,'' Ben-Ishai said on Israel radio.
   Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin's spokesman denied a report in
the Kuwaiti Al-Seyassah daily, which said Israel had abducted Obeid
to sabotage a PLO plan to win freedom for the American hostages
that was endorsed by the United States.
   Israel boycotts the Palestine Liberation Organization, which it
considers a terrorist group, and has repeatedly protested U.S.
contacts with the PLO.
   Rabin's spokesman, Eitan Haber, reached by telephone, said the
Kuwaiti report was ``nonsense.''
</TEXT>
