<SECOND>PM-Lynn Fire,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arson Blamed for Rooming House Fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN GALVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LYNN, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arson is suspected in a rooming house fire in
which at least three people were killed in this Boston suburb.
   Officials combed through the rubble of the burned-out Ben Crest
Plaza Wednesday in search of the bodies of two people who are
missing and also believed victims of the fire.
   ``It is the conclusion of the investigators that this incident
should be investigated with regard to a possible arson-homicide,''
said Essex County District Attorney Howard Whitehead.
   Whitehead said a Connecticut State Police dog trained to sniff
for gasoline, kerosene and other fire accelerants had been helpful
in gathering evidence, which was being analyzed at a laboratory.
   Joe McKenney, 24, who watched the blaze from his home in an
adjacent apartment building, claimed he saw a man in one of the Ben
Crest's rooms playing with matches and what he thought was rubbing
alcohol.
   ``Right in the middle of the floor ... he was fooling around
with alcohol,'' McKenney said. ``I saw him with it, playing with
matches.''
   But Bobby Barrett, 19, who was in the room McKenney was watching
about the time the blaze erupted, said no one was playing with fire.
   Fire Marshal Joseph O'Keefe said his investigators also were
trying to determine if the building's fire alarm was operating by
tracing its circuitry and if an antiquated ``substandard''
sprinkler system was functioning.
   Tenants wearing nightclothes jumped from windows Tuesday to
escape the flames and swung down on ropes provided by management as
fire escapes. More than 19 tenants and rescuers were injured.
</TEXT>
