<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     08-10 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Eases, Gold Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar eased in quiet European trading this
morning and currency dealers said they expected it to remain in a
narrow range for the rest of the week.
   Gold prices rose.
   ``There is a lack of ideas'' moving the market, said Alfred
Zapfel, chief trader at the Bank of Boston in Frankfurt.
   The European market is particularly quiet because many traders
are on vacation and others are letting the U.S. market take the
lead, he said.
   ``If anything will happen, it will happen in the U.S.,'' agreed
a trader in Italy.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 0.20 yen to a closing 139.05 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 139.10 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Wednesday:
   _1.8902 West German marks, down from 1.9000
   _1.6295 Swiss francs, down from 1.6350
   _6.3920 French francs, down from 6.4050
   _2.1328 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1440
   _1,360.75 Italian lire, down from 1,364.40
   _1.1735 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1710
   In London, it cost $1.6285 to buy one pound, more expensive for
buyers than $1.6170 late Wednesday.
   Gold opened in London at $365.75 a troy ounce, unchanged from
late Wednesday. At midmorning, the city's five major bullion
dealers fixed a recommended price of $366.40.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $366.30, up from $365 late
Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.18 to close at $367.06.
   Silver was quoted in London at $5.18 a troy ounce, up from
Wednesday's $5.15.
