<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 0734EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Politics     08-10 0642</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Politics,0663</SECOND>
<HEAD>Emperor Swears in Kaifu, New Cabinet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID THURBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor Akihito today held a swearing-in ceremony
for new Prime Minister Toshiki Kaifu and his Cabinet, a group Kaifu
said had been chosen to help ``ensure a balance of voices from the
people'' as he seeks reforms.
   ``There are both political reform and tax reform, and I plan to
do both reliably,'' he said.
   Kaifu, 58, and his scandal-plagued Liberal Democratic Party face
an opposition-dominated upper house of Parliament for the first
time in the party's 34 years of governing Japan.
   Also for the first time, the Cabinet includes two women _ Sumiko
Takahara, a non-politician and economics specialist who is head of
the Economic Planning Agency, and lawmaker Mayumi Moriyama,
director of the Environment Agency.
   Women have been particularly angered by a new 3 percent sales
tax that the Liberal Democrats forced through Parliament last year,
and were seen as a major factor in the party's upper house defeat
July 23.
   Kaifu replaces Sousuke Uno, who served only 69 days as prime
minister before resigning to take responsibility for the election
losses. He also had been accused of keeping paid mistresses.
   If the opposition parties can form a coalition on key issues
such as abolishing an unpopular new sales tax, the Liberal
Democrats could be forced into concessions or a possible
legislative stalemate, which could force early elections for the
lower house.
   The Liberal Democrats hope Kaifu's administration can brighten
their image before those elections, which must be held by next July
at the latest.
   The opposition parties used their greater powers on Wednesday by
making Socialist Party Chairwoman Takako Doi the upper house's
choice for prime minister.
   The lower house voted for Kaifu, the newly chosen leader of the
Liberal Democrats and, under the constitution, the lower house
decision prevails.
   After its induction in a ceremony at the Imperial Palace, the
new Cabinet held its first meeting today.
   Kaifu pledged Tuesday to reduce the influence of factions among
the Liberal Democrats, but other posts in the 20-member Cabinet
were carefully distributed among the main sub-groups within the
party.
   ``I want to let lots of fresh air in,'' Kaifu said of his
government after jogging in his neighborhood this morning.
   ``By listening to the voice of the people, I hope to reduce the
gap between the people and Nagatacho,'' he said, referring to the
government office area in Tokyo.
   ``For that reason I chose people from outside government. And to
ensure a balance of voices from the people, I highlighted the
appointment of women,'' Kaifu added.
   He said the Cabinet's motto would be ``dialogue and reform.''
   Kaifu was chosen to lead the party's rebuilding efforts because
of his relative youth and reform credentials. However, analysts say
enthusiasm within the party for reform has weakened now that the
Recruit influence-buying scandal is largely over.
   Kaifu has acknowledged receiving about $110,000 in political
donations from Recruit Co., but said they were legally reported.
Four other members of the new Cabinet and two new top party
officials also have said they received Recruit contributions.
   The company has been accused of giving political donations and
selling bargain-priced stock to leading politicians to obtain
favors.
   Kaifu must negotiate with opposition parties over a revision of
the sales tax that will acceptable to the public and he must decide
how to respond to continuing U.S. trade demands.
   Opposition from farmers, a traditional source of governing party
support, to more agricultural imports also was seen as factor in
the Liberal Democrats' loss in the upper house elections.
   Kaifu probably will visit the United States in early September
to meet with U.S. leaders, Kyodo News Service reported.
   It quoted unidentified Foreign Ministry officials as saying
Kaifu would assure President Bush that there will be no major
changes in Japanese foreign policy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
