<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 0829EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ArtForgery     08-10 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Art Forgery,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Artist Helped Break Up Nationwide Forgery Ring</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A master forger duped galleries with phony
Picassos, Dalis and Chagalls until one of the artists he copied
recognized a counterfeit, prosecutors say.
   District Attorney Ira Reiner on Wednesday credited artist Hiro
Yamagata with the break that led to the arrest of Anthony Tetro.
   ``The forger in this case is the single largest forger of
artwork in the United States,'' said Reiner, telling of a yearlong
undercover investigation that resulted in the seizure of 250
counterfeit paintings.
   Reiner spoke against a colorful backdrop of paintings that
mimicked those of Salvador Dali, Pablo Picasso, Marc Chagall and
Yamagata.
   Tetro, 39, of Claremont, was arrested last month and freed on
$10,000 bail on charges of conspiracy to commit grand theft and 44
counts of forgery.
   Charged along with him is Mark Henry Sawicki, 31, an art dealer
who ran a gallery in Sherman Oaks and allegedly distributed Tetro's
forgeries to galleries in Beverly Hills, New York, Chicago and Boca
Raton, Fla.
   Reiner said Tetro, who drove a Rolls Royce, sold forgeries for
$20,000 apiece.
   The alleged scheme crumbled last year when Yamagata, a
34-year-old Japanese-born artist who lives in Bel Air, stopped at a
gallery while taking relatives from Japan on a tour of Beverly
Hills, Yamagata said.
   ``I didn't paint that!'' Yamagata exclaimed when relatives
excitedly told him his paintings were on display.
   Yamagata, whose watercolors sell for $6,000 and up, went to
police. Investigators posed as art buyers and swept through
galleries across the country, placing deposits on artworks, then
returning to seize the frauds, Reiner said.
   Two of the phony paintings were recovered from Japan, Reiner
said, indicating the forgery network may have been international.
   No galleries were charged. Reiner said they apparently were
unaware that the paintings were forgeries.
   ``Even the most sophisticated and honest gallery can be duped,''
he said.
   Yamagata, who speaks halting English, said he has been painting
since he was 7 and has worked since then to develop his distinctive
style.
   Of the alleged forger, he said: ``I hope he finds his own
style.''
</TEXT>
