<FIRST>r i PM-UN-Hostages     08-10 0375</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UN-Hostages,0386</SECOND>
<HEAD>UN Envoy's Mission Found No Clues to Higgins' Fate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The secretary-general said he is ``almost
certain'' Marine Lt. Col. William R. Higgins is dead but that a
U.N. envoy sent to investigate Higgins' fate was unable to say when
or how he was killed.
   The envoy, Marrack Goulding, returned to New York on Wednesday
after a visit to Lebanon, Syria, and Israel, where he tried to
determine Higgins' fate and find his body.
   ``In spite of extensive conversations with various parties who
might be in a position to know the facts, Mr. Goulding could not
obtain definite proof of Col. Higgins' fate,'' the
secretary-general, Javier Perez de Cuellar, told reporters on
Wednesday.
   ``Having heard his report, however, I have regretfully come to
the conclusion that it is almost certain that Col. Higgins is dead.
I shall continue to try to establish with certainly what happened
to him, and if my fears are confirmed, to recover his body.''
   A pro-Iranian group in Lebanon said July 31 it had hanged
Higgins in retaliation for Israel's refusal to free Sheik Abdul
Karim Obeid, a Shiite Moslem clergyman kidnapped by Israeli
commandos July 28.
   Higgins' captors released a poor-quality videotape showing a man
who appeared to be Higgins hanging, but there was no way of telling
when he died. Some reports have said Higgins was killed last year.
   Higgins' wife, Robin, and the FBI say they believe Higgins is
dead. He was on U.N. peacekeeping duty when he was kidnapped Feb.
17, 1988, in south Lebanon.
   ``I can only repeat my profound sorrow and outrage at the tragic
fate of a courageous and dedicated officer who was serving the
cause of peace in Lebanon under the flag of he United Nations,''
Perez de Cuellar said.
   He said he assured President Bush he would ``remain in close and
continuous contact with all those who may be in a position to help
resolve this problem, as well as the wider problem of all the
hostages.''
   Sixteen Western hostages are held in Lebanon, including eight
Americans.
   The longest held is Terry A. Anderson, 41, chief Middle East
correspondent for The Associated Press, who was kidnapped March 16,
1985.
</TEXT>
