<FIRST>r a PM-Eastern     08-10 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>Some Eastern Pilots Crossing Picket Line</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of Eastern Airlines pilots
have crossed the picket line since the five-month-old strike began,
giving Eastern confidence it can meet its goal of 1,700 pilots for
its new schedule.
   The crossovers have come despite a union vote this week to stay
on strike as long as Eastern's current management controls the
airline.
   At least 365 pre-strike Eastern pilots have returned to work,
100 to 150 of them since Monday, according to company and union
officials. All but 220 of Eastern's 3,500 pilots joined a strike by
Eastern's Machinists launched March 4.
   During the walkout, Eastern has borrowed crews from Continental
Airlines, which like Eastern is owned by Texas Air Corp.
   But if pilots continue to stream back, the Miami-based carrier
may be able to rebound alone.
   ``Our needs are being met, and we will fill our pilot quota of
1,700 pilots,'' said Eastern spokesman Robin Matell. ``There's not
any question that we will be able to meet our schedule.''
   The union has kept the airline to 30 percent of its pre-strike
schedule of more than 1,100 daily departures. Eastern's goal is 800
daily departures by 1990. The airline expects to have 390 daily
departures next Tuesday.
   Ron Cole, a spokesman for the striking pilots, maintained that
the union isn't overly concerned with the crossovers.
   The returning pilots are ``creating a nightmare for Eastern,''
he said.
   Cole said that the pilots who are returning are not qualified to
fly aircraft Eastern has available and that friction between newly
hired pilots and returning pilots will hurt safety in the cockpit.
   ``We anticipate that a lot of the new hires will be leaving,''
Cole said.
   Eastern said relations between the former strikers and the new
pilots have been friendly.
</TEXT>
