<FIRST>r p PM-Calif-Abortion     08-10 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Calif-Abortion,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pro-Choice Advocates Face October Runoff For 76th Assembly District
Seat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ESCONDIDO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An advocate of abortion rights has
apparently won the Republican nomination for a state Assembly seat
over five abortion opponents, with the counting of most absentee
ballots completed.
   Tricia Hunter had 14,822 votes, or 196 more than her closest GOP
rival, Richard Lyles, after 532 absentee ballots were counted
Wednesday. About 135 more ballots were to be counted today, not
enough to affect the outcome.
   The election Tuesday to fill a seat left empty by the death of a
legislator in June was the first state race since the U.S. Supreme
Court ruling last month giving states more latitude in restricting
abortions.
   ``I think the statement that came out of this race is that
voters want to know the candidates' position and they are not going
to let them waffle their position,'' Hunter said.
   ``The candidates are going to have to take one side of the issue
or the other. I've been pro-choice for a long time and I believe
it's an individual decision that a woman has the right to make.''
   Unless Hunter's apparent victory is somehow overturned, she will
advance to an Oct. 3 election against Democrat Jeannine Correia,
who bested one other Democrat in Tuesday's voting. Both Democrats
support abortion rights.
   The district is largely Republican _ 54 percent to 33 percent
Democrat _ making the GOP candidate an overwhelming favorite.
   ``I believe the abortion issue was the deciding factor in this
election,'' said Correia.
   Voters were free to pick from among six Republicans and two
Democrats on one ballot.
   If one of the eight had won 50 percent of the vote, he or she
would have won outright. Instead, there will be runoff between the
top vote-getter from each party.
</TEXT>
