<FIRST>u i PM-Poland 1stLd-Writethru   08-10 0573</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0471,0591</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communist-Allied Party Talks With Solidarity About Forming Government</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with Peasant Party leader meeting with
Solidarity, prime minister. Changes byline. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist-aligned United Peasant Party
today met with Solidarity to consider its invitation to form a
governing coalition that would exclude the Communists.
   With Solidarity's 161 parliamentary seats and the Peasant
Party's 76, a Solidarity-Peasant alliance would have a bare working
majority of 237 votes in the 460-member parliament.
   If joined by the small Democratic Party, which also has been
linked to the Communists, the Solidarity-led coalition would have a
firm majority.
   The Democrats said Wedneday that they would like to discuss
Solidarity leader Lech Walesa's invitation to join forces, but no
meeting has been scheduled.
   The talks between the Solidarity labor movement and the Peasant
Party today were held in private at Peasant Party executive
offices. Sen. Andrzej Wielowieyski and Sejm Deputy Jacek Kuron,
deputy chairman of the Solidarity caucus, were among those
representing Solidarity.
   They were joined by a handful of Peasant Party lawmakers,
including Aleksander Bentkowski, the party's parliamentary leader.
   ``We're at the beginning of the beginning,'' said Jaroslaw
Kaczynski, a Solidarity senator from Elblag, who attended the
hour-long meeting as Walesa's envoy. He said the talks would
continue.
   Earlier today, Bentkowski met with the new prime minister, Gen.
Czeslaw Kiszczak, a government spokesman confirmed.
   Peasant Party officials refused comment on the meeting.
   According to the opposition newspaper Gazeta Wyborcza, the
meeting was for Bentkowski to inform Kiszczak that most of the
Peasant deputies in the Sejm, or parliament, would oppose a Cabinet
nominated by Kiszczak.
   Walesa said Monday that any government formed by Kiszczak would
only extend the Communists' 45-year-old monopoly on power. The
coalition he seeks would put the Communists in the opposition in
parliament.
   The Democrats and Peasants have been linked to the Communists
since the late 1940's.
   The Democratic Party said Wednesday the wording of Walesa's
proposal ``makes it difficult to take a final stand'' and that it
wanted direct talks to clarify the offer.
   The party said in a statement after a leadership meeting that it
was ``ready to participate in any government of national confidence
giving realistic hopes for overcoming the current stalemate and
improvement of the economic situation.''
   Solidarity's parliamentary floor leader, Bronislaw Geremek, said
Kiszczak is expected to present candidates to fill the Cabinet by
Aug. 24. ``Until then we have time for dialogue,'' he said.
   Bentkowski told state TV on Wednesday that his caucus is
``susceptible to Lech Walesa's proposition, and generally speaking
questions the appropriateness of its participation in the current
coalition'' with the Communists.
   The Peasant Party's constituents reacted negatively to
Kiszczak's election Aug. 2, he said.
   ``There are still two weeks before a final decision, but on the
basis of remarks presented so far, one may conclude that the club
will vote against the Cabinet presented by Gen. Kiszczak,''
Bentkowski said.
   Several deputies urged the party to reject a coalition with
Kiszczak on the ground that it would have no public support. Others
appealed for a coalition with Solidarity. ``The people are
revolting. They won't hold for long,'' said Tadeusz Sytek from
Ostrow Wielkopolski, western Poland.
   However, Sejm Speaker Mikolaj Kozakiewicz, a Peasant Party
member, told state TV that Walesa's offer seemed to be an
``extreme'' position and was ill-timed because a prime minister was
already chosen.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
