<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Abduction 1stLd-Writethru a0508 08-10 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Abduction, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0508,0434</SECOND>
<HEAD>Confession Could Help Solve Case of Missing Children In Tokyo Suburb</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 6th graf, ``The police...'' with 1 graf to UPDATE with
charge filed against suspect in photo case. Pickup 7th graf, ``The official...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARI YAMAGUCHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who was arrested for allegedly taking nude
photographs of two children has confessed to kidnapping and killing
one of four girls whose disappearance terrorized a Tokyo suburb,
police said today.
   Officers found a child's skull near a place mentioned by the
man, and the skull was being examined to see whether it was that of
Ayako Nomoto, the 5-year-old girl the man confessed to killing in
early June, police said.
   A police official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said it
was too early to decide whether the man should be charged as
Ayako's killer or whether he would be linke to the case of the
other three girls.
   Newspapers put out extra editions and television stations
extended news programs to cover the case. Television crews went
into the man's house to film his book and videotape collection, and
reporters interviewed his co-workers.
   Parents have been closely watching their children in Saitama
prefecture, just north of Tokyo, since the abductions began in
August 1988. Three girls have been found dead and one remains
missing.
   The police official said the man, Tsutomu Miyazaki, 26, was
arrested July 23 for allegedly forcing two elementary schoolgirls
to let him take nude photographs of them. The official said the
suspect was charged with indecent assault and that he will be
questioned further about the abductions.
   The official said the latest police search began after Miyazaki
told officers he had buried part of Ayako's body in a camping park
in western Tokyo.
   Five days after her disappearance, a girl's body without a head,
hands or feet was found at a public bathroom in a cemetery in
Saitama.
   The other three girls are:
   _Mari Konno, 4, who disappeared in August 1988. Her bones and
ashes, in a cardboard box, were placed in front of her home in
Saitama in February. A letter in the box said, ``Mari burned to
death.'' Letters sent later to her home and the national newspaper
Asahi Shimbun by a writer identifying herself as Yuko Imada claimed
responsibility for the abduction and murder.
   _Erika Namba, 4, whose naked and strangled body was found in
December in a campground 20 miles west of her Saitama home.
   _Masami Yoshizawa, 7, who was kidnapped in October and remains
missing.
</TEXT>
