<FIRST>r a PM-ActivistMurdered     08-10 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Activist Murdered,0523</SECOND>
<HEAD>Neighbors Point to Drug Dealers in Death of Activist's Wife</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL GEITNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents are angry in the Brooklyn neighborhood
where an anti-drug crusader was fatally shot through her bedroom
window. They are also scared.
   ``On my block I see what goes on but I shut up,'' Marguerite
Wise said Wednesday. ``I'm afraid for my life and my kids.''
   Maria Hernandez, 34, a mother of three, was getting ready for
work about 4:30 a.m. Tuesday when at least five shots were fired
into her family's first-floor apartment. A bullet hit her in the
head; she died hours later.
   On Wednesday, her husband, Carlos, went ahead and testified
before a grand jury against a neighbor Mrs. Hernandez had accused
of drug dealing, a source said.
   ``That woman never hurt anybody,'' said Mrs. Wise, who lives
around the corner from the Hernandezes. ``She's trying to protect
her neighborhood, her kids.''
   Mrs. Wise said she is too afraid to complain to police about the
drug dealers that plague the neighborhood. ``You cannot open your
mouth,'' she said. ``You can't move noplace _ the rents are too
high. You don't like it but what are you going to do?''
   A patrol car had been driving past the Hernandez home about once
an hour since Saturday because the family had received death
threats from drug dealers.
   The three-story building was a burned-out shell when the
Hernandezes moved in four years ago. They completely renovated it.
A neighbor, Carmen Camacho, said they were always yelling at drug
dealers sitting on their stoop to move on.
   Ms. Camacho, who has lived on the block for 15 years and is
godmother to the Hernandezes' 3-year-old son, said she is afraid to
go outside, even to attend the block association meetings the
Hernandezes organized.
   Speaking in Spanish interpreted by her 13-year-old daughter, Ms.
Camacho said she has seen the neighborhood deteriorate _ when ``the
drug addicts moved in'' _ and saw some improvement come from her
neighbors' efforts.
   Hernandez, 33, went into the chambers of a grand jury Wednesday,
spending several hours there. A source who spoke on condition of
anonymity said he testified against next-door neighbor Raymond
Gonzalez, who is accused of stabbing Hernandez in the arm and
threatening him with a machine gun last month after Mrs. Hernandez
accused Gonzalez of selling cocaine in front of their house.
   Police say they have no suspects in the shooting. Gonzalez was
in custody over the stabbing at the time of Mrs. Hernandez's death.
   Hernandez had no comment when he left the grand jury room but
told The New York Times, ``I am going to stay here and keep
fighting the drugs, because of the kids and innocent people.''
   After the shooting, police stood guard at the Hernandezes'
building, mostly to protect the family from curious crowds and the
news media.
   While women with baby carriages gathered out front, a block
away, six or so dealers sold heroin with brand names like
``Terror'' and ``Steel Ball.''
</TEXT>
