<SECOND>PM-Lebanon-Hostages, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0500,0465</SECOND>
<HEAD>Militiamen Raid Shiite Homes; Report Says Hostages Moved</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with militiamen raiding Shiite houses,
two peacekeepers injured. No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Hostages, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli-backed militiamen raided houses
in Shiite Moslem villages in south Lebanon today to search for
suspects in a bombing that injured five Israeli soldiers and an
allied militiaman.
   Also today, the Beirut weekly Ash-Shiraa quoted unidentified
``non-Arab'' sources as saying armed women have been moving the
Western hostages to new hideouts in Beirut and its suburbs.
   A U.N. source said two Norwegian soldiers, serving with the
United Nations' peacekeeping force in south Lebanon, were slightly
wounded when they tried to stop militiamen of the Israeli-sponsored
South Lebanon Army from carrying out arrests in the southern
villages of Ibl El-Saqi and Rashaya.
   The source, who insisted on anonymity, said the militiamen threw
grenades at the Norwegian soldiers, who were manning a checkpoint.
   The Voice of the South, the radio of the South Lebanon Army,
said the militia rounded up several young Shiite men for
questioning in connection with Wednesday's bombing.
   It said most arrests were made in the village of Khiyam. Khiyam,
Ibl El-Saqi and Rashaya are in Israel's self-designated security
zone in south Lebanon, which is patrolled by the South Lebanon Army
and Israeli troops.
   On Wednesday, a Shiite Moslem clergyman detonated a truck bomb
in south Lebanon as an Israeli patrol passed by. Five Israeli
soldiers and an SLA militiaman were injured.
   The pro-Iranian group Hezbollah said the attack was to avenge
Israel's July 28 abduction of Sheik Abduk Karim Obeid, a
Hezbollah-affiliated cleric.
   Ash-Shiraa did not say whether the reported moving of the
Lebanese hostages was related to Obeid's abduction.
   The weekly said the hostages were transported in ``medium-sized
buses, equipped with every comfort _ beds and chairs. ... As for
the windows, they were curtained so no one could see anything
inside (the bus).''
   Ash-Shiraa said the ``women kidnappers'' in long black chadors
moved the hostages at night and were equipped with automatic
weapons to be used only under ``utmost necessity.''
   The report could not be independently verified.
   Ash-Shiraa gained international renown in November 1986 when it
broke the story of secret U.S. arms sales to Iran in return for the
release of hostages. But its recent reporting on the hostages has
not been accurate.
   Ash-Shiraa did not say when the hostages were moved.
   There are 16 foreign hostages in Lebanon, _ eight Americans,
four Britons, an Irishman, an Italian and two West Germans. Most
are believed held by Shiite Moslem extremists loyal to Iran.
   Longest held is Terry A. Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent for The Associated Press. He was abducted March 16,
1985.
</TEXT>
