<FIRST>r i PM-SouthAfrica 2ndLd-Writethru a0521 08-10 0404</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0521,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Use Whips, Batons To Disperse Marchers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE with 18 injured. Pickup 4th, `The
march...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police swinging whips and
batons broke up a rally by 500 trade union members outside a
courthouse today, and officials said at least 18 black
demonstrators were injured and 20 others were arrested.
   The union members, who were singing and dancing, marched about
two miles from a train station to the Kempton Park courthouse
outside Johannesburg before police chased them from the area, said
the Congress of South African Trade Unions, the nation's largest
labor federation.
   At least 18 people suffered injuries that required treatment at
Johannesburg Hospital, said federation spokesman Neil Coleman.
   Police arrested 20 demonstrators who failed to disperse, but
Capt. Ruben Bloomberg said he was unaware of any injuries.
   The march was staged in support of 27 workers ordered to appear
in court for allegedly singing freedom songs and dancing on public
trains.
   The Congress of South African Trade Unions says more than 400 of
its members have been charged with disturbing he peace for singing
on trains since June. Most of those who have appeared in court
received fines.
   Today's court proceedings were postponed when the men ordered to
appear did not show up.
   The union said its members will continue singing on trains that
carry workers to and from their jobs in the cities and the outlying
black townships.
   ``We will continue in a spirit of defiance,'' said union
official Ariel Mabalane. ``They sing to popularize their campaign,
to express their feelings as the repressed and exploited.''
   The labor group is one of the leading members of the Mass
Democratic Movement, an anti-apartheid coalition that launched a
nationwide mass defiance campaign Aug. 2.
   In another labor conflict, 13,500 autoworkers remained on strike
in wage disputes at the Toyota, Volkswagen and South Africa Motor
Corp. plants.
   Toyota officials today described the strike as the worst ever in
the South African automaking industry.
   The autoworkers, most of whom belong to the National Union of
Metalworkers of South Africa, have been off the job since last week.
   The union is trying to negotiate a wage agreement on a
nationwide basis with all major auto companies. The strikes began
while negotiations were taking place and the companies have accused
the union of bad faith.
</TEXT>
