<FIRST>r i PM-Germany-Flights     08-10 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Germany-Flights,0253</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lufthansa Inaugurates First Postwar Service to East Germany</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lufthansa airlines today
inaugurated the first scheduled flights between West Germany and
East Germany with an 80-minute trip from Frankfurt to Leipzig.
   Previously, the two German states were linked by air only twice
yearly, when special charters were arranged to take businessmen to
and from the biannual Leipzig trade fair.
   East Germany's Interflug airline has been authorized under an
agreement signed by officials from Bonn and East Berlin last month
to provide service between Leipzig and Duesseldorf, West Germany.
Weekly Interflug flights are expected to begin Friday.
   Flight LH6010, a Boeing 737, took off from Frankfurt airport at
9:13 a.m. with a host of dignitaries on hand to see the West German
carrier's first regularly scheduled flight to Leipzig.
   Lufthansa officials said earlier that the flight agreement runs
only through Oct. 31. The airlines want to determine the popularity
of the flights before agreeing on a permanent schedule.
   Officials on both sides of the border believe the new routes
will be popular, especially in light of the sharp increase in
travel between the two German states.
   More than 7 million visits to West Germany by East German
citizens were recorded last year, and Chancellor Helmut Kohl's
chief of staff, Rudolf Seiters, reported Wednesday that the travel
trends are growing.
   The Lufthansa-Interflug agreement required and received the
approval of the Allied powers, which continue to exercise some
jurisdiction over German air space.
</TEXT>
