<FIRST>r w PM-RunawaysJourney     08-10 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Runaways Journey,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Iowa Boys Get What They Want After Two Days on the Road</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After more than two days on the road, fueled
by pizza and financed by checks drawn on their father's account,
two Iowa boys got what they wanted in a hearing before a federal
judge in Washington.
   A D.C. Superior Court judge ruled Wednesday that the boys, aged
10 and 12, can live with their mother temporarily. Their father had
been given custody of the children after a 1985 divorce.
   The boys were missing for 56 hours as they traveled more than
1,000 miles on Greyhound buses, headed for their mother's home in
North Carolina, before they were stopped in the District of
Columbia last Tuesday.
   In an interview with The Washington Post, the boys described
their getaway from their father's home in Ames, Iowa, equipped with
two changes of clothes, a Sony Walkman and four blank checks.
   The boys, whose names have not been released, said they spent a
night in the Iowa woods before persuading a bank to let them write
a $300 check.
   ``I just went to the bank and told the guy I wanted $300 and he
told me what to write on it,'' said the 12-year-old.
   They bought bus tickets, and began a zig-zagging trip across the
Midwest.
   Their first meal on the road was $15 worth of pizza. ``We had it
for breakfast,'' said the younger brother.
   ``They were probably just jumping the bus from one station to
another, trying to figure it out as they went along,'' said John
Wick, a Greyhound sales agent.
   The boys' father and the Story County sheriff asked Greyhound
for help when their bicycles were found at the bus station.
Greyhound traced the boys to the District of Columbia an hour
before their bus arrived Aug. 1. A D.C. police youth division
officer was waiting for them.
</TEXT>
