<FIRST>r i PM-Afghanistan     08-10 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan,0389</SECOND>
<HEAD>Afghan Rebel President Criticizes Rival Leader</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PESHAWAR, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of the Afghan rebels'
self-proclaimed government today branded his own foreign minister a
``killer'' of innocent Afghans and other guerrillas.
   Sibghatullah Mojaddidi, president of the rebel
government-in-exile, said his regime would have a better chance of
survival without hard-line rebel leader Gulbaddin Hekmatyar, who
serves as foreign minister.
   Hekmatyar is leader of the powerful Hezb-i-Islami resistance
group.
   ``He considers himself the hero of the jihad (holy war), but in
fact he's a killer,'' Mojaddidi said in an interview. ``He has
killed hundreds of mujahedeen inside Afghanistan and hundreds of
innocent people inside Afghanistan.''
   Mujahedeen, or Moslem guerrillas, under Hekmatyar's command are
accused of killing 32 rebels of the rival Jamiat-i-Islami rebel
group in northern Afghanistan on July 9. Hekmatyar has admitted his
men's involvement in the slayings but said they were provoked.
   Jamiat leader Burhanuddin Rabbani has called for Hekmatyar's
suspension from the rebel government.
   The infighting threatens the unity of the rebel factions who are
fighting Afghanistan's Soviet-backed government.
   ``This man is destroying Afghanistan,'' Mojaddidi said of
Hekmatyar. His party, the Afghan National Liberation Front, is
viewed as more moderate than either Hekmatyar's or Rabbani's.
   Asked whether the rebel government would be better off without
Hekmatyar, Mojaddidi replied: ``Why not?''
   Hekmatyar was not immediately available for comment. His chief
political officer, Abdul Qadir Karyab, said of Mojaddidi, ``We
think this man is mad.''
   He said the Hezb-i-Islami party had not decided whether to pull
out of the rebel government, as Hekmatyar threatened to do unless
it held elections inside Afghanistan and in refugee camps outside
the country.
   He indicated his party might continue as a member of the
government if an election commission already appointed came forward
with a schedule for the polls.
   The mujahedeen, the most powerful of which are headquartered in
Pakistan, are fighting to oust the Marxist government in Kabul and
establish an Islamic republic in Afghanistan.
   The rebels are united in their hatred of the communists but
differ widely on the nature of a Moslem government and the means to
achieve it.
   The ruling People's Democratic Republic of Afghanistan took
power in a 1978 coup that sparked the Moslem insurgency.
</TEXT>
