<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 1135EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DetroitSymphony     08-10 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Detroit Symphony,0223</SECOND>
<HEAD>Symphony Musicians Take Pay Cut</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Musicians have voted to take a 9.8 percent pay
cut in a four-year contract designed to keep the Detroit Symphony
Orchestra alive.
   The agreement, approved 82-8 with one abstention Wednesday, was
reached Monday, said Wesley Jacobs of the Detroit Federation of
Musicians.
   ``We want to do everything we can to be a part of the
rejuvenation of the financial health of this orchestra,'' said
Jacobs.
   The musicians had one year left on their old contract, but the
orchestra sought a new one to reduce its debt, projected at $11.7
million this budget year. Under the new contract, the base annual
salary will drop to $47,694.
   The symphony missed a payroll last month and had threatened to
close until the Legislature appropriated $1 million in emergency
aid, received last week.
   The musicians say the 75-year-old orchestra, considered one of
the nation's top 10, is an important asset for a city fighting a
reputation for drugs and crime.
   The orchestra has blamed its financial problems on low
attendance caused by an inability to draw younger concertgoers and
blacks, who make up two-thirds of the city's population of 1
million.
   Several other U.S. symphonies also run at a deficit, including
those in Denver, Nashville, New Orleans and Pittsburgh.
</TEXT>
