<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 1209EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Fetus-Drugs     08-10 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fetus-Drugs,0358</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Arrested for Endangering Fetus By Swallowing Cocaine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIDDLETOWN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pregnant woman who police say stuffed
a quarter-ounce of cocaine into her mouth and swallowed it as she
was being arrested was charged with causing a risk of injury to a
minor.
   If Nellie Baez, who is four months' pregnant, is convicted, it
would overturn Connecticut case law that holds that a fetus is not
a person _ a question central to the abortion debate, authorities
said.
   But lawmakers, civil libertarians and John J. Kelly, the chief
state's attorney, doubted the charge would hold up in court because
of a 1986 state court ruling that a fetus is not a person.
   Baez, 20, was arrested Aug. 1 and arraigned Monday after being
hospitalized. She also was charged with cocaine possession and
tampering with evidence.
   Police said the fetus appears to be fine.
   Kelly said of the risk-of-injury charge, ``I don't see that as
fitting.''
   However, Kelly said the increasing incidence of cocaine-addicted
newborns will force lawmakers to consider of whether the state
should protect the fetus.
   In Rockford, Ill., a grand jury in May refused to return
manslaughter charges against a woman whose 2-day-old daughter died
allegedly from prenatal cocaine use. In Florida, at least two women
have been arrested under a drug-delivery law in the past year after
giving birth to babies with cocaine in their systems.
   Martha Stone, legal director of the Connecticut Civil Liberties
Union, said her organization would fight attempts to bolster a
fetus' rights over a woman's rights.
   ``Women have the constitutional right to privacy and the right
to procreate by choice,'' Stone said. ``If the criminal laws are
being used to accord fetuses rights and, in any way (protect
against) harm to the fetus, it interferes with the woman's absolute
right to privacy.''
   Anti-abortion activists applauded legal efforts to protect
fetuses, saying such cases will provide the push needed to overturn
abortion laws.
   ``I wish they'd consider every unborn baby at risk,'' said Mary
Ann Pressamarita, executive director of Defenders of the Unborn.
</TEXT>
