<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 1233EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Burma     08-10 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Burma,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>17,877 Criminals Released in Burma</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANGOON, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burma's military government has released
17,877 prisoners held on criminal charges after a recent amnesty,
the official Working People's Daily said Thursday.
   Western diplomats and an opposition party spokesman said,
however, the government also has arrested thousands of political
dissidents.
   Under an amnesty announced July 20, death sentences for criminal
offenses were commuted to life imprisonment, life terms were
reduced to 10 years, and all others were cut by two thirds.
   Cases under trial against people arrested before the military
takeover Sept. 18 were to be dropped and those serving sentences of
under two years were to be immediately released, the order said.
   The amnesty does not apply to cases of treason or breaches of
martial law, which was imposed during the takeover to prevent open
political dissent.
   Rangoon-based Western diplomats contacted by telephone from
Bangkok on Wednesday said the military had arrested up to 3,000
people on political charges since July 20 after putting under house
arrest Aung San Suu Kyi and Tin Oo, the leaders of the main
opposition party the National League for Democracy.
   Diplomats and dissidents said that in the time between the army
takeover and the latest wave of arrests up to 3,000 more people may
have been arrested.
   Martial law forbids political gatherings of more than five
people. Military tribunals already have sentenced to death three
members of the National League for allegedly planning a bomb
attack. Five youths were given five-year jail terms for shouting
slogans during an anti-government protest July 17.
   During last year's mass protests for democracy, authorities also
released thousands of criminals on to the streets. Diplomats said
the move was aimed at convincing the people of the need for a tough
army presence.
   They also speculated that authorities may want to clear space in
the jails to make way for newly arrested political prisoners.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
