<FIRST>r w AM-HUD-Handicapped     08-10 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD-Handicapped,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>HUD Announces Grants To House Homeless Handicapped</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Department of Housing and Urban
Development on Thursday said it would award $10 million in grants
to provide permanent housing for the handicapped homeless.
   The money, awarded after competitive bidding, will go to 66
projects in 21 states and the District of Columbia, HUD Secretary
Jack Kemp said.
   ``President Bush and I are committed to ending the appalling
tragedy of homelessness,'' Kemp said in a statement.
   The grant program was authorized by Congress in the McKinney
Homeless Assistance Act, named after the late Connecticut Rep.
Stewart McKinney.
   The states getting the grants to help the handicapped homeless
must match the HUD money with an equal or greater amount of state
and local funding.
   The 66 projects were selected from 102 applications totaling $21
million. Grants totaling $9,947,189 were authorized, HUD said.
   The grant money can be used to buy or rehabilitate buildings to
use for permanent housing and to provide technical assistance and
operating funds to non-profit organizations that sponsor the
projects.
   Under program guidelines, the money can be used to provide
housing to handicapped who currently are homeless or deemed in
danger or becoming homeless. People with physical or mental
impairments are eligible for the program.
</TEXT>
