<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Soviet-US     08-10 0182</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Soviet-US,0187</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Captain Says More Exchanges With Soviets Possible</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The captain of a U.S. warship that
recently visited the Soviet port of Sevastopol said Thursday there
will be more contact between the U.S. Navy and the Soviets.
   The next one might be a call by Soviet warships at the West
Coast of the United States, said Cmdr. Ronald C. Bogle, captain of
the guided missile frigate USS Kauffman.
   The Kauffman has anchored at the Bosporus strait, which splits
Istanbul, on its return from Sevastopol last week. It will head for
the Mediterranean, where the U.S. 6th Fleet is based.
   The vessel was escorted by the guided missile cruiser USS Thomas
S. Gates on the first U.S. naval visit to that port since World War
II and the first to any Soviet port since 1975.
   Thousands of Soviets welcomed the U.S. sailors, showering them
with gifts and attention.
   ``This was absolutely the best port visit I have had in my 18
years in the navy,'' Bogle said. ``Neither side could understand
why this was not done sooner.''
</TEXT>
