<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Swiss-Vandals     08-10 0156</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Swiss-Vandals,0159</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vandals Topple Statue in Region Known For Separatism</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LES RANGIERS, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unknown vandals toppled and
stole part of an eight-ton World War I statue Thursday in the Jura
region, which is known for periodic violence by separatists.
   Police said there were no immediate suspects or claim of
responsibility for the pre-dawn attack, carried out with the aid of
a pulley and a steel cable. The stone statue of a soldier was
missing its head and part of the bayonet after the attack, police
said.
   In 1984, the separatist Jura youth organization Beliers claimed
an almost identical attack on the monument at Les Rangiers, which
commemorates the Swiss army's mobilization at the time of World War
I.
   French-speaking separatists are agitating for a part of the
historic Jura region that remains in the German-speaking canton of
Bern to join a separate Jura canton created 10 years ago. Tension
has since declined, however.
</TEXT>
