<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 1247EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-DC-10Landing 1stLd-Writethru a0497 08-10 0806</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-DC-10 Landing, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0497,0825</SECOND>
<HEAD>Engine Failure Forces DC-10 To Make Emergency Landing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with FAA chief's comments and
FAA figures on safety of DC-10; PICKS UP 7th graf, ``We heard ...'; SUBS
final graf with 5 grafs to add history of plane, more passenger quotes.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Northwest Airlines DC-10 carrying 256 people
made an emergency landing in Denver after its tail engine
apparently began breaking up. Officials said they found
shrapnel-like holes in the engine cover.
   The incident resembled the engine failure that preceded last
month's crash of a United Airlines DC-10 in Sioux City, Iowa, in
which 111 people died.
   Flight 308 from Los Angeles to Minneapolis landed safely at
Stapleton International Airport about 6:30 p.m. Wednesday, said
airport spokesman Richrad Boulware. There was no apparent damage to
its hydraulic controls, unlike the Iowa jet.
   Less than 30 minutes earlier while cruising at 39,000 feet, the
crew reported a loss of oil pressure and severe vibration in the
tail engine and shut it down, said Greg Feith, spokesman for the
National Transportation Safety Board.
   A 13-member NTSB investigative team from Washington was sent to
Denver.
   Accidents that do not involve fatalities or serious damage to
aircraft normally are investigated by regional offices, but the
Northwest failure was ``too much of a coincidence,'' Feith said,
referring to the Sioux City crash.
   In Washington, however, Federal Aviation Administration chief
James B. Busey said officials ``know of no hard facts that would
lead us to take action to ground DC-10s.''
   Busey said he did not have enough information to compare the
incident with the crash in Sioux City. But he said the DC-10 is
``safe to fly. I would fly in the aircraft today.'' He called it a
``comfortable, good-performing'' airliner.
   A government-industry task force looking into possible design
changes in the DC-10 and other wide-body airliners was holding its
first meeting today, Busey said. The FAA formed the group after the
Iowa crash and said it was also in response to incidents several
years ago involving a Boeing 747 and a Lockheed L-1011 in which
engine failures caused damage to aircraft control mechanisms.
   At least 18, or about 4 percent, of the 445 DC-10s built have
been involved in accidents, FAA figures show. That is a higher
percentage than for Boeing 747s or Lockheed L-1011 jumbos.
   Busey said the Northwest incident was an example of ``the way
the system should work'' because the pilots quickly shut down the
engine, diverted to a nearby airport and landed safely with no
injuries.
   ``We heard a loud noise,'' said passenger Don Burnett. ``It was
a boom and a shudder. We couldn't see it. We just felt it,'' he
said. ``Someone said something was hanging from the engines.''
   ``They experienced a severe vibration from the No. 2 engine,
(and) as a precautionary measure, they elected to make an
unscheduled landing,'' said Kevin Whalen, a spokesman for the St.
Paul, Minn.-based airline.
   The No. 2 engine is mounted in the aircraft's vertical
stabilizer, just above the tail wing. On United's Flight 232, the
No. 2 engine disintegrated, shooting shrapnel that apparently
severed hydraulic lines used to control the jet. The investigation
into the cause of that crash is continuing.
   Boulware said there were ``multiple shrapnellike holes in the
outer cowling'' or cover of the No. 2 engine.
   ``One of the holes was big enough I could have stuck my hand
through,'' he said.
   Boulware said he also saw broken turbine fan blades inside the
engine, and that the engine's tail cone was missing.
   But he added, ``We can't draw any comparisons to the Sioux City
flight. We don't know exactly what happened.''
   Northwest spokesman Bob Gibbons said there were two small holes
in the engine's cowling. He said Northwest DC-10s are equipped with
Pratt and Whitney engines, unlike the United jet, which used
General Electric engines.
   The DC-10 has one engine under each wing in addition to the tail
engine.
   The DC-10-40 model plane was one of 22 purchased by Northwest,
Gibbons said. It was built in 1972, airline officials said. They
said they had no immediate information on the performance history
of the plane or the No. 2 engine.
   Whalen said the landing was normal in terms of controlling the
airplane. The 245 passengers were being placed on alternate flights
to Minneapolis, he said. There also were 11 crew members on board,
he added.
   Passenger John Ophoven, a Minneapolis businessman returning home
with his family from a vacation at Disneyland, said the plane
``just shook a lot.
   ``The pilot said the hydraulics were fine, and they had all the
steering,'' said Ophoven. ``The vibration lasted a minute or two.
   ``We dropped fast for a little while. It never really tipped. It
slowed down. Then it smoothed out.''
</TEXT>
