<FIRST>r i AM-Canal-Workers     08-10 0623</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canal-Workers,0641</SECOND>
<HEAD>Surviving Canal Construction Workers Proud of Their Accomplishment</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EL PARAISO, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``We worked for the better to come,''
said Arnold Small. ``We knew it was a good thing we were doing.''
   What Small and tens of thousands of others were doing in the
early years of the century was digging the Panama Canal, the
waterway that joined the Atlantic and Pacific oceans 75 years ago
on Aug. 15.
   Small was 24 in 1914, when the first ship sailed through.
   ``I helped build the canal. That is a wonderful thing to
remember,'' Small said in an interview as he watched an honor guard
place a wreath on a monument to the thousands of workers who died
during a failed French attempt to build a canal in the 19th century.
   Small sat in a wheelchair on the side of a small hill in the
steamy heat of the green, lush woods on the banks of the canal near
the Pedro Miguel Locks.
   Small was born in Barbados and, like thousands of fellow
islanders, came to Panama to find work. He later fought with the
British army in Europe during World War I before returning to
Panama.
   Only Small and a few companions survived those days of malaria,
yellow fever, picks and shovels, sweat, blood, dynamite and wages
of 10 cents an hour.
   Men came by the thousands from Barbados, Jamaica, Ireland, the
Basque area of Spain, Greece, Barbados and many other lands, to
work under American bosses and engineers.
   They dug the canal, damming a river to create a huge lake and
building the system of locks that raises ships in 1,000-foot
waterbeds 85 feet above sea level and lowers them 50 miles away.
   There were only a little more than 300 Panamanians actually
digging.
   ``Even then we had started our service-oriented economy,'' canal
deputy administrator Fernando Manfredo said, smiling. ``We had
thousands (of Panamanians) providing food, lodging, water and other
services to those who actually dug the canal.''
   Thousands died in accidents in the days when health insurance
was unknown and liquor was the medicine that made pain go away.
   ``In those days all of us had to drink quinine almost every day
while working,'' said Constantine ``Parky'' Parkinson.
   ``When the rainy season came it fell for weeks, sometimes for
months, One's working clothes had to be worn every day for days wet
because there was no sun to dry them. One had to wash his own
clothes and keep the camp clean,'' said Parkinson, 94, who came
from Jamaica.
   ``On the Fourth of July we got a free train to take us to Panama
for the celebration,'' he said. ``There was plenty of free food and
cool drinks.''
   ``I remember my grandmother talking about how when Halley's
Comet was passing by (in 1910), everybody was saying that all were
going to be killed, so a bunch of Spanish workers decided to get
drunk out of their minds and die that way. All they got was a
hangover,'' Manfredo said.
   ``We made Panama a gateway to the world,'' Small said. ``My
brother, Walter, brought me here and I started as a water boy in
1911. I am a lucky man. Others younger than me are in worse shape.
I thank God I am alive.''
   Parkinson lost a leg during construction. Until recently, he had
been campaigning for more benefits for non-U.S. citizens who worked
on the canal.
   ``It was a labor force that had pride in what it did. ``It is a
tradition that our workers still hold,'' Manfredo said. ``During
the worst time of the political disturbances here last year,
absenteeism of canal workers was at its lwoedt.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
