<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Settlers     08-10 0567</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Settlers,0590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Settler Population Up Despite Uprising</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LOUIS MEIXLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The population of Jewish settlements in the
occupied territories is 6,500 higher than last year, despite the
20-month-old Palestinian uprising, the government said.
   The figures, released Wednesday by the government-run Central
Bureau of Statistics, show that Jewish settlements grew almost 400
percent more than Jerusalem, the second-fastest growing area.
   The growth rate has, however, slipped since the uprising against
Israeli rule of the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip began 20
months ago.
   Settler leaders attributed the continued growth to right-wing
activists moving to the occupied lands in a show of Jewish resolve
to hold onto the disputed lands.
   Noam Arnon, a spokesman for the Gush Emunim settler movement,
said settlers who move to the territories want to ``give a positive
answer to the uprising.''
   Left-wing legislators expressed skepticism about the government
figures. Critics said some Jewish nationalists bought homes in the
territories to boost population figures but did not move to the
area.
   Dedi Zucker, a legislator from the leftist Citizens Rights
Movement, also said the figures do not reflect those who leave the
settlements but do not legally change their addresses.
   Independent observers said the settler population may be higher
than the government figures. Most also said both leftists and
rightists have tried to skew the figures.
   The Bureau of Statistics reported that 66,500 Jews lived in the
occupied territories in late 1988, an increase of 10.3 percent over
1987.
   According to the bureau, 2,500 of the new residents were
accounted for by the number of births over deaths, while 4,000
people moved to the area.
   In 1986, the year before the outbreak of the Palestinian
uprising, the settler population increased by 15.8 percent, the
bureau said.
   Many observers attribute the slower growth to the uprising,
which has seen constant stoning and firebombing attacks on
settler-owned cars.
   At least 531 Palestinians and 38 Israelis have been killed in
the revolt, which began in December 1987.
   The bureau did not survey the Palestinian population, but past
figures show 1 million Arabs in the West Bank and 700,000 in the
Gaza Strip.
   At least 80 percent of the settlers are commuters who take
advantage of government-subsidized housing in settlements near
Israel, observers said.
   Arnon said that among many committed Jews, the uprising actually
provided an incentive to move into the territories.
   ``Many people who were unsure of whether to move into a
settlement or not did so last year because of the security
problems,'' he said. ``Whoever thinks the nation of Israel is
moving out of here had better wake up.''
   The United States considers the more than 130 Jewish settlements
in the occupied territories an obstacle to peace. U.S. policy calls
on Israel to give up occupied land, seized from Jordan and Egypt in
the 1967 Middle East war, in exchange for peace.
   Meron Benvenisti of the independent West Bank Data Base Project
said his figures showed the settler population was closer to 74,000
at the end of last year, up from 67,000 in 1987.
   Benvenisti said his figures are higher because the government
does not take into account Israelis who move to settlements without
legally changing their addresses so their children can attend
better schools in Israel.
   He said the growth was abetted by new roads built by the army
that made commuting faster and avoided Arab towns.
</TEXT>
