<HEAD>Thunderstorms Sweep Desert Southwest</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with quotes, detail from storms
in California, Arizona. PICKS UP 6th graf pvs, `Elsewhere, showers...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms rumbled across the deserts of California, Nevada
and western Arizona early today, flooding homes and roads, causing
mudslides and setting palm trees on fire with lightning.
   Yuma, Ariz., received 3{ inches of rain Wednesday night, 1{
times its normal rainfall for the entire year. It was the second
major rainfall in two weeks in a town where the average annual
rainfall is one of the lowest in the nation _ a little more than 2{
inches.
   The thunderstorm began with gusty winds that stirred up dust and
sand and reduced visibility to half a mile at times. The heavy rain
that followed further reduced visibility to a few hundred feet.
   The storm severed communications in much of Yuma, damaged a key
water main and caused mudslides and major flooding. About a foot of
water covered the runway at the airport.
   ``Most of our roads are gone. Lots of homes have water in them
and we've got poles and wires down,'' said sheriff's Deputy Kevin
Kretchmer. Some cars were washed away by floodwaters, but all
motorists were believed safe, he said.
   The Red Cross opened a shelter in a National Guard armory and
took in more than 40 residents of a flooded area, officials said.
   In east-central California, roads in the Benton area of Mono
County had to be closed after they were covered with water 2 feet
deep. Some people had to be rescued by helicopter, officials said.
   In the desert resort of Palm Springs, Calif., several palm trees
caught fire from lightning bolts and power was knocked out in some
areas when the storm rumbled through late Wednesday, said police
Sgt. Mike McCracken.
   Elsewhere, showers and thunderstorms were widely scattered over
western sections of the central Plains, especially near the
Kansas-Colorado line. Showers also extended along coastal sections
of the south Atlantic states.
   High pressure over the north Atlantic states dominated the
weather across most of the eastern half of the nation. Skies were
clear early today from New England across the Ohio and Tennessee
Valleys to much of Texas.
   Today's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstorms
from Florida to the southern and Middle Atlantic coast states;
showers and thunderstorms across the Rockies, the central and
southern Plateau and the Desert Southwest; and sunshine throughout
the rest of the nation.
   Temperatures were forecast to be in the 70s from the upper Ohio
Valley across the Appalachians to much of the Atlantic coast; in
the 60s or 70s along the Pacific Coast; in the 90s over the Florida
Peninsula, southern Texas, portions of the northern Plains, the
southern Plateau and interior valleys of California and Oregon;
above 100 degrees over the Desert Southwest; and in the 80s
throughout the rest of the nation.
   Temperatures at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 46 degrees at Bradford,
Pa., to 85 degrees at Phoenix.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 65 foggy; Boston 60 fair; Buffalo 57 fair;
Charleston, S.C. 67 cloudy; Cincinnati 58 fair; Cleveland 59 fair;
Detroit 63 fair; Miami 79 fair; New York 67 cloudy; Philadelphia 62
partly cloudy; Pittsburgh 55 fair; Portland, Maine 54 fair;
Washington, D.C. 66 cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 66 fair; Denver 68 partly cloudy; Des Moines
66 fair; Fort Worth 64 fair; Indianapolis 58 fair; Kansas City 66
fair; Nashville 63 fair; New Orleans 65 fair; Oklahoma City 65
partly cloudy; St. Louis 67 fair; Minneapolis@St. Paul 63 fair; San
Antonio 71 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 68 cloudy; Anchorage 57 cloudy; Boise 72
fair; Honolulu 78 partly cloudy; Las Vegas 80 partly cloudy; Los
Angeles 66 foggy; Phoenix 84 cloudy; Salt Lake City 74 cloudy; San
Diego 69 cloudy; San Francisco 56 fair; Seattle 56 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 57 fair; Toronto 66 partly cloudy.
