<FIRST>u a PM-ABA-FlagBurning     08-10 0206</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-ABA-Flag Burning,0212</SECOND>
<HEAD>ABA Opposes Any Amendment to Ban Flag-Burning</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Bar Association's policy-making
body has voted to oppose the adoption of a constitutional amendment
against desecrating the flag.
   The resolution, adopted in a voice vote Wednesday by the
459-member House of Delegates at the ABA's annual meeting, said the
ABA was acting ``in the interest of preserving intact the right to
freedom of speech and expression.''
   The ABA also said it opposes any federal legislation making it a
crime to desecrate the American flag as a political protest.
   At the same time, the ABA declared the flag a ``revered national
symbol that ought to be treated with great respect by all citizens
of the United States of America.''
   The resolution is in response to calls by many, including
President Bush, for a constitutional amendment against defiling the
flag.
   That call came after the U.S. Supreme Court ruled in a Texas
case in June that flag-burning is protected under the First
Amendment guarantee of free speech.
   A report by an ABA task force supporting the resolution quoted
the 18th century French philosopher Voltaire: ``I disapprove of
what you say, but I will defend to the death your right to say it.''
</TEXT>
