<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 1340EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-ArmsTalks     08-10 0442</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arms Talks,0458</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Talks Set Before Foreign Ministers Meet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY CZUCZKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S.-Soviet negotiations on chemical weapons will
resume next week, an American diplomat said Thursday.
   A Soviet official said new agreements could be reached in the
10-day round, but the U.S. assessment was more cautious.
   The talks are aimed at setting joint inspections of each side's
chemical arms sites and settling disputes over how to monitor
stockpiles.
   The superpowers say such moves will help speed the Geneva talks
on a global ban of the weapons, where verification long has been a
point of disagreement.
   U.S.-Soviet talks were expected to resume in the fall. Now, the
new round precedes next month's meeting between Secretary of State
James A. Baker III and Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze
in the United States.
   In the round, ``the Soviet delegation intends to complete the
development of an agreement on those areas where positions of the
U.S.S.R. and U.S.A are close,'' Moscow's chief envoy Sergei
Batsanov told the 40-nation Conference on Disarmament.
   The conference has been debating a worldwide ban on the
production, stockpiling and use of chemical weapons for 21 years.
   U.S. envoy Max Friedersdorf said negotiators will ``make every
effort'' to build the last round's progress and finish draft
agreements in the new session, set for Aug. 15-24.
   But he said ``some big divergences'' remain and refused to
predict whether work could be completed.
   After the last round, both sides reported agreement on
principles governing on-the-spot inspections. They said more work
was needed on other issues, including an exchange of stockpile data
and the timing of inspections.
   Moscow removed a main obstacle last month by accepting the U.S.
position that inspections begin even while a global chemical arms
ban is being drafted.
   Geneva negotiators will seek to work out a detailed accord on
this point, Friedersdorf said in an interview.
   He said the Soviet shift was ``an important step ... but as far
as getting a worldwide ban, it doesn't move the process forward as
much as we would like.''
   ``In the overall picture, we've still got a long way to go,'' he
said.
   Batsanov said early inspections ``would be a very serious
confidence-building measure'' and foster ``openness and
transparency in the military field.''
   The United States and Soviet Union have the world's biggest
chemical arsenals.
   Through inspections of Soviet sites, U.S. officials say they
want to verify Moscow's claims it has no more than 50,000 tons of
chemical armaments. Some Western analysts have said the actual
stockpile is more than six times bigger.
   Neither side has given firm indications when data exchanges or
inspections could begin.
</TEXT>
