<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--EarringFlap     08-10 0180</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Earring Flap,0183</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Fired for Wearing Diamond Stud</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLOVIS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A water entertainment park, Wild Water
Adventures, has fired a male employee for wearing a diamond stud in
his left ear.
   Ted Hallisey, 27, said Wednesday he plans to file complaints
with the American Civil Liberties Union and the state Department of
Fair Housing, but an official of the state agency doubted that the
case will be investigated.
   ``In the state of California, an employer can have reasonable
grooming standards,'' said Gus Oliveira, district administrator of
the fair employment agency. ``As long as they are not burdensome
and are enforced equally, they are lawful.''
   Hallisey, a Fresno State University student, contended that it
is unfair to let women employees wear earrings and not men. The
employee handbook at Wild Water Adventures, outside Fresno, allows
women who watch over the water rides or sell refreshments to wear
post earrings, but bans them on male employees.
   ``We don't let men wear dresses here either,'' said park
spokeswoman Kathy Siggers. ``We try to maintain a traditional,
conservative dress code.''
</TEXT>
