<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Mikeska     08-10 0189</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Mikeska,0196</SECOND>
<HEAD>Taylor Restaurateur Who Served Barbecue To Presidents Dies at 68</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAYLOR, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rudy Mikeska, a restaurateur who over more
than three decades served barbecue to presidents, governors and
millions of others, has died of cancer. He was 68.
   The Mikeska family was cited by Texas Monthly magazine in 1986
as ``The First Family of Texas Barbecue.''
   Mikeska, who died Wednesday at his home in this town near
Austin, served Presidents Lyndon Johnson and Gerald Ford, former
Govs. Preston Smith and Dolph Briscoe, and catered both of
incumbent Gov. Bill Clements' inaugural dinners.
   He once catered a meal for 18,000 people at the South Texas
Nuclear Project, a nuclear power plant, according to Mikeska's son,
Tim Mikeska.
   The younger Mikeska estimated that 5 million people have been
served by the restaurant in Taylor in the last 16 years.
   Mikeska's has four custom-made barbecue pits that can cook 66
10-pound briskets at once. The restaurant can prepare food for more
than 2,000 people per hour, Tim Mikeska said.
   Survivors include his wife and two daughters and one son.
   A funeral Mass is scheduled Sunday in Taylor.
</TEXT>
