<FIRST>r a AM-Swindall-Sentence     08-10 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Swindall-Sentence,0250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: At Least Three Years In Jail Recommended for Swindall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal probation officer has recommended that
former Rep. Pat Swindall serve at least three years in prison for
his conviction on nine counts of lying to a federal grand jury, a
newspaper reports.
   The Fulton County Daily Report said the officer, Riley Erwin,
determined under federal sentencing guidelines that the minimum
sentence would fall into the 37- to 46-month range. The guidelines
do not allow for parole or a suspended sentence.
   The newspaper, which reports largely for the county's legal and
legislative community, said U.S. Attorney Robert Barr, initially
unaware of the confidentiality of Erwin's preliminary report,
confirmed its contents.
   But Barr said Thursday: ``I am aware of the report but I can
neither confirm or deny its contents.''
   He said, however, that the sentencing formula is ``no big
secret'' and anybody could sit down with the guidelines, which are
public, and the convictions and arrive at the same conclusion.
   Swindall, a Georgia Republican, was found guilty of nine perjury
charges related to testimony involving his attempt to negotiate an
$850,000 home loan from an undercover agent posing as a money
launderer.
   Swindall, who lost his 4th District seat to former actor Ben
Jones last November while under indictment on the charges, was
convicted June 21. Sentencing is set for Aug. 28.
   Barr said his office has not made a sentencing recommendation
but expects to do so soon.
</TEXT>
