<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Temple     08-10 0435</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Temple,0448</SECOND>
<HEAD>Extremists Demand Entry to Temple Mount As Jews Mourn</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM RON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 40 ultra-nationalist Jews demanded entry
to the Temple Mount on Thursday as thousands of other Israelis
recited lamentations on a holy day marking the tragedies that
befell the Jewish people.
   The day of mourning is known as Tisha Be-Av, or the ninth of the
Jewish lunar month of Av, the greatest day of mourning in the
Jewish calendar. Jews traditionally pray on the day at the Western
Wall of the Mount, the last remant of the ancient Jewish temple.
   Members of the extremist Temple Mount Faithful and the
ultra-nationalist Tehiya party demonstrated at the foot of the
Temple Mount, demanding they be allowed to pray on the hilltop,
which contains two Moslem mosques.
   ``Arabs are allowed into the site in their thousands, but Jews
are humiliated and made to go up five by five,'' one demonstrator
shouted.
   Police armed with riot-control gear blocked the demonstrators
from entering the mount except in groups of five, escorted by
officers, to avoid clashes between Jews and Moslems.
   ``We are in total control of the situation,'' said police
spokesman Avi Zelba.
   The Temple Mount is a site of religious significance to both
Jews and Moslems. The Western Wall at the base is the last remnant
of the temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 A.D.
   The mount is known as Haram Al-Sharif, or Noble Sanctuary, to
Moslems. It is administered by Moslem religious authorities and
houses the Al Aqsa Mosque and the Dome of the Rock, revered as the
site of Mohammed's ascent to heaven.
   The Jewish extremists built a monument to ``Jewish victims of
Arab terror'' at the entrance to the mount after police refused to
allow them to erect it in the walled compound.
   The mount has been the site of clashes between Moslem extremists
and police in the course of the 20-month Palestinian uprising
against Israeli occupation.
   It is situated in Jerusalem's Old City, captured by Israel from
Jordan in the 1967 Middle East war.
   Nearby, crowds of Jewish worshipers sat next to the sacred
Western Wall praying and reciting lamentations as they passed 24
hours of fasting. Sitting on the ground is a custom meant to
display sorrow.
   Tisha Be-Av commemorates the destruction of the first temple in
Jerusalem by the Babylonians in 586 B.C., as well as the
destruction on the second temple.
   Tisha Be-Av last 24 hours. Entertainment sites are closed by
law, while radio stations replace popular tunes with melancholy
music and programs devoted to the significance of the holiday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
