<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 1415EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     08-10 0606</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0622</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sinhalese Radicals Attack Police Station, Kill 2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sinhalese radicals stormed a police
station in a seaside resort Thursday, killed two policemen and
escaped with 17 automatic guns, military officials said.
   Elsewhere, 16 more people were killed in Tamil and Sinhalese
ethnic violence since Wednesday, said the officials, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   They said 25 radicals from the People's Liberation Front took
part in the dawn attack on the police station in Bentota, a popular
resort 45 miles south of Colombo.
   The militants arrived in two vans, threw grenades, opened fire
on guards and fled with the weapons, the officials said.
   On Wednesday, members of the front shot and killed a Sinhalese
soldier's mother and three sisters in the southern Kalutara
district, the officials said. Also in Kalutara, three civilians
were killed by the radicals, they said.
   In the north-central town of Polonnaruwa, soldiers shot to death
a radical fleeing a search operation, the officials said. Three
civilians were killed in the last 24 hours in that town, they said.
   The government blames the left-wing radicals for 4,000 killings
since they launched an anti-government campaign two years ago to
protest the Indian peacekeeping soldiers in the northeast. Indian
soldiers were deployed under an Indian-Sri Lankan peace accord to
disarm Tamil militants who had agreed to end an insurgency for an
independent nation.
   While all rebel groups surrendered arms, the dominant Liberation
Tigers of Tamil Eelam reneged on the pact, signed on July 29, 1987,
and began attacking Indian soldiers. At least 1,000 Indian soldiers
have died in ongoing fighting. About 10,000 Sri Lankans have died
in the six-year separatist war.
   Indian soldiers shot and killed five Tamil Tigers on Wednesday
in Jaffna in the north and Batticaloa in the east, the military
officials said.
   President Ranasinghe Premadasa had asked India to withdraw its
soldiers by July 29 to appease the Sinhalese militants and the
Tamil Tigers who had started negotiating with the government.
   The deadline was rejected by Indian Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi,
sparking a diplomatic dispute between the countries. Gandhi said he
will order the troops home only when security for the Tamils in the
northeast is assured.
   A showdown was averted when Premadasa sent his Foreign Minister
Ranjan Wijeratne on July 29 for talks in New Delhi on the
withdrawal of the estimated 45,000 soldiers.
   Since the talks began, India withdrew 2,220 soldiers and said it
will pull out the rest in phases by February. Premadasa, however,
said they should leave by the middle of September.
   Wijeratne said that during the New Delhi talks, both sides
agreed a peace committee should oversee security for all
communities in the north and east. The proposed committee would
include representatives of all former Tamil rebel groups and would
be headed by a government minister, he said.
   The other terms for a withdrawal that were worked out during the
New Delhi talks were being studied by the government and the
opposition parties, he said.
   ``If the government accepts the package ... then the cease-fire
(between Indian soldiers and Tamil Tigers) and the induction of the
Tamil Tigers into the peace committee can be worked out,'' he said.
   Tamils, who form 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people,
demand a separate nation, citing discrimination by the majority
Sinhalese in jobs and education. Sinhalese make up 75 percent of
the population and control the government and the military.
   India became involved in the ethnic problems of its southeastern
neighbor because of the sympathies of its own 60 million Tamils for
the rebel cause.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
