<FIRST>r w AM-Iran-Contra     08-10 0465</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Contra,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutors Seek To Make Iran-Contra Court Session Public</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors said Thursday that an Aug. 23
court session regarding the Iran-Contra criminal case against a
former CIA station chief should be open to the public.
   In court papers, the office of independent counsel Lawrence
Walsh said the legal arguments before the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals may determine whether Joseph Fernandez will be put on
trial. Also at stake is the ability of Walsh's office to conduct
its work free from interference by the Justice Department, the
prosecutors' papers said.
   The Justice Department, over the objections of the independent
counsel, is taking legal questions concerning classified
information in the Fernandez case to the appeals court in Richmond,
Va.
   The independent counsel is objecting to the appeal, saying the
Justice Department's action in effect would wrest control of the
case from Walsh's office.
   The appeals court has scheduled a closed hearing.
   Fernandez, the spy agency's former station chief in Costa Rica,
is the highest ranking CIA officer ever indicted, associate
independent counsel Laurence Shtasel said in a nine-page brief.
   ``The First Amendment interest in judicial openness is
particularly apparent in the circumstances of this unusual
appeal,'' said the papers filed with the appeals court.
   ``Parts of the government are pitted against each other over the
ultimate issue of who will control this prosecution,'' the
prosecutors noted.
   Also involved in the legal battle, said the prosecution, is the
independent counsel's ability to prosecute government officials,
including those in the CIA, ``in a manner unrestrained by the
Department of Justice.''
   U.S. District Court Judge Claude Hilton in Alexandria, Va.,
decided last month that Fernandez is entitled to disclose as part
of his defense the locations of CIA stations in El Salvador and
Honduras and a third CIA facility in a Latin American country.
   The judge also said Fernandez may disclose details of secret CIA
programs in Costa Rica which prosecutors said were initiated at the
request of that country's government.
   The projects are a sophisticated communications station,
assistance to Costa Rica's defense forces and a program dealing
with Nicaraguan nationals in Costa Rica to enhance that country's
preparation for possible aggressive action by Nicaragua.
   The Justice Department, acting on behalf of the CIA, objected to
making detailed disclosure about the stations and programs and
announced it would appeal Hilton's rulings.
   Walsh's office says the department's only course of action is to
file an affidavit prohibiting disclosure of the information on
national security grounds. That could lead to dismissal of some or
all of the criminal charges against Fernandez.
   Walsh's office could then file its own appeal with the appeals
court.
   The Justice Department is reluctant to take the drastic step of
filing a potentially case-killing affidavit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
