<FIRST>r w AM-US-PLO     08-10 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-PLO,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Department Questions PLO's Intentions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department said Thursday a Palestine
Liberation Organization statement raises questions about the
group's ``commitment to accommodation, understanding and peace.''
   Spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler commented in response to a
question about the statement by the Fatah, the main group of the
PLO, at a meeting in Tunisia.
   Delegates to the fifth congress of the Fatah approved a
resolution calling for ``intensification of the armed struggle and
all other forms of battle to put an end to the Israeli occupation
of Palestinian territories.''
   The Fatah resolution, distributed by the Palestinian news agency
WAFA, did not say what kind of military operations might be
conducted outside the occupied lands or define ``all other forms of
battle.''
   Hard-liners had pressed the congress to recommend extending the
armed struggle beyond the West Bank and Gaza. PLO leader Yasser
Arafat's declaration that military action would be confined to the
occupied territories had helped persuade the Bush administration to
open a dialogue with the PLO.
   At the State Department, Ms. Tutwiler said: ``The political
program ... raises questions about Fatah's commitment to
accommodation, understanding and peace. This statement's derogatory
rhetoric on Israel, its tone of confrontation and violence and its
preference for unrealistic principles and solutions instead of
practical ideas for peace are unhelpful.''
   Under Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's election plan for
the area, Palestinian delegates would be chosen to negotiate with
Israel.
   Fatah said elections must be held in ``a democratic atmosphere
under international supervision after the withdrawal of Israeli
forces ... as part of a global plan for a definitive solution to
the Israeli-Arab conflict.''
