<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 1645EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-TreasuryAuction     08-10 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Treasury Auction,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yields Still Falling</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also on financial circuits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yields on 30-year Treasury bonds fell in
Thursday's auction to the lowest level in nearly three years as the
government completed a series of huge debt auctions intended to
raise $44.5 billion this week.
   The average yield was 8.14 percent, down from 9.11 percent at
the last auction on May 11.
   It was the lowest rate since 30-year bonds averaged 7.54 percent
on Nov. 6, 1986. The bonds will carry a coupon interest rate of 8[
percent with each $10,000 in face value selling for $9,983.30.
   A total of $9.75 billion in bonds were sold out of bids totaling
$20.1 billion.
   In addition, the Treasury on Thursday auctioned special
short-term debt securities totaling $15 billion which will include
the first $5 billion raised to pay for the savings and loan bailout.
   The 247-day bills, which the government must repay on April 19,
have an average yield of 8.36 percent.
   Thursday's auctions followed the sale of $10.03 billion in
three-year notes with an average yield of 7.93 percent on Tuesday
and $$9.76 billion in 10-year notes with an average yield of 8.03
percent on Wednesday.
   The auctions are part of the regular sales done once every three
months to roll over the government's debt. This week's followed the
vote in Congress last week to raise the national debt limit by $70
billion to $2.87 trillion through Oct. 31. By then, Congress hopes
to complete work on a bill boosting the Treasury's permanent
borrowing authority to more than $3.1 trillion.
</TEXT>
