<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Arafat     08-10 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Arafat,0570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinians See Arafat With Freer Hand, Israel Sees Retreat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prominent Palestinians said Thursday that PLO
chief Yasser Arafat may have a more flexible hand in pursuing his
peace proposals after winning a vote of confidence from his Fatah
faction.
   But Israel's Foreign Ministry said decisions of the Fatah
General Congress this week represented a ``step backward'' from
moderation. A liberal Israeli newspaper, Haaretz, deplored the
group's insistence on continued armed struggle.
   The six-day meeting by more than 1,000 Fatah members, which
ended Thursday, overwhelmingly endorsed Arafat's policies, which
this year carried the Palestine Liberation Organization to official
recognition of Israel.
   It was seen by many mainstream Palestinians in the
Israeli-occupied territories as a triumph over hard-liners who have
opposed Arafat's turn to diplomacy in the PLO's efforts to win a
Palestinian state.
   ``I think he's been given a free hand,'' said George Jakaman,
professor of philosophy at the West Bank's Bir Zeit University.
   Daoud Kuttab, a prominent Palestinian journalist, said,
``Arafat's maneuverability has been enhanced, both in the political
resolutions and in the persons elected to top positions in Fatah.''
   Radwan Abu Ayyash, a Fatah supporter and head of the Arab
Journalists Association, said in an interview that ``one of the
reasons such a (meeting) was held was to give Arafat more support,
more credibility among his own people in order to move ahead.''
   Kuttab said Arafat's victory over hard-liners ``signals to the
smaller factions and to adversaries ... that when Arafat is
talking, he's talking with the support of the vast majority of
Palestinians.''
   Kuttab said the decisions give Arafat greater power to explore
Israel's proposal for elections in the occupied West Bank and Gaza
Strip.
   The Fatah meeting left open the possibility of elections after
an Israeli troop withdrawal from the territories.
   Israel's government approved a plan in May that calls for
Palestinians in the occupied lands to choose representatives who
will negotiate limited autonomy as an interim solution. Final
disposition of the West Bank and Gaza would be left until later.
   ``If Arafat wanted tommorrow to name a delegation ... to make
initial negotiations with the Israelis, he can do this with more
confidence than he could before,'' Kuttab said.
   That prospect worries Palestinian leftists, who fear Arafat has
given up too much by accepting Israel and by restricting
Palestinian guerrilla activity to military targets and Israeli-held
territory.
   Hard-liners at the Fatah congress won a call for ``the
intensification of the armed struggle ... to put an end to the
Israeli occupation of Palestinian territories.''
   That reiteration of Fatah's traditional path of guerrilla
action, launched by Arafat and a handful of colleagues in 1964,
chilled Israeli views of the conference.
   Despite widespread recognition of the PLO as the representive of
the world's 5 million Palestinians, Israel has outlawed any
dealings with the PLO, claiming the organization is a terrorist
entity.
   ``Part of what they call armed struggle, we call terrorism,''
said Israeli Foreign Ministry Spokesman Alon Liel.
   He noted the Fatah statements did not explicitly repeat Arafat's
Dec. 14 declaration renouncing terrorism, recognizing Israel and
accepting a U.N. resolution endorsing a land-for-peace trade with
Israel.
   Israeli officials claims that Fatah has launched 11 attacks and
attempted attacks in Israel since December, casting doubt on its
renunciation of terror.
</TEXT>
