<FIRST>r a AM-People     08-10 0944</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People,0986</SECOND>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Malcolm Forbes will celebrate his 70th birthday
with a $2 million bash at his palace in Tangiers, Morocco,
according to a published report.
   Elizabeth Taylor, Lee Iacocca, Barbara Walters and Henry
Kissinger are among the 650 guests invited to the party on the
weekend of Aug. 18, the magazine USA Weekend reported in its Aug.
11-13 edition.
   The tab for the Forbes magazine publisher will include 410 hotel
rooms, two chartered jets, bagpipers and belly dancers, it was
reported.
   ``No matter how you're entertaining, do it the way you'd enjoy
going to a party,'' said Forbes. ``If you have fun, everyone else
will.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hours before being rushed to the hospital
with chest pains, popular 1950s and '60s television personality Art
Linkletter went ahead and appeared on ``The Pat Sajak Show'' even
though he was already feeling ill, spokesmen said.
   The 77-year-old humorist, whose ``Art Linkletter's House Party''
was television's longest-running daytime variety show, was taken by
ambulance to the University of California, Los Angeles, Medical
Center on Wednesday night. He was held for observation and tests,
said nursing supervisor Susan Davidson.
   ``He is fully alert, talking and laughing,'' Ms. Davidson said.
   Linkletter was stricken soon after appearing on CBS' ``The Pat
Sajak Show,'' and had been feeling ill before he taped the show,
said Sajak spokesman Bob Burton.
   ``Art is the definition of a trouper,'' Sajak said in a
statement. ``He was obviously in some discomfort, but he performed
beautifully.''
   Rich Elbaum, another spokesman at the hospital, said doctors had
not immediately determined if Linkletter had suffered a heart
attack. He was listed in fair condition.
   The entertainer was stricken at his house in the exclusive Bel
Air area about 7 p.m.
   Linkletter was host of several popular radio and TV shows,
including ``Art Linkletter's House Party'' and ``People Are
Funny.'' The ``House Party'' began as a radio show in 1944 and
moved to television in 1952. It stayed on the air until 1969,
setting a longevity record for shows of its type.
   His books ``Kids Say The Darndest Things'' _ based on interviews
with youngsters down on his ``House Party'' _ and ``Old Age Is Not
For Sissies'' were best-sellers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Miss America Bess Myerson and her
boyfriend, Carl Capasso, who recently finished a two-year prison
term for tax evasion, aren't living together but are still a
twosome, Capasso says.
   ``I'm a single parent in an apartment with kids in it and she
has her own apartment. We live separately but we're together,''
Capasso told the New York Post in an interview published Thursday.
   Asked about marriage, Capasso grinned and said, ``Listen, that's
the one thing that could break up any relationship.''
   The couple were acquitted Dec. 22 on charges they tried to have
Capasso's divorce payments to his former wife, Nancy, reduced by
giving a job to the divorce judge's daughter in Myerson's office.
   Myerson was the city's commissioner for cultural affairs.
   In Thursday's editions, Post columnist Cindy Adams reported that
while Capasso, a sewer contractor, was in prison, Myerson would
bring his teen-age son and daughter to see him.
   Asked about his jail time, Capasso said, ``Where I was is not a
rock pile. They don't pick pieces out of your skin. But make no
mistake about it, it's jail.
   ``In order to get through it, you have to intellectualize above
it. ... But the depression and oppression, the constant sublimating
depletes your energy. It's exhausting.''
   Capasso was released June 26 from a halfway house in Manhattan.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OLYMPIA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dan Evans, a former U.S. senator and
three-term governor, will begin doing television and radio
commentary in Seattle later this month.
   Evans said his commentaries will be based on his experiences in
politics and said they ``will give me a chance to add to the
intelligence of political dialogue.''
   The 63-year-old Evans was Washington governor from 1965 to 1977,
then served six years as president of Evergreen State College.
   In 1983, he was appointed to the U.S. Senate to replace the late
Sen. Henry ``Scoop'' Jackson, and he won a special election that
fall to serve out Jackson's term. But he opted not to seek a full
term last year.
   Evans said his commentaries will run about 1{ minutes two or
three times a week on the Seattle CBS affiliate, KIRO television;
and on radio stations KIRO-AM and KSEA-FM. He said he will also
take part in covering political stories.
   ``I'll probably be the color man on election nights and during
other political doings,'' he said.
   Since returning from Washington and a fellowship at Harvard,
Evans has joined the boards of Washington Mutual Savings Bank and
McCaw Communications, a cellular telephone and pager company.
</TEXT>
