<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Strike 1stLd-Writethru   08-10 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Strike, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0575,0606</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strikers Say Walkout Spreading in Estonia, 20,000 Reported Out</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with parliament passing resolution
suspending strikes; pickup 5th pvs, `Kopykin said...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAREY GOLDBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Walkouts spread Thursday in Estonia to include up
to 20,000 workers, and protest leaders said they had no plans to
call off the 2-day-old protest against a new election law, reports
from the Baltic republic said.
   In a bid to stop the strike, the Estonian parliament passed a
resolution Thursday suspending all strikes at enterprises and
organizations in Estonia, Tass reported.
   The official news agency said the decree would take effect as
soon as it was published and directed the government to ``ensure
uninterrupted functioning of the Estonian economy and services to
the population.''
   The strike by non-Estonian workers was sparked by a new law that
tightens residency requirements for voting and holding office.
Non-Estonian residents of the republic complain that the law, which
was passed Tuesday by the republic's parliament, is aimed against
them because many are new arrivals.
   An editor at Estonian Radio, Maarika Saarna, put the number of
strikers at 20,000 but cautioned it could be exaggerated because it
was based largely on reports from the strikers themselves.
   Strike committee member Artur Kopykin refused to estimate the
number of strikers but said 37 enterprises had joined the walkout.
On Wednesday, 22 enterprises were reported on strike, including
shipyards and a motor works.
   Kopykin said the government had not begun negotiations with
strikers and ``has made no move to come toward us.''
   ``Until the government starts negotiations, there can be no talk
about stopping the strike,'' he said by telephone from Tallinn, the
republic's capital.
   Saarna said strike agitators were trying to stir up non-Estonian
workers by warning them they would soon be treated as badly as
blacks under apartheid in South Africa.
   ``If you tell a rather illiterate person that this is our last
chance and otherwise we'll be kicked out, of course he'll strike,''
she said in a telephone interview. ``
   The government newspaper Izvestia reported Thursday that
``alienation is growing between two groups of the population in
Estonia.''
   It said that on Tallinn's central square, Estonians have set up
a protest mourning the death of an Estonian who was killed Saturday
night in a drunken brawl with a Russian. They hold signs saying
``On this spot, a drunken Russian from Moscow killed an Estonian
boy,'' Izvestia said.
   Yevgeny Kogan, an ethnic Russian and leader of the InterMovement
group that lobbies for non-Estonians' interests, said strikers were
demanding the republic's parliament reconsider ``discriminative''
parts of the law on elections and another law making Estonian the
republic's official language.
   He said in an interview Thursday the new election law would
deprive tens of thousands of people of the right to vote. The new
law requires that candidates for elective office live in the same
place for five years, or in Estonia for 10 years. Voters must have
lived in the same district for two years or in Estonia for five.
   Kopykin claimed the strike had virtually paralyzed the railroads
in Estonia and had spread to the construction industry.
   Some disruption in morning bus traffic was reported in Tallinn,
but drivers were brought in from out of town to fill in, Saarna
said.
   Ethnic Estonians make up slightly more than 60 percent of the
population, and pushed the law to protect themselves from an influx
of other nationalities. Russians make up about a third of Estonia's
1.6 million people.
</TEXT>
