<DOCNO> AP890810-0120 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 2112EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Beans     08-10 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Beans,0471</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farmer's First State-Certified Organic Crop Accidentally Sprayed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROYAL CITY, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A farmer who spent years developing a
crop of organically grown beans saw his effort wasted in a few
airplane passes when his field was accidentally sprayed with
pesticides.
   ``In my mind, the beans are not only ruined, but the ground is
contaminated,'' said Peter Eriksen, who has been farming pinto and
garden beans without chemicals for 13 years. ``This is quite
devastating to me.''
   Years of building the field's fertility, through the spreading
of manure and other organic means, were ruined, Eriksen said.
   ``I'm different than commercial chemical farmers in that I
consider the soil to be a biologically active, and it's a fact, not
just my belief,'' Eriksen said.
   The state Department of Agriculture, which started an organic
certification program last year, is investigating the accidental
spraying. Department officials say it will be three years before
they can once again certify crops grown on Eriksen's 60-acre
sprayed field as organic.
   ``That about makes me cry,'' Eriksen said.
   Eriksen was tending to his sloping field on the west end of this
central Washington town on July 18 when he noticed two low-flying
airplanes overhead.
   ``From my vantage point, I couldn't determine if he was spraying
on a neighbor's field or on my field. ... Then I could see when he
came around again that he was spraying in my field.''
   The second plane started spraying on the west side.
   Ericksen said he frantically waved his arms to signal one of the
pilots, but to no avail. He then picked up a 4-inch aluminum pipe
and began waving that. The planes finally flew away.
   Pilot Randy Ferguson of Stephens Flying Service, who was
contracted to spray neighboring farms, said he thought the farmer
was trying to warn him away from cattle.
   ``We were in an area where we normally don't fly. Beans look
like beans from an airplane,'' said Ferguson, who has been in the
business for 13 years and said he didn't know there were organic
crops in Grant County.
   The planes apparently mistook Eriksen's field for one a couple
of miles southwest.
   Eriksen said a Seattle insurance agent for the flying service
told him the maximum liability of the policy was $100,000. He said
he plans to file a lawsuit seeking ``well, well above that amount.''
   Eriksen estimated that his organic beans could have brought him
twice the price of a regular crop because of the growing demand for
pesticide-free foods. Carrie West of the agriculture department's
certification program advisory board agreed.
   There are 150 farmers, most in eastern Washington, who received
organic certification from the state Agriculture Department this
year, said program manager Verne Hedlund.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
