<FIRST>r a AM-Bonanno     08-10 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bonanno,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Says Bonanno Threw Posh Wedding After Lawyer Paid By Taxpayers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Derald in 3rd graf is cq.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The son of a reputed Mafia boss threw a
$72,000 wedding party ``worthy of royalty'' for his daughter, just
three months after taxpayers picked up the tab for his attorney's
fee, prosecutors said.
   Salvatore ``Bill'' Bonanno had claimed he was too poor to pay
his attorney $19,250 for appealing his convictions in a
home-improvement scam.
   The October 1988 wedding party came complete with filet mignon,
ice sculptures and a 14-piece orchestra, state Deputy Attorney
General Derald Granberg said in papers filed Wednesday in Superior
Court.
   Granberg, who successfully prosecuted Bonanno for bilking four
elderly Alameda County residents of more than $40,000 in the late
1970s, is objecting to Bonanno's latest attempt to avoid serving a
four-year term.
   ``This defendant belongs in state prison, it is as simple as
that,'' Granberg said.
   Bonanno, 57, is the son of reputed mob boss Joseph Bonanno Sr.
The younger Bonanno is scheduled to return to court Aug. 18, when
he is scheduled to begin serving his sentence. Superior Court Judge
Joseph Karesh is expected to decide between prison and probation.
   Karesh sentenced Bonanno in March 1986 for his convictions four
months earlier on eight counts of grand theft and conspiracy to
commit theft for the bogus home-improvement contracts.
   Bonanno, however, was allowed to remain free on $50,000 bail
while he unsucessfully appealed his convictions. Karesh then
ordered Bonanno to surrender June 16, but allowed a two-month delay
to help his 84-year-old father, who is facing charges of refusing
to testify before a federal grand jury in New York.
   But last month, Bonanno's lawyer, Charles Garry, asked Karesh to
modify the four-year sentence to probation. Garry said that since
the sentence, Bonanno has lived ``an utterly blameless life.''
   Granberg called Bonanno the ``dominant'' member of the
conspiracy and criticized Garry for accepting public funds to
represent Bonanno.
   Granberg said Bonanno is being sued by the Fairmont Hotel in San
Jose for failing to pay most of the $72,000 tab for the wedding
party of his daughter, Felippa.
   ``The conclusion suggested by this scenario is that the
defendant perpetrated a fraud upon either the (state) or the hotel
or both,'' Granberg said.
</TEXT>
