<FIRST>r w AM-HelmsleyLawyer     08-10 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Helmsley Lawyer,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defender in Helmsley Tax Case to Lead Federal Tax Prosecutors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the attorneys defending New York hotel
owner Leona Helmsley at her tax-evasion trial is expected to
oversee criminal tax prosecutions at the Justice Department,
sources said Thursday.
   James A. Bruton III is the choice of Assistant Attorney General
Shirley Peterson, head of the Justice Department's tax division, to
run the unit's criminal-tax section, said department sources, who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Bruton's appointment as deputy assistant attorney general is not
expected to be announced until after the conclusion of the New York
City trial of Mrs. Helmsley, who appears in advertisements as ``the
queen of the Helmsley Hotels.''
   Bruton is part of a four-attorney team defending charges that
Mrs. Helmsley and her husband, Harry, evaded payment of $1 million
of federal taxes by reporting $4 million worth of renovations on
their mansion as business expenses.
   During a break in his cross-examination of an IRS agent
testifying for the prosecution Thursday, Bruton said ``I can't
comment'' when asked about the expected appointment.
   The Helmsley case one of the most publicized criminal tax cases
brought by the Justice Department in recent years.
   Prosecutors charge the renovations on the Helmsleys' Greenwich,
Conn., estate that were written off as business expenses included
the installation of a marble dance floor and sound system to pipe
music to a barbecue pit.
   Mrs. Helmsley and her husband head a $5 billion hotel and real
estate empire. Helmsley, 80, is also charged but is not being tried
because he was declared mentally incompetent.
   The prosecution charged in its opening statement that Mrs.
Helmsley used the hotel business as ``a personal piggy bank,''
charging numerous personal purchases as business expenses,
including two jade figurines worth $500,000.
   A partner at the Washington law firm of Williams &amp; Connolly,
Bruton, 39, was a trial attorney in the Justice Department's tax
division from 1977 until 1981. Before that he worked two years in
the general counsel's office of the Internal Revenue Service.
   The prosecution is expected to rest its case early next week and
the case should go to a jury after a brief parade of defense
witnesses.
   Also on trial in U.S. District Court in Manhattan are former
Helmsley hotel executive Frank Turco and Joseph Licari, once a top
aide to Mr. Helmsley.
</TEXT>
