<DOCNO> AP890810-0124 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 1729EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Salvador     08-10 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador,0549</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Parties Promote Peace Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of a commission
promoting peace talks between the rightist government and
Marxist-led insurgents said Thursday they found good will and
determination to resolve the nearly 10-year-old war.
   The commission, which comprises the three main opposition
parties, spoke just hours after rebels used a dump truck to plow
through a sentry position and attack an army post in the capital's
northern sector.
   Officials of the Christian Democratic Party, the National
Reconciliation Party and the Democratic Convergence are included in
the commission.
   The Christian Democrats handed over power on June 1 to President
Alfredo Cristiani of the rightist Republican Nationalist Alliance,
or Arena, which won a landslide victory in March presidential
elections.
   Four rounds of negotiations between 1984 and 1987 failed to end
the civil war, in which about 70,000 people have died.
   In his inaugural address, Cristiani offered to talk with the
rebel Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front. But the insurgents
rejected the mechanism for dialogue _ a non-governmental commission
_ suggested by the new president.
   The rebels want direct high-level negotiations with the
government.
   ``We have found that the political will to dialogue exists on
both sides. There are points of agreement, but there is also
distance and mistrust,'' said oppositon leader Hugo Carrillo. ``We
of the opposition political parties are serving as promoters of
dialogue in an effort to narrow that difference.''
   Central American presidents who met earlier this week in Tela,
Honduras urged that Salvadoran peace negotiations be resumed.
   Commission members met in late July with rebel commanders in
Mexico City and this week with Cristiani. They said both sides
encouraged them to continue the effort to create conditions for
talks.
   They said they expected both sides to make ``concrete gestures''
to emphasize their dedication to achieving a negotiated peace.
Carrillo said the commission had not discussed with the two sides
what such measures might be.
   But Carrillo mentioned as possibilities a rebel cease-fire and
an end to a government attempt to pass laws considered repressive
by the opposition.
   Cristiani has said he plans to introduce draft legislation
giving the police, armed forces and courts a freer hand in moving
against suspected subversives. The oppositon and human rights
organizations have described the proposed measures as totalitarian.
   The rebel attack began at dawn at the army post in Mejicanos, in
northern San Salvador. Sgt. Arturo Melendez, post commander, said
one soldier and one civilian were wounded.
   Another guerrilla squad ambushed a truck carrying National Guard
members to reinforce the Mejicanos post, killing one trooper and
wounding two, authorities said.
   Melendez told journalists that about 30 insurgents fired
rocket-propelled grenades at the post and sprayed it with automatic
weapons fire.
   The attack began when guerrillas aboard a dump truck smashed
through a roadblock on the post's perimeter. The rebels also fired
grenades at the Mejicanos town hall, destroying its door.
   About 8,000 leftist rebels have waged a nearly decade-long
battle against the U.S.-backed governments in El Salvador. They say
they want to change the economic system that has enriched a tiny
minority while leaving most Salvadorans destitute.
</TEXT>
