<FIRST>r w AM-Soviet-Crops     08-10 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Crops,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ag Department Estimates Lower Soviet Grain Production</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Crop Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department on Thursday
estimated Soviet grain production this year at 200 million metric
tons, 10 million below earlier forecasts, and said there would be a
resulting rise in imports.
   The department estimated grain imports by the Soviets in the
year that began July 1 at 36 million tons, 3 million above previous
estimates.
   Hot and dry weather across many of the spring wheat-growing
regions of the Soviet Union combined with a shrinkage in the
growing area are causing the drop, according to a report from the
Foreign Agriculture Service.
   It estimated wheat production down 4.5 million tons to 87
million, while coarse grains decreased by 5.5 million to 100
million.
   Over the last 14 years, Soviet grain production fell to its
lowest level, 140.1 million metric tons, in 1975 and climbed to its
high of 237.4 million in 1978. Grain production reached 211.4
million in 1987 and 195.1 million last year.
   This year, favorable conditions across much of the European
portion of the Soviet Union have failed to fully offset hot and dry
weather baking out soil moisture from the eastern Urals to western
Sibera, USDA said. It said cooler weather and showers in the last
week came too late to rescue spring grains.
</TEXT>
