<FIRST>r w AM-Garcia-GOP     08-10 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Garcia-GOP,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four GOP Congressmen Donate to Garcia's Campaign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   WASHINGTON _ In an unusual show of bipartisanship, four New York
Republicans have contributed to the re-election campaign of Rep.
Robert Garcia, D-N.Y., who is under indictment in the Wedtech
bribery scandal.
   Two of the four _ Reps. Benjamin Gilman Frank Horton _ serve
with Garcia on the House Post Office and Civil Service Committee.
Gilman contributed $100; Horton, dean of the state's House
delegation, gave $1,000.
   Reps. Norman Lent and Amo Houghton also gave $1,000 each to
Garcia, according to the Bronx Democrat's latest campaign finance
report filed with the Federal Election Commission.
   Lent even sent a letter earlier this year to all 13 New York
House Republicans asking them to help with Garcia's legal defense,
said John Hambel, a spokesman for Lent.
   Although Michael Mensch, a spokesman for Garcia, agreed it was
unusual for Republicans to give financial support to a Democrat, he
said, ``Republicans don't run against Democrats in the South
Bronx.''
   ``It's not like they're operating against their own party,'' he
said.
   But Howard Schloss, spokesman for the Democratic Congressional
Campaign Committee, said Republicans ``have set out this grand
strategy to try to beat Democratic incumbents'' and called the
contributions ``very embarrassing.''
   Garcia faces trial Sept. 11 on felony charges that he and his
wife, Jane, accepted bribes of cash and jewelry worth $185,000 from
the Wedtech Corp., a New York military contractor. Garcia's former
House colleague, Mario Biaggi was convicted last year of taking
bribes from Wedtech and is serving an eight-year prison sentence in
Texas.
   Twenty Democratic members from outside New York also contributed
to Garcia's re-election campaign in the first six months of 1989,
according to the FEC report.
   Most of the $171,725 that Garcia's campaign collected between
Jan. 1 and June 30 has gone for his legal defense, according to the
report. Garcia reimbursed himself $130,000 in legal fees from the
campaign, the report says.
</TEXT>
