<DOCNO> AP890810-0131 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 1811EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-ShuttleProblem     08-10 0691</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shuttle Problem,0713</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jet Lands On Its Nose With Landing Gear Failure</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos BX4,5,6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nose of a Trump Shuttle jet skidded down a
runway, throwing out a spray of sparks and smoke, after the Boeing
727 landed Thursday with its nose landing gear still retracted.
   There were no injuries among the 47 passengers and seven
crewmembers on the Boeing 727, according to Trump Shuttle officials.
   ``It was like a roller coaster ride like at Coney Island, and I
enjoyed that. You prepare yourself for the worst. But it was really
just like a rough regular landing,'' said passenger Glenn Porter of
New York.
   ``The pilot did an outstanding job,'' FAA spokesman John Mogul
said. ``The pilot held the nose off the ground, then lowered the
nose slowly to the runway.''
   The pilot, Capt. Robert Smith, de-emphasized his efforts and
said 727s are ``fabulous'' aircraft.
   ``This was all in a day's work as far as I'm concerned,'' said
Smith, 47, a former Navy pilot.
   He flew for Eastern Airlines for 19 years before billionaire New
York City developer Donald Trump bought Eastern's Shuttle,
including planes and landing rights for $365 million, and
inaugurated service under his own name on June 8. The Shuttle
offers frequent service among Boston, New York and Washington.
   Trump flew into Boston for an afternoon news conference.
   ``I think the whole crew is made up of heroes,'' said Trump,
adding that he did not anticipate any negative customer reaction
over the incident.
   ``I think the public confidence might be greater because of our
crew,'' Trump said.
   The plane, coming from New York's LaGuardia Airport, circled
Boston for nearly an hour, dumping fuel over the ocean and flying
roller-coaster ``G-force'' maneuvers trying to shake the nose gear
loose. The jet also made one rough touch-and-go landing _ banging
the main landing gear onto the ground and taking off again _ in an
effort to jar the front landing gear loose from its housing.
   After circling several more times, Smith settled the main
landing gear onto the runway and held the nose up as long as he
could.
   ``The people in the front were screaming and yelling,'' said
James Moriarty of New York. The pilot ``said be prepared for metal
on concrete. So that's what we were preparing for. It wasn't that
bad, though. You felt like you were just waiting for the nose to
drop.''
   Many passengers said the scariest moments came after the
landing, when firefighters sprayed the plane with foam and they
rushed to slide down emergency chutes.
   It was the second emergency landing involving a landing gear
problem in a little over a week in the United States. On Aug. 2, a
Piedmont Airlines Boeing 737 with 100 people aboard scraped its
left wing and engine at Greensboro, N.C., after its left main
landing gear jammed. No one was injured.
   Trump Shuttle president Bruce Nobles said the jet involved in
Thursday's emergency landing had been in service since January
1970, but said age was an unlikely factor in the incident.
   The National Transportation Safety Board was investigating.
   Passengers aboard the Trump plane said they had plenty of
warning.
   ``When they first said they had problems, everybody was just
kind of joking about it,'' said Charlie Cormay of Sudbury. ``Once
we realized there was going to be a crash landing, everybody got
pretty solemn.''
   When the plane finally came in for its landing, Cormay said, ``a
few prayers'' went through his mind.
   ``They prepared us very well,'' said Kathy Hussey of New York
City, who had come to Boston for a business meeting. ``By the time
we landed, we were all very happy and relieved.''
   ``Suddenly you were on the runway with foam on your face and on
your back,'' she said, adding that she probably would take the
train back to New York.
   Passenger Moriarty said many of the travelers were on business,
which he credited with the calm atmosphere. ``They were thinking of
their business appointments,'' he said.
   However, he added: ``People were holding hands with strangers,
which I thought was a nice gesture.''
</TEXT>
