<DOCNO> AP890810-0133 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 1816EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Afghanistan     08-10 0516</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0535</SECOND>
<HEAD>General Says Soviets Supplying Advanced Aircraft</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union is supplying
Afghanistan with new MIG-29 fighters and the latest Sukhoi
ground-attack jets in case of an attack by Pakistan, an Afghan
general said Thursday.
   The communist government has repeatedly accused Pakistan,
Afghanistan's eastern neighbor, of direct involvement in the Afghan
civil war. The most active Moslem guerrilla groups are based there.
   Lt. Gen. Abdul Haq Ulumi, a member of the Supreme Military
Council, said the contract for MIG-29s and SU-27s ``has been
completed,'' but he would not give the number of aircraft.
   ``Soon they will come. We will use them if necessary,'' he said
in an interview with several Western television journalists.
   Yuli M. Vorontsov, the Soviet ambassador, said in June that the
Kremlin was ready to meet an Afghan request for MIG-29s and the
latest Sukhois if fighting and border violations increased.
   A U.S. official was quoted at the time as saying delivery of the
planes would raise ``very serious questions not simply about
Afghanistan, but about Soviet interest in improved relations with
the United States more generally.''
   The Soviets have complained publicly about increased U.S. arms
shipments to the insurgents.
   Moslem guerrillas began fighting after a communist coup in April
1978. Soviet military forces entered Afghanistan in December 1979
and completed a U.N.-mediated withdrawal a decade later, Feb. 15 of
this year.
   Washington accuses Moscow of nearly doubling arms shipments to
Afghanistan since the withdrawal.
   Last month, a U.S. official said the Soviets were shipping from
$2.5 billion to $3 billion worth of weapons a year to Afghanistan.
U.S. shipments to the guerrillas, via Pakistan, were valued at
slightly more than $600 million.
   Both nations are guarantors of the April 1988 agreement
providing for Soviet military withdrawal and an end to involvement
in Afghanistan. They regularly accuse each other of violating its
provisions.
   U.S. officials said last month American arms shipments to the
guerrillas would continue. They have been quoted as saying the
insurgents willl get new weapons to counter high-altitude bombing
attacks and disable runways at air bases.
   Ulumi, who represents the armed forces on the Communist Party
Central Committee, mentioned the aircraft when asked whether
Afghanistan would be getting new weapons.
   ``The Soviets have promised to give us new weapons,'' he said.
``These are aircraft which are to defend Afghanistan in the face of
a possible Pakistani air attack.''
   Asked what kind of aircraft, he replied: ``MIG-29s and SU-27s.
The numbers are secret. The contract has been completed.''
   Rockets hit Kabul for the seventh day in a row Thursday, killing
nine civilians, all but one at a bus stop near the airport, the
government said. Sixteen people were reported wounded.
   At least seven rockets struck near the airport and in
northwestern Kabul, said Mohammad Nabi Amani, the Foreign Ministry
spokesman.
   He said 16 rockets hit the capital Wednesday, killing one person
and wounding 15.
   In the past week, more than 150 surface-to-surface missiles have
landed in the city, killing 30 people and wounding about 140 by
government count.
</TEXT>
