<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Prison 1stLd-Writethru a0595 08-10 0572</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Prison, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0595,0591</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Congressmen, Back From Soviet Camp, Say Some Prisoners Political</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to SPECIFY time of prison camp visit, ADD background
of visit, earlier comments. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAREY GOLDBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two U.S. congressmen said Thursday their visit to
a prison camp in the Ural Mountains convinced them the Soviet Union
is still holding political prisoners.
   Reps. Frank Wolf, R-Va., and Christopher Smith, R-N.J., who
visited the Perm 35 labor camp on Wednesday and interviewed 24
prisoners, said they could not specify how many were being held for
their political beliefs.
   But Wolf said ``many or most said they were political
prisoners'' and ``we believe that they are.''
   The congressmen said inmates complained of the cold and
isolation, and were allowed few visits from relatives.
   ``They ought to close the camp down,'' Wolf said. ``It's a
terrible place and it ought not to exist.''
   Perm 35 is known for housing Soviet dissidents, including noted
human rights activist Natan Sharansky, who now lives in Israel.
   Smith said Tuesday that Perm 35 was ``notorious for ...
mistreatment, particularly of political prisoners.''
   Wolf and Smith said the camp clearly was spruced up for their
arrival, with fresh paint on many walls and flowers on cafeteria
tables.
   They also visited punishment cells where, they were told,
prisoners were kept with no bedding or warm clothes even in the
dead of winter.
   Former prisoners have said confinement at the camp, about 1,000
miles east of Moscow and 80 miles outside the industrial town of
Perm, included every-other-day rations of bread and gruel and new
punishments tacked onto their sentences.
   The congressmen, who are members of the Helsinki Commission,
said they would seek to have more delegations visit such camps to
assure that conditions were humane.
   Smith said he hoped that bringing ``glasnost to the Gulag,'' or
more openness to the prison camp system, would bring improvements
in camp life.
   Asked how he reconciled his findings with President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's denials that the Soviet Union still has political
prisoners, Smith said, ``I believe Mr. Gorbachev may have been
misled by his own people.''
   Human rights groups estimate about 100 political prisoners
remain in the Soviet Union, according to a State Department
official accompanying the congressmen.
   ``We think Mr. Gorbachev will use his immense political power to
see these people are released,'' Smith said.
   Smith and Wolf said they and several human rights groups are
pushing Soviet authorities to review the cases of the prisoners
they met. Many were convicted of treason or for trying to illegally
leave the Soviet Union.
   The congressmen said they expected the Soviets ``to clean up
their own act'' before the Helsinki Conference on Human Rights
convenes in Moscow in 1991.
   The two men went to Perm on their own initiative after broaching
the idea to a senior Soviet justice official six months ago in the
Netherlands. They were granted approval one day before the trip to
Perm was scheduled and made the visit on Wednesday.
   They said this week that they received official permission after
meeting with Interior Minister Vadim Bakatin and the Soviet Union's
chief prosecutor, Alexander Sukharev.
   Smith said they ``wanted to expose some of the horror of a
prison camp.''
   On Tuesday, in a telephone call from Moscow to Washington, Smith
said, ``Frank Wolf and I and the first two congressmen to go the
the Perm camp.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
