<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Soviet     08-10 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Soviet,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet TV Crew Filming in Israel on Unprecedented Visit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARJORIE OLSTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet television crew filming in Israel for
the first time in more than 20 years on Thursday toured the
occupied West Bank with an army patrol.
   The Soviet crew, led by correspondent Yevgeny Kiselev, also is
to interview Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, Foreign Minister Moshe
Arens and Finance Minister Shimon Peres before leaving.
   The Soviet Union severed diplomatic relations with Israel as a
show of solidarity with Arab nations following the 1967 Middle East
war.
   The visit by the television crew is another sign of thawing
relations between the two nations. They have exchanged consular
delegations over the last two years and have stepped up cultural
visits and tourism.
   In an interview with Israel television on Thursday, Kiselev
said, ``the intefadeh (Palestinian uprising) is the main story for
any TV company working in Jerusalem. But I want to show life in
Israel as well.''
   At least 535 Palestinians and 38 Israelis have died in the
20-month-old uprising against Israeli rule of the occupied West
Bank and Gaza Strip. Ninety-one Arabs have been killed by other
Arabs, allegedly because they collaborated with Israel.
   In his tour of the West Bank, Kiselev interviewed the military
governor of Nablus, Col. Shmuel Morgan, and later spoke to a
reserve soldier who emigrated from the Soviet Union nine years ago.
   Kiselev also visited an Israeli kibbutz, or communal farm, and
toured high technology industries.
   The series on Israel, to be broadcast on the Soviet news show
``Vremya,'' will also include a report on the progress of 61
victims of December's devastating Armenian earthquake who arrived
in Israel on June 27 for six weeks of medical treatment and
rehabilitation.
</TEXT>
