<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 1931EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Panama-US     08-10 0587</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama-US,0606</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Forces Hold Security Exercise Following Standoff</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALINA GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT AMADOR, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Marines stormed ashore and a
mechanized infantry battalion rumbled across the Panama Canal on
Thursday in a security exercise one day after a standoff between
U.S. and Panamanian forces.
   The exercise was the latest U.S. show of force in and around
Fort Amador, a base for both U.S. and Panamanian forces and site of
an office maintained by Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   ``The operation was designed to carry out certain functions in
keeping with the mission of the U.S. defense forces and the
protection of the Panama Canal, particularly testing troop
readiness and deployment capability,'' said Col. Ronald Sconyers,
reading a U.S. Southern Command news release.
   ``The purpose was also to reaffirm our treaty rights, including
the right of transit.''
   U.S. officials have said they plan to vigorously enforce canal
treaty rights, including responsibility for canal security.
Officials hope to show Panamanians, especially military officers
who might oust Noriega, how helpless the general is in the face of
U.S. power.
   Noriega, de facto leader of Panama through his command of the
Panamanian Defense Forces, has successfully resisted all U.S.
attempts to oust him since he was indicted on U.S. drug trafficking
charges in February 1988.
   Noriega denies the charges and says the U.S. efforts to remove
him are part of an effort to retain control of the canal, which the
United States has pledged to give to Panama at the end of 1999.
   U.S. troops arrested but later released 29 Panamanians on
Tuesday. The next day, Panamanians arrested two U.S. military
policemen, leading to a three-hour U.S. blockade at Fort Amador
before the two were released.
   Transport ships, armored personnel carriers and light amphibious
vehicles took part in Thursday's exercise, with helicopters and
fighter-bombers providing cover.
   A small group of Panamanian soldiers stationed themselves about
100 yards from the Marine landing and small Panamanian helicopters
briefly flew overhead. Two Panamanian military trucks were blocked
for 10 minutes, without further incident.
   ``We are ensuring the security of the Fort Amador area, in
accordance with our treaty rights,'' said Sconyers.
   He refused to say how many troops were involved, but reporters
could see at least 800 soldiers and Marines, 50 troop carriers,
four seaplanes, landing craft and helicopters. The troops took up
combat positions in the grass around Fort Amador.
   The exercises began when a battalion of the mechanized 5th
Infantry Division left its base on the western side of the canal
and crossed a bridge to Fort Amador, while a light infantry company
of Marines landed at the end of the Amador Causeway south of the
fort.
   The Panamanian Defense Forces were told Thursday morning of the
U.S. plans. They held exercises a few miles away.
   In Caracas, Venezuela, Col. Roberto Diaz Herrera, the former
chief of staff of the Panamanian Defense Forces, said on Thursday
that Noriega was seeking a bloody clash with U.S. units in Panama
as a desperate move to regain military strength and remain in full
command of his country.
   Diaz Herrera, who has lived in Venezuelan exile since 1987,
said, ``Noriega is like a cornered tiger striking blindly with its
paws. He needs a massacre of Panamanian soldiers to arouse morale
among his troops and present Panama as a victim.''
   Diaz Herrera's charges that Noriega was deeply involved in drug
trafficking and that presidential elections were rigged to favor
the official candidates helped set off the continuing political
turmoil in Panama.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890810-0143 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 2247EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-WoundedKnee-FBI     08-10 0500</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wounded Knee-FBI,0514</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dismissal of FBI Agent's Claims Upheld on Appeal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An FBI agent who said he was defamed by a book
describing the violence and killing of two other agents during the
Wounded Knee occupation in South Dakota is not entitled to damages,
an appellate court has ruled.
   A three-judge panel of the 8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals on
Monday upheld a lower court's dismissal of claims by David Price,
an FBI special agent assigned to the Pine Ridge reservation during
the early 1970s.
   Price filed a $25 million lawsuit against Peter Matthiessen,
author of ``In the Spirit of Crazy Horse,'' and the book's
publisher, Viking Penguin Inc. The company suspended circulation of
the book pending the suit's outcome.
   The book dealt with a 1975 shootout at Pine Ridge reservation at
Wounded Knee that left two FBI agents dead and got American Indian
Movement activist Leonard Peltier two life prison terms.
   Price claimed the book accused him of becoming involved in
perjury by a witness, misconduct, gross negligence in the murder of
a woman thought to have been an FBI informant and withholding
information.
   The book presents the view of the AIM that it was targeted for
harrassment by the FBI. Matthiessen reviews the group's occupation
of Wounded Knee in 1973 and subsequent prosecutions of AIM leaders
Dennis Banks and Russell Means.
   According to the book, Price supervised Louis Moves Camp, a
witness at their trial whose testimoney was later discredited.
   ``Fairly or not, Price had come to personify the most cynical
abuses of the FBI's regressive attitudes toward Indians,'' the
author wrote in one passage referring to his interviewing the FBI
agent.
   The lawsuit accused the defendants of defamation, intentional
infliction of emotional distress, invasion of privacy and other
violations of his rights.
   Successive U.S. District Court rulings narrowed the suit's scope
to the defamation claims. Nearly four years after Price first filed
his suit and after the defendants incurred legal costs exceeding $1
million, the lower court dismissed remaining claims.
   In its response on Monday to Price's appeal, the 8th Circuit
Court acknowledged its ruling was ``an anomaly'' in a time when
court cases focus increasingly on whether there is injury. The
court said also that it searched diligently for fault and ignored
some injury to the appellant.
   ``But there is a larger injury to be considered,'' the court
wrote, ``the damage done to every American when a book is pulled
from a shelf, as in this case, or when an idea is not circulated.''
   The court noted that while Price was praised for his work at
Wounded Knee, he also became involved in public controversies. His
complaint, the court said, took statements from their setting in a
way that ``distorts the flavor'' of the book.
   ``In its entirety, `Crazy Horse' focuses more on public
institutions and social forces than it does on any public
official,'' the opinion said.
   ``The sentiments it expresses are debatable. We favor letting
the debate continue.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
