<FIRST>r a AM-CoachShooting     08-10 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Coach Shooting,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>Little Leaguer Shot by Coach Improves, Hospital Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A teen-age baseball pitcher who was shot in
the head by her coach improved to serious condition Thursday, but
detectives seeking a motive for the attack said they won't question
her until at least the weekend.
   The bizarre shooting, witnessed by motorists and at least one
law enforcement officer, occurred during rush hour Tuesday on busy
Interstate 80, about 15 miles northeast of Sacramento. Moments
later, the coach shot himself to death.
   Susanna Jacobs, a star pitcher in the suburban North Highlands
league, leaped from the moving pickup driven by her coach, Jesse
Aguilar, 42, while the vehicle traveled at 55 mph in the slow
eastbound lane. The girl bruised and battered herself while falling.
   Aguilar parked his truck on the shoulder of the freeway, walked
back to the injured girl and shot her once in the back of the head
with a revolver, according to motorists who stopped to help the
girl. He then turned the gun on himself.
   The girl's father, Roger Jacobs, said Aguilar had been following
his daughter in recent days and that he appeetween the two, he added.
   ``He never showed any signs of being a wacko,'' Jacobs said.
   Investigators said she confided to a close friend shortly before
the shooting that Aguilar had been following her around for about
two weeks.
   A spokeswoman at the University Medical Center said the
youngster's condition had improved Thursday to serious from
critical, following successful surgery to remove the bullet. She
reportedly was conscious and apparently aware of her surroundings,
but she was unable to respond to questioning, authorities said.
   A spokeswoman for Placer County Sheriff Don Nunes said
detectives would not attempt to question the teen-ager until
Saturday at the earliest.
   Placer County Sheriff's Detective Bill Summers said the girl and
Aguilar had argued frequently about baseball, but that
investigators were not yet aware of any deeper dispute between the
two.
   Jacobs said he believed Aguilar, a telephone company employee,
was jealous of his daughter's recent friendship with an 18-year-old
girl.
   Acquaintances described Aguilar as intense and competitive, and
said he had often volunteered to coach youth teams in baseball and
basketball.
   Miss Jacobs had played for Aguilar for years. In 1985, as a star
pitcher on an all-male team in the North Highlands Little League,
the girl gained citywide recognition of her athletic ability.
   She continued to play for Aguilar as she moved up from Little
League to the North Highlands Big League.
</TEXT>
