<FIRST>u i AM-Afghan-Guerrillas     08-10 0551</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghan-Guerrillas,0570</SECOND>
<HEAD>Afghan Guerrilla Criticizes Rival; Speculation About Poisoning Death</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PESHAWAR, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of the Afghan guerrilla
government called his foreign minister a ``killer'' Thursday and
said the movement would be better off without him.
   Speculation arose that a moderate guerrilla commander who died
of poisoning this week was killed by rivals. The dead man's son
blamed agents of Afghanistan's Marxist government, which Moslem
insurgents have fought since a communist coup in 1978.
   Sibghatullah Mojaddidi, president of the guerrilla
government-in-exile, said it would have a better chance of
surviving without Gulbuddin Hekmatyar, who serves as foreign
minister. Hekmatyar leads the Hezb-i-Islami, a powerful
fundamentalist faction.
   ``He considers himself the hero of the jihad (holy war), but in
fact he's a killer,'' Mojaddidi said in an interview. ``He has
killed hundreds of mujahedeen inside Afghanistan and hundreds of
innocent people inside Afghanistan.''
   The guerrillas are known as mujahedeen, or holy warriors. Those
under Hekmatyar's command are accused of killing 32 rebels of the
rival Jamiat-i-Islami group July 9 in northern Afghanistan.
   Hekmatyar admitted his men's involvement, but said they were
provoked. Jamiat leader Burhanuddin Rabbani has demanded Hekmatyar
be suspended from the guerrilla government.
   Such infighting threatens what little unity exists among the
guerrilla factions.
   Mojaddidi said of Hekmatyar: ``This man is destroying
Afghanistan.'' The president's Afghan National Liberation Front is
seen as more moderate than the factions of Hekmatyar and Rabbani.
   Asked whether the rebel government would be better off without
Hekmatyar, Mojaddidi replied: ``Why not?''
   Hekmatyar was not available for comment. His chief political
officer, Abdul Qadir Karyab, said of Mojaddidi, ``We think this man
is mad.''
   The moderate commander who died of poison was 75-year-old Haji
Abdul Latif, known as the Lion of Kandahar, who had clashed with
Hekmatyar and other fundamentalists.
   A letter from his son, Sher Agha, said Latif writhed in pain for
20 hours before dying Monday outside the arid southern city of
Arghastan, about 50 miles east of Kandahar, a guerrilla source
reported.
   Two of the commander's bodyguards confessed, saying the Afghan
government was behind the poisoning, and were put to death, the
source reported.
   Some rebel sources within and apart from Latif's National
Islamic Front of Afghanistan blamed factional rivalry, but would
not elaborate.
   ``How can we say who did it until we finish our investigation?''
asked Nasser-Zia, a spokesman for Latif's faction. Hamid Gailani,
another spokesman for the group, said ``it could be anyone,
including the government.''
   Agha's letter quoted the bodyguards, Mohammad Nadir and Mohammad
Zahir, as saying they were paid about $5,700 by the Afghan secret
service, known as the Khad, the source said.
   A dozen of Latif's men were slain one night last year after a
Khad agent who had infiltrated their ranks took government soldiers
to their hideout, he quoted the letter as saying.
   Latif had several disputes with fundamentalist factions,
particularly Hekmatyar's Hezb-i-Islami.
   Earlier this year, he claimed to have made a machine-gun attack
on a convoy led by Hekmatyar. He boasted of having driven Hekmatyar
from the Kandahar region, where Hezb-i-Islami was trying to
mobilize guerrilas for an attack on the city.
   Guerrillas in Latif's and other moderate factions have opposed
attempts to attack Kandahar, Afghanistan's second largest city,
where many of their families live.
</TEXT>
