<FIRST>u a AM-ActressSlaying     08-10 0598</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Actress Slaying,0617</SECOND>
<HEAD>California Authorities Snatch Suspect in Actress Slaying From Tucson
Jail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man accused of the fatal shooting of
actress Rebecca Schaeffer was hustled out of Arizona by Los Angeles
authorities Thursday after his public defender filed the wrong
motion in the wrong court.
   District Attorney Ira Reiner said his office seized the chance
to ``snatch'' Robert John Bardo, 19, from Tucson after realizing
that Bardo's defense lawyer had challenged to his extradition in
the wrong court.
   Lori Lefferts, a Pima County deputy public defender appointed to
represent Bardo in extradition proceedings, said his transfer to
Los Angeles was ``totally in violation of his rights. He had an
absolute right to a hearing and he never got that hearing.''
   However, she said: ``I have absolutely no remedy. It's all over
for here.''
   She said she did not learn about the action until two hours
after he left on a plane to Los Angeles.
   The public defender apparently thought she had eight days to
challenge extradition, but Reiner said: ``She didn't have eight
minutes.''
   ``This is not a game,'' Reiner said at a news conference. ``This
is murder, and if we are able to move into Tucson and snatch him,
we are going to do that.''
   ``Because of a momentary lapse by his lawyer, we were able to
avoid the lengthy and, in this case, unnecessary delays of an
extradition proceeding,'' he said.
   A governor's warrant was served on Bardo on Monday. A defense
attorney can file petition for a writ of habeas corpus to fight the
warrant.
   But instead of filing for a writ, which would have automatically
held Bardo until a hearing could be held, Ms. Lefferts filed a
motion to stay the proceeding pending a mental health examination,
and filed it in Justice Court instead of Superior Court.
   ``The judge denied her motion, he refused to put a stay on the
extradition. And so Los Angeles was advised that they could pick
Bardo up,'' said Ricki Macey, head of the fugitive warrant unit in
the Pima County Attorney's office.
   Ms. Lefferts still could have filed a petition for a writ in
Superior Court, but in the meantime, two police investigators
hurried to reach Tucson Wednesday before the court clerk's office
closed at midnight.
   Their flight was delayed four times. But with an escort by
Tuscon police officers, they made it in time to complete paperwork,
take custody of Bardo and fly him back to Los Angeles on a 6 a.m.
flight.
   Reiner said the quick move averted a protracted legal battle
over Bardo's mental competency.
   Miss Schaeffer, 21, who had costarred in the television series
``My Sister Sam,'' was shot to death in Los Angeles on July 18.
   Bardo was arrested the next day in Tucson after he ran in and
out of traffic on Interstate 10 near a downtown exit.
   Detectives said statements by Bardo prompted them to notify Los
Angeles authorities investigating Miss Schaeffer's death.
   Bardo, who lived at his parents' Tucson home, collected
videotapes of the series, once was thrown out of a TV studio where
Miss Schaeffer was working, sent her a rambling love letter and had
hired a detective agency to find her address, officials have said.
   Bardo had been held in lieu of $1 million bond in the Pima
County Jail's mental health unit and had been under a suicide watch.
   Ms. Lefferts declined to say if Bardo has undergone psychiatric
evaluation.
   Bardo was scheduled to be arraigned on the murder charge in Los
Angeles on Friday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
