<DOCNO> AP890810-0151 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 2024EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Crops     08-10 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Crops,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Farmers to Get Hard Currency for Surplus Grain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAREY GOLDBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet farmers will soon be able to cash in on
their cash crops under a new decree that allows them to sell
surplus grain and seeds for hard currency, the official Tass news
agency reported Thursday.
   The resolution says farmers can sell part of their high-quality
wheat, peas, lupine and oil-bearing seeds to the government for
convertible currency that can be used to buy hard-to-get foreign
goods.
   The reasoning is that the chance to earn hard currency will
stimulate so much extra production that the state will end up
paying its own farmers less than it would have paid for imports to
make up chronic shortages, Tass said.
   Tass said the new system will be introduced on a test basis in
1989-90.
   Economist Nikolai Shemelev suggested at the Congress of People's
Deputies in June that the Soviet Union adopt such a system.
   Tass said the state will pay $96 in hard currency per ton of
strong and durum wheat; $64 per ton of other high-quality wheat;
$128 per ton of pea and lupine, and $144 per ton of sunflower, soy,
rape, flax and mustard seed.
   ``The farms will be free in spending the currency,'' Tass said.
   Soviet citizens' access to foreign currency is normally very
restricted, but restrictions have begun to loosen slightly as more
Soviet firms are allowed access to foreign markets under President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reforms.
   The ability to buy foreign goods takes on added significance in
the face of shortages of such basics as soap, detergent and
medicine due to economic dislocation brought on by reforms.
   The government will also look into the possibility of allowing
individual farmers with private plots and those who lease their
land to sell for hard currency as well, Tass said.
   Its report said the new resolution was passed in accordance with
a decision of the Congress of People's Deputies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
