<FIRST>u i AM-Hungary-EastGermany     08-10 0487</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary-East Germany,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>East Germany Promises Returning Asylum Seekers Will Not Be Peosecuted</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE JAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East Germany has pledged not to punish
hundreds of its citizens who have gone underground in Hungary or
are seeking asylum on West German diplomatic property, Hungarian
officials said Thursday.
   The Interior Ministry officials also said Hungary was examining
about 10 petitions for political asylum, but that none of them were
from East Germans.
   ``We have been authorized to announce (by East Germany) ... that
those East German citizens now at the West German Embassy, as well
as those East German citizens residing here illegally will not be
subject to punitive measures if they return to East Germany within
a short time,'' said Police Col. Karoly Nagy told reporters. ``They
can (then) submit their emigration petitions.''
   A West German Embassy official said he believed the East German
offer was good only for those in Hungary.
   Those in the East Berlin mission had been promised freedom from
prosecution but not permission to submit emigration requests, he
said. The West German, who attended the news conference, asked that
he not be named.
   East Germans began occupying West German diplomatic legations in
Eastern Europe nearly two weeks ago, apparently out of frustration
over the lack of reform in their communist country and the
difficulty of emigrating through official channels.
   As many as 400 are reported holed up in embassies and consulates
in Budapest and Prague, and at the permanent mission in East
Berlin. An undetermined number is said to have gone underground in
Hungary, fearing persecution if they return because of their escape
attempts.
   East German media said Thursday that 158 East Germans were on
West German diplomatic property in Hungary.
   Hungarian officials speaking privately have conceded that the
standoff is leading to tensions with Warsaw Pact ally East Germany,
which has attacked reforms under way in Hungary.
   Hungary is the only Soviet bloc nation to have joined the U.N.
Convention on the rights of refugees, and Nagy said the petititons
of the approximately 10 asylum-seekers were being examined in the
spirit of the convention, although new Hungarian refugee laws were
not yet complete.
   Hungary first joined the convention stipulating the right to
asylum for those persecuted because of race, religion, nationality
or political beliefs in March.
   In a statement distributed at the news conference, the Interior
Ministry said that despite Hungary's acceptance of the convention
``our nation does not wish to become an exiting channel ... for
east European citizens.''
   The officials acknowledged that ethnic Hungarians and Romanians
who flee to Hungary are being permitted to stay without
formalities, although a similar bilateral agreement exists with
Bucharest. They said such unequal treatment will end by October,
when each case will be examined on its merits, regardless of the
applicant's citizenship.
   Formally Soviet bloc allies, Romania and Hungary are deeply
split over territorial and ethnic disagreements.
</TEXT>
