<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 2319EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Marcos     08-10 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Marcos,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Imelda Marcos Pleads To Leave Country; Promises To Return</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Philippine First Lady Imelda Marcos
pleaded Thursday to leave the United States, but promised to return
to face prosecution on criminal racketeering charges ``if it is the
last thing I do.''
   ``Your honor, I would like to make a plea and a pledge. A plea
to bring President Marcos home to his motherland, the
Philippines,'' she said, sobbing.
   ``If it is the last thing I will do in my life, I will come back
to New York to vindicate ... our name, the name of the Marcoses,
for the truth will set us free,'' she told Chief U.S. Immigration
Judge William R. Robie.
   Mrs. Marcos, 60, is challenging a travel ban imposed in June by
the Immigration and Naturalization Service which bars her from
leaving the United States. Robie is expected to issue his ruling in
Washington in several weeks.
   Mrs. Marcos wants to take her dying husband, Ferdinand, the
former Philippine president, back to their homeland, but more than
the INS order is preventing their departure.
   The Marcoses were indicted by the United States last October for
allegedly stealing more than $100 million from the Philippines and
stashing it in the United States. Marcos was separated from the
case because of his failing health, but Mrs. Marcos pleaded
innocent and was released on $5 million bail.
   Her bail provisions require her to stay in the country, and
Marcos' attorney Richard Hibey said that makes the travel order
unnecessary.
   Besides, Hibey said, Philippine President Corazon Aquino has
forbidden Marcos' return, dead or alive, and the ban extends to his
family. The 71-year-old Marcos has been hospitalized here for the
past seven months and was listed in critical condition Thursday.
   Mrs. Marcos has repeatedly said she would like to bring her
husband home to die, and has appealed to Mrs. Aquino to allow her
wish.
   Hibey said he would ask a federal judge to expand Mrs. Marcos'
bail provisions to allow her to leave only if Marcos dies, Mrs.
Aquino relents and the INS order was lifted.
   ``I'm dealing with the legal realities, she's dealing with what
she really wants,'' Hibey said.
   The government contends the travel ban should stand because the
Marcoses are billionaires and the loss of $5 million would not
prevent Mrs. Marcos from fleeing; that they unsuccessfully plotted
to overthrow Mrs. Aquino; that their presence in the Philippines
would destabilize the government and that no extradition treaty
exists between the two countries to ensure Mrs. Marcos' return.
   Roy Hendricks, acting district director of the INS in Honolulu,
testified Thursday that he had no ``specific reason'' to believe
Mrs. Marcos would flee and that he issued the travel ban on orders
from Washington.
</TEXT>
