<FIRST>r a AM-AssembliesofGod     08-10 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Assemblies of God,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Church Delegates Change Rule Governing Ministers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentecostal denomination that endured
the Jimmy Swaggart and Jim Bakker scandals has rewritten its rules
of conduct for ministers to include sexual misconduct as a
punishable offense.
   The Assemblies of God said the more specific wording was part of
a rule revision that had been planned for six years. Delegates
approved the change Wednesday at the denomination's general council
meeting.
   Previously, any offenses involving sexual misconduct fell under
the general statement of ``any conduct unbecoming to a minister or
indiscretions involving morals.''
   Swaggart was expelled in 1988 for refusing to accept a one-year
suspension after his tearful confession of ``moral failure.'' He
had been accused of patronizing a prostitute.
   Bakker, founder of the PTL ministry, was stripped of his
credentials in 1987 after admitting a sexual encounter with church
secretary Jessica Hahn.
   Other causes for disciplinary action are ``dictatorial
authority'' over a congregation, inefficiency, a noncooperative
spirit, a habit of running into debt and the remarriage of a
divorced clergy member whose former spouse is still living.
   A credentials committee will decide whether a minister is
rehabilitated or dismissed for an offense, based on the manner and
thoroughness of repentance, the attitude of the minister toward the
discipline and willingness to cooperate.
   The only busines on the meeting's scheduled Thursday was
committee reports on Christian educating, dealing with the
restructuring of the denomination's division of Christian education.
   On Wednesday, the Rev. G. Raymond Carlson was re-elected to his
second four-year term as general superintendent, the denomination's
chief executive officer.
   The church has 1.3 million members and an attendance of roughly
twice that.
</TEXT>
