<FIRST>r a AM-Allergies     08-10 0206</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Allergies,0211</SECOND>
<HEAD>Allergies Predicted Higher In Northeast, Elsewhere</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Parts of the South, Midwest and Northeast are
expected to have a worse hay fever season this year, beginning in
about two weeks, according to the American Academy of Allergy and
Immunology.
   A good growing season that began with a wet spring means New
York, Pennsylvania and New Jersey could experience the worst
increase in allergic reactions to the pollen of ragweed and other
plants, said Sarah Kaluzny, communications manager for the academy,
based in Milwaukee.
   Other states predicted to be bad this year are Montana, Alaska,
Nevada, North Dakota, Oklahoma, Alabama, Georgia, Texas, Indiana
and Kentucky, she said.
   Doctors from most of the 50 states responded to an unscientific
survey by the academy, and none indicated this year would see an
improvement over last year, Ms. Kaluzny said. No responses came
from Arkansas, Colorado, Nebraska, Kansas, Illinios, Ohio, Utah,
New Hampshire, Massachusettes, Connecticut, Maryland, Florida,
North Carolina and Idaho.
   Ragweed is the major cause of allergies, with each plant
producing a million grains of pollen, Ms. Kaluzny said.
   Mold counts also are up in some areas of the nation because of
wet weather, contributing to the predicted increase in allergy
problems, she said.
</TEXT>
