<FIRST>r a AM-JDL-JDOFeud     08-10 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-JDL-JDO Feud,0574</SECOND>
<HEAD>Feud Between Militant Jewish Groups Results in Shooting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bicoastal feud between two militant Jewish
organizations erupted in violence in Greenwich Village on Thursday
when the head of one faction fired shots at the leader of another,
injuring a bystander.
   Mordechai Levy, head of the Jewish Defense Organization,
surrendered to police nearly 2{ hours after the shots were fired
following a dispute about court papers that were served in a libel
suit.
   Authorities said Levy would be charged with three counts of
attempted murder.
   The victim, Dominick Spinelli, was listed in stable condition at
St. Vincent's Hospital. He was sitting in a van on near Levy's
apartment when a shot came through the windshield and hit him in
the knee at about 12:25 p.m.
   Levy's apparent target was Irwin Rubin, the Los Angeles-based
head of the Jewish Defense League, who went with private
investigator Steve Rombom to Levy's Bleecker Street home to serve
him with papers in a libel action Rubin had filed.
   At issue were comments Levy made in an interview with a West
Coast radio station. The two groups _ the JDL and JDO _ have been
contentious for years, as Rubin and Levy battle over the mantle of
the JDL's founder, Meir Kahane.
   ``Levy left the JDL about 7 or 8 years ago. ... He formed his
own organization, the JDO, and they've been at odds with the JDL
since then,'' said Lt. David Nadel, a police liaison with the
Jewish community.
   ``Levy accused him (Rubin) of being a drug dealer and said
(Rubin's wife) attempted suicide,'' said Earl Krugel, chairman of
the JDL's Los Angeles Chapter. The lawsuit was filed in Los Angeles
Superior Court on July 27.
   Police Chief Robert Johnston said Levy called police Wednesday
and said ``there were two people on their way to kill him.''
   Then, when Rubin and Rombom went to Bleecker Street on Thursday
afternoon, they threw stones at a window of Levy's second-floor
apartment.
   ``In the course of events, apparently someone came over the
roof, looked down and started firing a Ruger Mini-14 (semiautomatic
rifle) at them,'' Johnston said.
   The street was closed as dozens of police were brought in, along
with a robot used in hostage situations and a portable bulletproof
wall.
   Police managed to reach Levy _ a heavy, bearded man _ by phone
in his apartment. At 2:50 p.m., he surrendered quietly.
   People who said they were linked with the JDO have claimed
responsibility for numerous bombings and other acts of violence in
New York, though Levy always has said later that his group was not
involved.
   Levy legally owns seven guns. ``This guy's got heavy weaponry
... with the armament he's got, he's dangerous,'' Johnston said.
   As for the JDO, Johnston said, ``We've dealt with them. They're
not a very large organization, not anywhere near the size of the
JDL.''
   The Jewish Defense League was originally formed by Kahane to
mount armed response to anti-Semitic acts in New York City. It
gained notoriety when its members were linked to bombings, most of
them aimed at Soviet targets in retaliation for the way that
country treated its Jewish population.
   Kahane left the JDL and moved to Israel. A power struggle
ensued, with Rubin and Levy among the contenders its leadership.
</TEXT>
