<FIRST>u a AM-DC-10Landing 2ndLd-Writethru a0703 08-10 0589</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-DC-10 Landing, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0703,0602</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigators Say DC-10 Tail Engine Apparently Failed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 8 grafs to UPDATE with NTSB member's comments, CLARIFY
that Sioux City crash engine was General Electric; SUBS 10th graf pvs,
`Investigators from ..., to conform.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-FAA-DC-10s, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal investigators Thursday examined the
battered tail engine of a Northwest Airlines DC-10 that made an
emergency landing after the engine broke up.
   None of the 256 people aboard was injured. A piece of the
engine's tail cone was missing and there were numerous small holes
in the engine cover, said Joseph Nall, a member of the National
Transportation Safety Board.
   ``The initial look at the aircraft shows relatively minor
external damage to the No. 2 engine,'' Nall said after
investigators inspected the plane in a hangar at Stapleton
International Airport.
   Nall said a fuel cutoff line also was severed when the engine
broke apart in flight, but crew members used a backup system to
shut down the engine shortly before making an emergency landing
Wednesday at Stapleton.
   Nall said the flight and data recorders of the DC-10 were taken
to Washington, D.C., where inspection showed that only the last 30
minutes of the emergency were recorded and the engine failure
itself apparently was erased.
   Stapleton spokesman Richard Boulware, who saw the damaged
engine, said, ``One of the holes was big enough I could have stuck
my hand through.''
   Boulware said he also saw broken turbine fan blades inside the
engine.
   Officials declined to compare Wednesday's incident with the
General Electric tail-engine failure that preceded last month's
crash of a United Airlines DC-10 in Sioux City, Iowa, that killed
111 people.
   ``We are looking at this incident on its own, on its merit,''
Nall said. ``All we're doing at this point is looking at this
accident, this DC-10, this Pratt &amp; Whitney engine. We're not
looking at DC-10s.''
   Flight 308 was en route from Los Angeles to Minneapolis when the
engine began breaking up. The crew reported a loss of oil pressure
and severe vibration in the tail engine and shut it down, said Greg
Feith, an NTSB spokesman in Denver.
   The plane landed safely in Denver a half hour later, at about
6:30 p.m.
   Investigators from the NTSB, the Federal Aviation Administration
and Northwest examined the plane. Nall said NTSB investigators
expected to interview crew members within the next week.
   Feith said accidents that do not involve fatalities or extensive
damage to aircraft usually are investigated by regional offices,
but the Northwest failure was ``too much of a coincidence''
following the Sioux City crash.
   The No. 2 engine, one of three on the jet, is mounted in the
aircraft's vertical stabilizer, just above the tail wing. On
United's Flight 232, the No. 2 engine disintegrated, shooting
shrapnel that apparently severed hydraulic lines used to control
the jet. The investigation into the cause of that crash is
continuing.
   In Washington, FAA chief James B. Busey said agency officials
``know of no hard facts that would lead us to take action to ground
DC-10s.''
   Busey said there is insufficient information yet to link the
incident with the Iowa crash, and said the DC-10 is ``safe to fly.
I would fly in the aircraft today.''
   He called it a ``comfortable, good-performing'' airliner.
   Busey said the Northwest incident was an example of ``the way
the system should work'' because the pilots quickly shut down the
engine, diverted to a nearby airport and landed safely with no
injuries.
</TEXT>
