<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 2157EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Chile     08-10 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chile,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>Buchi Chosen Lone Goverment Candidate To Succeed Pinochet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY EVA VERGARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Finance Minister Hernan Buchi on
Thursday became the lone government candidate in the race to
succeed military President Augusto Pinochet after a veteran
politician withdrew from the race.
   Voters on Dec. 14 will pick a succeessor to Pinochet, who took
power in a bloody military coup in 1973.
   Buchi _ considered Pinochet's candidate _ was credited for much
of Chile's economic recovery, boosting exports and presiding over a
decline in inflation and the nation's foreign debt.
   But the opposition _ united around the Christian Democratic
Party's Patricio Aylwin _ is expected to win the vote. The
coalition of 17 parties ranging from left to center-right has
promised its economic policies will emphasize aid to the nation's
growing number of poor.
   The new government is to take office on March 11, 1990. It will
be the first presidential election since Chileans chose Salvador
Allende, an avowed Marxist, in 1970.
   Sergio Jarpa, president of National Renewal, the nation's
largest conservative party, said his party would formally endorse
Buchi.
   Buchi, 40, called Jarpa's decision to step aside ``a show of
patriotism.'' Jarpa's announcement ended long and often difficult
negotiations among Pinochet's supporters, who hoped to face the
election with a single candidate.
   Pinochet was obliged to call the election after losing an
October referendum in which voters rejected a proposal to extend
his rule until 1997.
   The 73-year-old president and army commander is barred by the
constitution from seeking re-election. He has said, however, he
will retain his position as army commander in the next
administration.
   As finance minister from 1985 through April, Buchi led economic
policies that won substantial praise from bankers at home and
abroad.
   Inflation has fallen to 15 percent annually, a modest figure by
Latin American standards. Buchi also encouraged exports, which
boomed to $7 billion last year, leaving a surplus of $2 billion.
   The nation's foreign debt was cut from $21 billion three years
ago to $16.5 billion today.
   Even so, opinion polls give the 70-year-old Aylwin a substantial
advantage over Buchi. A poll released Thursday by the Center for
Contemporary Studies, a respected private research institution,
gives Aylwin the support of 53.8 percent of those polled to Buchi's
23.8 percent.
</TEXT>
