<FIRST>u w AM-Leland-Signal 3rdLd-Writethru a0718 08-10 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Leland-Signal, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0718,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Second Signal Picked Up in Rep. Leland Search</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to delete reference to ``directly opposite.''
Northwest is not directly opposite southwest.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A weather satellite passing directly over
Ethiopia picked up a second emergency distress signal Thursday, far
away from an earlier signal but still boosting cnfidence that it
came from the plane of missing Rep. Mickey Leland, officials said.
   The satellite that picked up the second signal passed directly
over Ethiopia and read the signal as coming from about 100 miles
north-northwest of Addis Ababa. Leland's plane was supposed to be
going southwest, far from where the new signal was detected.
   ``We have greater confidence in this particular signal because
the satellite was in a better position to make a location,'' said
Russell Koffler of the National Oceanic Atmospheric Administration.
   The newest signal was picked up about 6 p.m. EDT on a different
wavelength from the signal the satellite detected Wednesday night,
Washington time.
   Koffler said the plane Leland, D-Texas, was flying in has the
capability to broadcast on both the wavelengths that have been
picked up.
   The newest signal comes from far from the earlier signal,
however, which officials believe was southwest of Addis Ababa. Both
signals have been far from the flight path Leland's plane would
have taken to reach the refugee camps near the Sudanese border he
was headed for when his plane was reported missing on Monday.
   ``We are confident we got a good fix. We have more confidence in
this signal than in the one last night,'' said Koffler.
   ``It doesn't mean it's from that particular plane,'' he
cautioned, adding there would be few such sources for distress
signals in the thinly populated African nation, however.
   Koffler said the clarity of the latest signal, the knowledge
that Leland's plane could transmit signals on both wavelengths that
have been detected and the rarity of other distress signals
increased belief that the new signal came from Leland's plane.
   Ethiopia was at the edge of the area covered by the satellite
when it picked up the earlier signal. Search teams have headed on
foot for the remote mountain area where the earlier signal was
believed to originate and searchers hoped to send planes to that
region at Friday's daybreak in Ethiopia.
   Like the earlier signal, the new signal was relayed from the
satellite to a ground station in India.
   ``We'd normally have confidence within a 20-mile radius with
that signal, but it is still fairly marginal'' because of the
distance the signal was relayed, said Koffler.
</TEXT>
