<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 2340EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-BlackPolitics     08-10 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Black Politics,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>Political Equality Goal of Black Women's Convention</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHEVEL JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A stronger role in politics for black women
is the goal of the National Political Congress of Black Women,
which convened Thursday in New Orleans to draft its national policy
agenda.
   The non-partisan association founded in 1984 by former U.S. Rep.
Shirley Chisholm is holding its convention here through Sunday.
Organizers of the conference expect more than 2,000 black women to
attend.
   ``We're here to make sure political parity becomes a reality for
Afro-American women before we move into century 21,'' said C.
Delores Tucker, chairwoman of the Democratic National Committee's
Black Caucus.
   ``We will challenge women here to take firm positions in local
government and demand the power that goes with it, to re-claim
their neighborhoods and to support black-owned businesses,'' Tucker
said.
   Tucker, who is the NPCBW's vice-chairwoman, said 1987 figures
show black women held 1,482 of the more than 500,000 elected
offices nationwide.
   The organization's mission is to register black women voters,
develop public policy, seek women to hold elective office and
develop them as candidates and involve young people as early as
possible in politics, Tucker said.
   ``This conference is about the business of addressing the issues
of major concern to those of us who are Afro-American _ the drug
issues, the issues of affirmative action and civil rights and the
issues of education,'' said Chisholm, the organization's national
chairwoman.
   The group must continue to confront whatever obstacles appear in
the effort to gain an equal political voice, said Dr. Gloria Toote,
former assistant secretary of the Department of Housing and Urban
Development and also vice-chairwoman.
   ``We're not asking for affirmative action that gives reverse
discrimination but we are asking for affirmative action that
promises 20 acres and a mule,'' Toote said. ``For had the ex-slave
of America received the 20 acres and a mule we would not now be the
under class of America, the illiterate of America and the last
hired first fired of America.'' she said.
</TEXT>
