<HEAD>Edward Lujan Suffers Heart Attack</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf, `Edward Lujan, ..., to UPDATE his condition to
stable but guarded.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Edward Lujan, a state Republican Party
leader and brother of U.S. Secretary of Interior Manuel Lujan Jr.,
suffered a heart attack Thursday, an aide to the secretary said.
   Edward Lujan, an Albuquerque insurance executive, was in stable
but guarded condition at Valley View Hospital in Glenwood Springs,
Colo., Steve Goldstein said from his office in Washington, D.C.
   Lujan and his wife, Virginia, were in Colorado on vacation,
Goldstein said. They were at a recreational vehicle park Thursday
morning, where Lujan was unhooking hoses to the RV when he felt
pain. Mrs. Lujan drove her husband to the hospital.
   Edward Lujan is a former chairman of the New Mexico GOP and was
unsuccessful in his bid last year for the Republican nomination for
the U.S. House seat left vacant when Manuel Lujan retired after 10
terms.
   Goldstein said Manuel Lujan was in Albuquerque and would go to
Colorado on Thursday. Manuel Lujan suffered a heart attack in 1986
and had triple bypass surgery. Goldstein said he has fully covered.
