<FIRST>r i AM-Zambia-SouthAfrica     08-10 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Zambia-South Africa,0211</SECOND>
<HEAD>Zambian President to Meet South Africa's De Klerk</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUSAKA, Zambia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Kenneth Kaunda said Thursday he
will meet the leader of South Africa's governing party, F.W. de
Klerk, on Aug. 28 for talks on ways to end apartheid.
   De Klerk, as head of the National Party, is expected to become
South Africa's president after Sept. 6 parliamentary elections.
   In South Africa, Foreign Minister Pik Botha said he would
accompany de Klerk on the visit to Livingstone, Zambia. He said the
visit grew out of talks initiated with Kuanda by retiring South
African President P.W. Botha.
   He gave no further information.
   Kaunda announced the meeting following a one-day summit in
Lusaka of the six African nations aligned against white-governed
South Africa.
   ``I have briefed my colleagues and I will meet him (De Klerk) in
Livingstone on Aug. 28,'' he told reporters.
   Kaunda is chairman of the six-nation group, which comprises
Angola, Botswana, Mozambique, Tanzania, Zambia and Zimbabwe.
   The Zambian president has led calls for isolation of South
Africa until it ends its policy of racial separation known as
apartheid. The African National Congress, the main guerrilla group
fighting to overthrow the South African goverment, is based in
Zambia.
</TEXT>
