<FIRST>r a AM-Widow'sMaid     08-10 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Widow's Maid,0261</SECOND>
<HEAD>Live-in Maid Sentenced To Three Years In Theft From Elderly Widow</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BARTOW, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former live-in maid who bilked nearly
$900,000 from an elderly, paralyzed widow kept prisoner in her own
home was sentenced Thursday to three years in prison.
   Barbara June Stevens, 54, was sentenced to serve the prison term
along with 10 years probation under a plea bargain struck with
prosecutors last month.
   Prosecutors said Ms. Stevens confined 71-year-old Valeria Lust
to her Lakeland home by taking away the woman's walker and
telephone and by giving her illegally obtained prescription drugs
to keep her sleepy.
   Some of the $883,534 stolen from the widow in 1987-88 went to
Fountain of Life Inc., a TV ministry in Greenville, N.C., and to
Sonshine Cathedral in Highland City, authorities said.
   Under the plea agreement, Ms. Stevens is required to testify and
cooperate in the investigation of Fountain of Life televangelist
Jim Whittington and the Rev. Daniel Atwood, former pastor of
Sonshine Cathedral.
   Neither Wittington nor Atwood _ who is serving a prison sentence
in Pennsylvania for stealing from followers _ has been charged in
the case.
   Ms. Stevens pleaded guilty last month to charges including
kidnapping, forgery, grand theft and conspiracy. In the plea
bargain, prosecutors agreed to drop 55 other charges that could
have brought a life prison term.
   Assistant Public Defender Frank Solorzano said at the sentencing
hearing that Ms. Stevens was ``largely a victim herself.''
   ``She's a very religious person,'' he said. ``She looks for
false prophets.''
</TEXT>
