<FIRST>u a AM-Mofford-Gun 2ndLd-Writethru a0720 08-10 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mofford-Gun, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0720,0489</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Prosecutor Held, Released</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 4th, ``There are ..., to UPDATE with governor's
comments, attempts to reach Herand.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who moves erratically because of severe
multiple sclerosis was arrested Thursday when police escorting
Arizona Gov. Rose Mofford saw him with a gun which turned out to an
unloaded collector's item.
   No one was injured in the incident in Florence, a town southwest
of Phoenix, and Mrs. Mofford went about her business, officials
said.
   Raymond P. Herand, 42, a former county prosecutor, was
questioned and released after officers determined that he had not
known Mrs. Mofford was in the area and had no intention of
threatening anyone, said Sgt. Allan Schmidt, chief spokesman at the
state Department of Public Safety.
   ``There are no charges,'' he said. ``None will be filed.''
   Mrs. Mofford praised the officers for protecting her and said
she hadn't seen the incident. ``I really didn't know what was
happening,'' she said, adding that she wasn't scared.
   Herand's home telephone was not answered, and an office that has
taken messages for him in the past said it had no way of contacting
him.
   Schmidt said Florence Police Chief Tom Rankin and three state
officers spotted Herand near his car with a gun just as Mrs.
Mofford and her top aides were preparing to leave a restaurant
after a task force meeting on state prisons.
   There were varying accounts on exactly what happened next but
general agreement by Schmidt, Mofford press secretary Vada Manager
and several eyewitnesses that Mrs. Mofford stayed in the restaurant
while officers took Herand in custody and grabbed the weapon.
   ``I stepped back and pulled the governor,'' said state Land
Commissioner M. Jean Hassell. ``She was very, very calm and very
collected. There was no panic.''
   One of the officers on the governor's security detail also
stayed with her, Schmidt and Manager said.
   ``She did not know of it as it was occurring,'' Schmidt said.
   Herand, a former assistant Pinal County attorney who now lives
in Glendale, did not resist.
   He later explained to officers that he had the gun on his
dashboard because of a law requiring that weapons in cars be in
full view, and had taken it from the vehicle to protect it from the
heat of the sun, Schmidt said. He said officers found no evidence
that the gun had ever been used.
   The police officers reacted appropriately because ``you have to
presume the worst,'' Schmidt added. ``You don't ask. You just do.''
   A local state officer grabbed Herand's gun while Rankin turned
him around, Schmidt said. Another state officer handcuffed the man.
   Mrs. Mofford, a Democrat, was elected as secretary of state in
1986 but became governor last year when the legislature impeached
elected Republican Gov. Evan Mecham.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
