<FIRST>r a AM-Baby-FacedBandit     08-10 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baby-Faced Bandit,0379</SECOND>
<HEAD>Suspect Featured On Nationwide Crime Program Standing Trial In Salt
Lake</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An FBI agent testified Thursday that he
literally caught a bank robbery suspect redhanded as the man was
waiting for a flight at Salt Lake International Airport.
   FBI Agent Paul Ladner told a federal court jury he found red dye
on David Lee Martin's forearm and hand, indicative of the red
substance that explodes out of dye packs hidden in bags of bills by
bank tellers.
   Dye-splotched bills also were found in a backpack the defendant
was carrying, and dye stains and burn marks were discovered on his
body after he was taken to the Salt Lake County Jail, Ladner said.
   Martin, accused of being the ``Baby Face Robber'' profiled on
the America's Most Wanted television program, is charged in U.S.
District Court with robbing the First Interstate Bank in Sugar
House of $1,562 on June 20.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney David Schwendiman said Martin also is
wanted in bank robberies in Denver, Los Angeles and San Diego. He
faces prosecution in Colorado and California in 16 separate
robberies.
   Police in Lafayette, Colo., Martin's former hometown, also have
a warrant for his arrest stemming from a June 1988 burglary.
   Tim Talbot, a ticketing agent for AmericaWest Airlines,
testified at Thursday's proceedings that money Martin used to pay
for an airline ticket to Reno, Nev., was covered with a red
substance.
   FBI agents had informed airport security that a bank robbery
suspect might attempt to buy a ticket to Reno after Martin
allegedly told the cab driver who brought him to the airport of his
destination.
   The driver, Tim Newland, said in a police report he thought he
recognized Martin from the TV program, which aired June 11.
   Talbot identified Martin to FBI agents who intercepted the
defendant as he tried to leave the airport. Several bank employees
at the trial identified Martin as the man who robbed the bank.
   If convicted, Martin, 24, faces up to 20 years in prison and a
$250,000 fine.
   When the Utah trial is finished, Martin likely will be brought
to Colorado to face four counts of bank larceny, said assistant
U.S. Attorney Tom O'Rourke.
</TEXT>
