<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 2239EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Namibia     08-10 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia,0555</SECOND>
<HEAD>SWAPO Says South Africa Out To Rig Namibian Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The main Namibian rebel group said
Thursday that South Africa will run 150,000 South African voters
and Angolan guerrillas into Namibia to rig November's election,
``with the connivance'' of U.N. officials.
   The Angolan guerrillas, members of the National Union for the
Total Independence of Angola, have has fought the Marxist
government of Angola with South African aid since losing out in a
civil war after independence from Portugal in 1975.
   Hinyangerwa Asheeke, the U.N. observer for Nambia's South West
Africa People's Organization, or SWAPO, suggested that the rebel
movement would not recognize the results of an election that is not
``free and fair.''
   African nations asked the Security Council to meet urgently
Monday on ``the deteriorating situation in Namibia.'' Ghanaian
Ambassador J.V. Gbeho made the request in a letter to the council's
president.
   Besides the situation Asheeke complained about, the nations are
upset over the presence of former members of the counterinsurgency
patrol Koevoet in the territory's police. They are also worried
about election registration procedures that would enable
authorities to record how individuals voted, and a cumbersome
vote-counting process.
   A spokesman for South Africa's U.N. Mission, Aubrey K. Dwyer,
replied that South Africans are eligible to vote under
U.N.-approved election laws for Namibia, and that U.N. election
monitors would prevent ineligible voters such as the Angolan
guerrillas from perpetrating vote fraud.
   SWAPO fought a guerrilla war from 1966 against South Africa's
rule in Namibia, but it accepted a cease-fire. It is the largest
Namibian political party.
   Asheeke said a loophole in Namibia's election law allows up to
100,000 South Africans who worked in Namibia for four years or more
to register to vote.
   He said an additional 50,000 Angolan rebels will be fraudulently
registered to vote in Namibia, a land of 1.3 million people.
   South African officials have estimated from 500,000 to 600,000
people will register to vote.
   An influx of anti-SWAPO voters could deny the Marxist party a
two-thirds majority in the election for a constituent assembly,
forcing it to form a coalition government that would be more
cooperative with South Africa.
   Asheeke said ``Pretoria proceeded with enacting this election
law, obviously with the connivance of the special representative of
the United Nations'' in Namibia, Martti Ahtisaari.
   As U.N. special representative for Namibia, Ahtisaari must
approve the election laws, and could suspend the election if he
believes the process is not free and fair. He has not suggested he
will do that.
   On April 1, U.N. peacekeepers and administrators began
implementing a one-year plan to oversee the transition to
independence.
   South Africa has ruled Namibia since World War I.
   South Africa signed accords with Angola and Cuba in December,
agreeing to free Namibia if 50,000 Cuban troops stationed in Angola
are sent home by mid-1991.
   In Windhoek, Namibia, relatives said Thursday that 79 Namibians
held prisoner by SWAPO have returned home in the past two weeks,
but more than 1,000 remain jailed in southern Angola.
   The Parents Committee of Namibia, whose family members were
detained by SWAPO, said the 79 came back unexpectedly along with
refugees returning in the big U.N. repatriation campaign.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890810-0178 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 0644EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DigestBriefs     08-10 0862</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Digest Briefs,0894</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, saying he doesn't want to miss
any signal that might lead to freedom for American hostages, is
again extending a hand to Iran while insisting he won't make any
deals.
   ``I hope I'm open-minded enough to talk and to exercise every
diplomatic channel I can to free these Americans,'' the president
told reporters Wednesday.
   However, Bush insisted he would do nothing ``that would put some
other American, perhaps in some other place, at some other time, at
risk, and that means trading off or negotiating for hostages.''
   As the president continued to press diplomatic efforts,
including talks through third parties with Iran, he urged all
American churches, synagogues and other places of worship to ``say
a special prayer this weekend'' for the hostages, their families
and for world peace.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some savers can expect less interest on their
deposits and families may soon find it a bit less expensive to buy
a home, as the government today begins spending $50 billion to
resolve the savings and loan crisis.
   President Bush signed legislation Wednesday committing American
taxpayers to an estimated $157 billion _ $600 for every man, woman
and child _ over the next 30 years to solve the nation's biggest
financial crisis since the Depression.
   ``We can and will preserve a safe, efficient and equitable
financial system for ourselves and ... for our kids,'' Bush said
before signing a bill providing money to cover more than $100
billion in S&amp;L losses over the past decade to speculative, and
often fraudulent, lending.
   The Treasury Department planned today to borrow the first $5
billion of a $20 billion downpayment to be made over the next seven
weeks to reduce an estimated $20 million in daily losses by
insolvent but still operating S&amp;Ls.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People in Felix Bloch's position often put a
coat over their heads or run the other way whenever a news camera
is pointed at them. But Bloch, the most visible spy suspect ever,
uses a different approach.
   He makes himself available to every lens and microphone.
   ``I've developed a real symbiotic relationship with the media,''
said Bloch, who has _ not by choice _ been leading a caravan of FBI
and news people since it was revealed he is suspected of spying for
the Soviet Union.
   Bloch's walks around Washington are attracting attention the way
Harry Truman's used to. Bloch made a trip to the cleaners Wednesday
and it was recorded by cameras. He went for a 22-mile hike Tuesday
and caused a coterie of Bloch watchers to go huffing and puffing
along.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Babies conceived in laboratories with the
high-tech help of fertility experts are just as likely to be normal
as babies made by amateurs in the traditional way, researchers say.
   The study was conducted to determine if infants conceived by in
vitro fertilization _ the so-called test-tube babies _ are more apt
to develop physical or mental abnormalities than other children,
said Dr. James L. Mills, a National Institute of Child Health and
Human Development researcher.
   ``The original question was, `are these children going to be
developmentally delayed?' The answer to that is very clearly not,''
Mills said Wednesday in a telephone interview. ``They did extremely
well.''
   In a study published this month in the Journal of Pediatrics,
Mills and a team of scientists from Eastern Virginia Medical School
compared the development of 83 children born as a result of in
vitro fertilization, or IVF, with 93 children born from normal
conception. The children were matched by age, sex, race, age of the
mother and other factors. They were all between 12 months and 30
months old.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tuition inflation is easing a bit at many
colleges, especially public two-year institutions, but a year at
the costliest private colleges will top $21,000, an annual survey
shows.
   The College Board, in its annual tuition survey released
Wednesday, found average charges heading 5 to 9 percent higher come
fall.
   At two-year public colleges, the increase will average 5 percent
to $842, slightly less than the 5.9 percent annualized rise in
consumer prices during the first six months of 1989.
   Average tuition and fees at four-year public institutions will
increase 7 percent to $1,694, with an additional $3,039 in average
room and board charges.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Mills Inc. says its new cereal is
nothing more than a breakfast food that can reduce cholesterol, but
Procter &amp; Gamble Co. thinks it should be tested as a drug if it's
going to make health claims.
   P&amp;G, which sells over-the-counter medicines, wants the U.S. Food
and Drug Administration to order General Mills to pull the cereal,
Benefit, off the market. It contends cereals should under the same
federal testing as drugs before health benefits such as reduced
cholesteral can be advertised.
   General Mills disagrees.
   ``It's a cereal that's made from grain. It's consumed like a
cereal. It's no different from any other cereal that's on the
marketplace that contains soluble fiber and has the ability to
lower cholesterol,'' General Mills spokesman Craig Shulstad said
Wednesday.
</TEXT>
