<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 0744EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-CityDogs Adv16   08-10 0763</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-City Dogs, Adv 16,0791</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wednesday PMs, Aug. 16, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dog Owners Find Ways to Cope in New York City</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pond in Brooklyn's Prospect Park is a quiet
spot, rimmed by tall oaks and a meadow. But early each morning it
goes to the dogs.
   Dogs by the hundreds are unleashed around it, many running
around a field before taking an early morning dip. Before 8 a.m.,
park police don't enforce the leash law, and the dogs don't waste
the precious time.
   ``All I have to do is say the word, `park,' and they are out the
door,'' said Allen Koppelman, owner of a greyhound and a Russian
wolfhound.
   The morning romps in the park are just one sign of the largely
unnoticed ``other society'' living in New York _ an estimated
600,000 dogs.
   Their owners form social groups, such as the Prospect Park Dog &amp;
Breakfast Club. They hire dog walkers, form dog play groups,
frequent canine clothing shops.
   When they meet, they discuss the peculiar trials of keeping a
pooch in the city, from pooper-scooper vigilantes to landlords who
won't let anything with four legs in the door.
   ``It's a whole other society in this city,'' said Joan
Chrysikopoulos, 30, who owns two miniature poodles. ``People buy
dogs coats, hats, have sweaters knit for them.''
   Dogs are big business, with several specialty shops in the Upper
East Side selling items costing hundreds of dollars.
   ``If they can afford to buy dogs for $1,500, they can afford to
take care of them,'' said Karen Thompson, owner of Karen's For
People and Pets, a pet accessory and dog grooming shop.
   Chrysikopolous believes there's another reason for spoiling
dogs. ``The guilt factor is tremendous. You know your dog can't go
outdoors when he wants to. I worry that they are so bored.''
   She has bought her dogs sweaters and raincoats. ``If it's below
50, it's definitely a sweater. They live in an apartment all day
and aren't used to the cold.''
   The raincoats may be more for show. ``I would never have put a
raincoat on a dog if we lived in the suburbs. Here there's more
peer pressure,'' Chrysikopolous said.
   The biggest issue for dog owners, though, is finding space for
their pets to run. Last fall, park police began enforcing the leash
law after many years of not doing so, writing $50 tickets to
violators.
   The reaction was swift. Dog groups formed, including
Chrysikopoulos' Carl Schurtz Park Dog Owners Group, and they
protested to park officials. Pro-leash groups formed to fight back.
   William F. Dalton, chief of citywide services for the Parks
Department, surprised by the intense feelings over dogs, held a
dozen meetings.
   The temporary solution was to not enforce the law until 8 a.m.
The parks department is also considering confined areas for dog
runs, longer weekend off-leash hours and even obedience tests where
no-leash licenses could be given for dogs that respond to their
master.
   Fran Lee, founder of Children Before Dogs, boils in anger at
this. Letting dogs run free, she said, increases the threat of
bites _ 8,000 are reported in the city each year _ and
dog-transmitted diseases, especially from excrement.
   ``I happen to love animals,'' she said. ``But I hate the animal
owners.''
   She chases owners who don't scoop up after their dogs. When one
woman refused her command, Lee says she picked up the poop and
dumped it on the woman's head.
   ``When a dog is pooping on the street, everyone is militant
about that,'' said 23-year-old Tina Caruso, who runs Dogsbuddy, a
dog walking service. ``They stand there and wait to see if you pick
it up. I make sure I'm standing poised with a plastic bag in my
hand.''
   Still, if there are hassles, dog owners also find rewards in
city living.
   Members of the Prospect Park Dog &amp; Breakfast Club bring bagels
and coffee while their dogs cavort.
   ``My dog is better socialized in the city than when we lived in
the suburbs,'' said Melanie Sutherland, talking about Morgan, a
border collie.
   Chris Panny, 34, said the park provided a dog play group for his
cocker spaniel, Zuckie.
   Someone threw a tennis ball in the water. Zuckie went out after
it, one of a half-dozen dogs with the same idea.
   ``Look at that! Look at that!'' Panny said. ``He's going to the
middle of the lake!''
   Zuckie mouthed the ball expertly. Owners all around clapped
appreciatively.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed PMs, Aug. 16</NOTE>
</DOC>
