<DOCNO> AP890810-0180 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 1032EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e PM-APonTV-Cannell Adv11   08-10 0887</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP on TV-Cannell, Adv 11,0905</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Friday PMs, Aug. 11, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Cannell Changes Course Again with `Top of the Hill'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stephen J. Cannell has created a couple dozen
television series, among them at least two sure to be included in
any history of television.
   In 1974, Cannell's ``The Rockford Files'' premiered, starring
James Garner as TV's first truly realistic private eye _ one who
ran credit checks on prospective clients and quit cases immediately
upon suffering any kind of physical threat. The critics loved it
and so did audiences.
   A decade later, Cannell created another ``different'' series,
featuring a rag-tag band of misfits who joined together to fight
the bad guys. ``The A-Team'' made a cultural icon out of Mr. T. The
show got huge ratings, but the critics hated it, labeling it
cartoonish, violent junk TV.
   Later, Cannell followed with ``Hunter,'' a hit in ratings that
was ignored or panned by the critics.
   Cannell rebounded with the critics two seasons ago with the
simmering, cerebral ``Wiseguy,'' starring Ken Wahl as a federal
agent deep undercover in various crime venues. It's up for five
Emmy awards.
   This coming season, Cannell takes another turn with ``Top of the
Hill,'' a thoughtful political drama starring William Katt
(``Greatest American Hero'') as an idealistic Californian who steps
in to take over his ailing father's congressional seat.
   The show will premiere next month on CBS.
   Cannell told a meeting of television critics that the show,
which has been in his mind for a few years, was based on the
real-life activist congressman Leo J. Ryan, D-Calif., who was
killed by followers of the Rev. Jim Jones when he went to Guyana to
investigate Jones' religious cult.
   Ryan, said Cannell, was an advocate for his constituency, not a
delegate. ``A delegate says, you elect me, I'll go to Washington,
I'll be your delegate. In two years, I'll come back, put my record
before you and you'll decide whether or not you want to return me
to the House. The advocate says, I will be your advocate. I will go
there, and if there is anything where you cannot get help, where
you are unable to use the system correctly to benefit yourself in a
situation where you've been wronged, then I will be your advocate.''
   Katt's Congressman Tom Bell is a Democrat, Cannell said, though
Bell's leaning to the liberal or conservative side will vary
depending on the issue with which he's presented. In the future,
those issues will include child custody conflicts, the media
feeding-frenzy over ethics violations, and the crumbling of
inner-city schools.
   Katt told the television critics he himself has not considered
running for office, but he would vote for a man like Bell, ``who
listens to his own conscience.''
   Cannell will have five shows on the air when the new season
opens. ``Hunter'' continues on NBC, ``Top of the Hill'' and
``Wiseguy'' are on CBS, and he has the continuing ``21 Jump
Street'' and the new ``Booker'' on Fox. This is not a record for
Cannell. He had five shows on the air in 1985, ``The A-Team,''
``Riptide,'' ``Hardcastle and McCormick,'' ``Hunter'' and
``Stingray.''
   Cannell, who writes many of the episodes of his shows, said he
prefers brainier stuff to the shoot-'em-ups like ``A-Team.''
   ``When I get to the part in a script where I have to do the old
shoot-out or the car chase or whatever it is,'' he said, ``that's
when I have to keep hitting myself in the head, you know, because
the fun part is to write the characters and the relationships and
the cerebral drama.''
   Cannell thinks ``the audience kind of got tired of car chases.
... I think Steve Bochco (`Hill Street Blues,' `L.A. Law'), who's a
dear friend of mine, went a long ways toward showing networks that
you could do different kinds of programming and still entertain.''
   ``Top of the Hill,'' not unlike Bochco's shows, will not shy
away from making political statements, but that's not its primary
purpose, Cannell said. ``I don't see my role here as inflicting my
sense of politics on anybody else, but rather to entertain you
through good dramas dealing with good relationships.
   ``I wouldn't know where I will eventually go with it,'' Cannell
said. ``But what I think I'm trying to say is that I think this
country could use a political figure as a hero to look up to, and
hopefully, Tom Bell can be that figure.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   ANOTHER MAN IN A DIFFERENT HOUSE _ You think there weren't
candidates pounding down the walls to be the new host of PBS'
``This Old House''? ``We had well over 400 resumes,'' said Russell
Morash, creator and executive producer of the popular fixer-upper
series. ``I heard from building inspectors who wanted the job. Got
a call from a brain surgeon. ... I heard from a well-known female
concert pianist. I heard from the guy that installed my burglar
alarm system.'' The man who finally got the job was Steve Thomas,
an author who had appeared in an episode of PBS' ``Adventure''
series. Former ``This Old House'' host Bob Vila left in a conflict
with the producers over his commercial endorsements.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri PMs, Aug. 11</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
