<FIRST>a e BC-APArts:Oz-Stars Adv11-13   08-10 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-AP Arts: Oz-Stars, Adv 11-13,0443</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv11</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv12</HEAD>
<HEAD>$Adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions, Aug 11-13 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-AP Arts: Wizard of Oz</HEAD>
<HEAD>Where Did All the Munchkins Go....?</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   What ever happened to the Witch, Dorothy and
the Scarecrow? Did their movie careers soar or plunge? Here's a
brief look at what became of the stars who brought such memorable
characters to the screen in ``The Wizard of Oz.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
  Judy Garland became a full-fledged star as Dorothy. After
co-starring with Mickey Rooney in youth musicals, she went on to
other musical productions such as ``Meet Me in St. Louis,''
``Easter Parade'' and ``Summer Stock.'' She also did dramas such as
``The Clock.'' But because of her erratic behavior she was fired by
MGM. In 1951, she made a smashing comeback at New York's Palace
Theater and starred in a remake of ``A Star Is Born.'' But her
career never fully recovered. She died in London in 1969 of an
accidental barbiturate overdose.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
  Frank Morgan, who played the Wizard, continued under contract
to MGM, usually as a befuddled bumbler. He died in his sleep in
1949 after starting the role of Buffalo Bill in ``Annie Get Your
Gun.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Ray Bolger, the Scarecrow, returned to the stage for ``Where's
Charley?,'' which he also did on film. He made other film musicals
such as ``April in Paris'' and ``Babes in Toyland,'' and was active
in television. He died in 1987.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Cowardly Lion Bert Lahr also returned to the theater for
musical comedies as well as the existentialist ``Waiting for
Godot.'' He appeared in the films ``Rose Marie,'' ``The Second
Greatest Sex'' and ``The Night They Raided Minsky's.'' He died in
1968.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Jack Haley, the Tin Man, made a few films during the 1940s and
did a cameo role in ``Norwood'' in 1970, under the direction of his
son, Jack Jr. He died in 1979.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Lillie Burke, who played the good witch Glinda, continued her
specialty of dithering dowagers in ``The Man Who Came to Dinner,''
``Father of the Bride'' and other films. The widow of producer
Florenz Ziegfeld died in 1970 after a long illness.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Margaret Hamilton never achieved the same notoriety of her
Wicked Witch, but she remained a busy character actress in such
films as ``My Little Chickadee,'' ``State of the Union'' and
``Riding High.'' She became a familiar figure as Cora, the small
town shopkeeper of the Maxwell House coffee commercials. She died
in 1985.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, Aug. 11-13</NOTE>
</DOC>
