<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 1328EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-Dinkins Adv13   08-10 1192</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dinkins, Adv 13,1220</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Aug. 13, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>David Dinkins: Mr. Mellow for Mayor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   He speaks carefully, quietly and with precise
diction. He is slow to criticize, slower to attack, temperate in
his positions. A calm and deliberative leader, friends say. Boring,
critics retort.
   The new Mr. New York?
   Could be. David Dinkins, avoiding the political pugilism that
made Edward I. Koch mayor, soon may walk off with Koch's job.
Should he win this year's election, Dinkins would be the city's
first black mayor _ and its most laid-back chief executive in a
long while.
   Consider his less-than-fiery rhetoric: ``I guess you think it's
best to just rifle off a thought without reflection,'' Dinkins
recently scolded Koch. ``It seems to me that reflection and
gathering of intelligence in order to make a judgment is highly
desirable.''
   That's a far cry from the sharp-tongued incumbent, whose
combative style has alternately charmed and offended his
constituents for a dozen years. As the prototypical brash New
Yorker, Koch has dominated city politics.
   But the city, beset by social problems from crime to drugs to
AIDS, may be ready for a more mellow approach: Polls say the
unassuming Dinkins, after one term as Manhattan borough president,
runs even with Koch and leads two other candidates in the race to
win the Sept. 12 Democratic primary.
   ``Ed is the quintessential hot candidate, and David provides the
perfect relief,'' said David Garth, Koch's political strategist.
``Dinkins' problem is whether he has a spark. Koch's problem is
that he's got too many sparks.''
   ``They say David Dinkins may be too nice of a guy. That's a hell
of a compliment,'' said Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., long a Koch
critic. ``Maybe New York has had enough of the damn political
reaction and overreactions.''
   If Koch faces voter disenchantment, Dinkins must confront his
own set of hurdles. Some critics question his qualifications and
his grasp of issues, and they raise his failure to pay taxes for
four years two decades ago.
   But Dinkins' greatest challenge, political tacticians say, is to
bridge racial tensions and assemble a coalition of voters _ blacks,
who comprise up to a third of the Democratic vote, whites and
Hispanics.
   ``David has got to walk a thin line between exciting the black
vote and inciting the white vote,'' said Steven Matthews, campaign
manager for mayoral candidate Harrison J. Goldin, the city
comptroller. ``Part of the difficulty is the perception, in the
political community at least, that the issues that concern black
voters and white voters are somewhat different.''
   If there are competing concerns _ Matthews suggested that white
voters are more worried about crime, blacks about social programs _
Dinkins' bland and conciliatory style may reassure wary voters.
``Instinctively, David reaches out,'' said Garth. ``It's a nice
quality.''
   Dinkins, for example, was co-director of Jesse Jackson's New
York state campaign in last year's Democratic presidential race _
but he has not brought Jackson into the city to speak for him this
year. Dinkins thus has avoided exposing the old wounds of some
black and Jewish voters, caused by Jackson's 1984 reference to New
York as ``Hymietown'' and Koch's claim that Jews ``have got to be
crazy'' to support Jackson.
   Instead Dinkins has stressed comity, even to the exclusion of
specific plans for the city's seemingly intractable problems. While
his opponents at a recent debate stressed police protection,
government corruption and failing schools, Dinkins took his own
tack:
   ``What is essential is that we strive hard to understand the
backgrounds and heritages of each other _ hopefully so as to come
one to love another, but if not to love one another, certainly to
understand one another,'' he said. ``With understanding will come
respect. The absence of respect, or disdain that some have for
others, is a large measure of our difficulty.''
   For Dinkins, such comments constitute an elliptical criticism of
Koch. ``Clearly the tone of civility,'' he said at another debate,
``is set or is not set at the highest levels of government at City
Hall.''
   The mayor attacks far more directly: He has accused Dinkins of
tax evasion for failing to file in 1969, 1970, 1971 and 1972, and
questioned whether Dinkins can be trusted to manage the city's $26
billion budget.
   Dinkins has apologized for his tax ``procrastination,'' which
cost him an appointment as deputy mayor in 1973, noted that it
occurred long ago and pointed out that he was not charged with any
crime. But even his supporters concede the issue is a fair one for
opponents to raise.
   Critics have raised other matters, too, accusing Dinkins of
indecision and fiscal inexperience. He suggested easing
restrictions on public-employee strikes, then dropped the idea; he
suggested cutting the city sales tax, then backed off when reminded
that its proceeds are earmarked for bonds.
   But he largely has avoided controversy, running a leader's race,
racking up union and political endorsements, accentuating the
positive. ``It's the typical campaign of a front-runner,'' said
Matthews. ``It also happens to fit David perfectly.''
   Long an active Democrat, Dinkins, 62, rose to prominence only
recently, winning the borough presidency _ the job is equivalent to
a county executive _ in 1985 after two losing tries. He spent the
previous decade as city clerk and served one term in the state
Assembly in the mid-1960s.
   His own poor background, Dinkins has said, explains his concern
for social welfare. Born in Trenton, N.J., he came to New York with
his mother, a domestic, after his parents separated when he was 6.
He tells of selling shopping bags on the street, shining shoes,
washing dishes and cars and working his way through college and law
school. ``I can never remember not having a job,'' he said.
   Whether he will have the city's top job remains to be seen.
Dinkins would needs at least 40 percent of the primary vote to
avoid a runoff with the second-place finisher; he had just about 40
percent in recent polls, and has led in polls on a hypothetical
runoff against Koch.
   Should he win the nomination, Dinkins likely would face Rudolph
W. Giuliani, a former prosecutor who leads for the Republican
nomination, in November. Dinkins leads Giuliani in polls, and he
has a built-in advantage: Democrats outnumber Republicans by 5-1.
   An unknown factor is the extent to which some whites will refuse
to vote for a black candidate. ``Of course it's a concern. There
are members of ethnic groups who will never go for another,'' said
Rangel, who is black. But he said that does not apply to the
overwhelming majority of New Yorkers.
   Garth held a similar view: ``There are some racial overtones in
everything you do, but this is not a knee-jerk city on the racial
issue.''
   And Percy Sutton, a former borough president and the first
serious black candidate for mayor, in 1977, said Dinkins has the
qualities to overcome prejudice.
   ``In a city that is strident, David Dinkins has been a calming
voice,'' Sutton said. ``He is a person who brings people together.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Aug. 13</NOTE>
