<TEXT>
   The UAL Corp. board of directors said it was
``premature'' to make a decision on a $5.21 billion takeover bid
from Los Angeles investor Marvin Davis, but the unsolicited suitor
called the response encouraging.
   Industry analysts had predicted the parent of United Airlines
would reject the offer, but the board issued a brief statement
Wednesday night after a nearly six-hour meeting that neither
rejected nor accepted the billionaire's proposal for a negotiated
deal.
   The Chicago-based company said Davis set forth ``a highly
conditional proposal'' to buy the company for $240 a share. It was
the first time UAL disclosed the value of the offer, which would
total about $5.21 billion based on UAL's 21.7 million shares
outstanding. Industry analysts previously speculated the offer was
worth at least $200 a share.
