<FIRST>r f PM-TreasuryAuction     08-10 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Treasury Auction,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yields Fall in Huge Sale of Debt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yields on 10-year Treasury notes fell in
Wednesday's auction to the lowest level in nearly three years as
the government continued a series of debt auctions intended to
raise $44.5 billion this week.
   The average yield was 8.03 percent, down from 9.18 percent at
the last such auction on May 10.
   It was the lowest rate since 10-year notes averaged 7.25 percent
on Nov. 5, 1986. The notes will carry a coupon interest rate of 8
percent with each $10,000 in face value selling for $9,979.60.
   A total of $9.76 billion in notes was sold out of bids totaling
$18.68 billion.
   Wednesday's auction will be followed by the sale of $9.75
billion in 30-year bonds in minimum denominations of $1,000 on
Thursday.
   On Tuesday, the government sold $10.03 billion in three-year
notes with average yields at 7.93 percent, the lowest level in 18
months and down from 9.12 percent at the last auction on May 9.
   The auctions are part of the regular sales done once every three
months to refinance the government's debt. They were made possible
last week when Congress voted to raise the national debt limit by
$70 billion to $2.87 trillion through Oct. 31. By then, Congress
hopes to complete work on a bill boosting the Treasury's permanent
borrowing authority to more than $3.1 trillion.
   In addition, this week the government will offer a special
short-term debt security of $15 billion which will include the
first $5 billion raised to pay for the savings and loan bailout.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
