<FIRST>r f PM-BAT-Farmers     08-10 0347</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BAT-Farmers,0360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anglo Group Proposes Trust To Oversee Farmers Insurance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's Anglo Group PLC has proposed setting
up a three-member voting trust to oversee Farmers Group Inc. as
part of its bid for BAT Industries PLC, an apparent move to thwart
U.S. insurance opposition.
   An Anglo Group subsidiary, Holyake Investments Ltd., has offered
$21.6 billion, none of it in cash, for the British tobacco,
financial services, retailing and paper conglomerate.
   The bid is being reviewed by U.S. insurance regulators because
BAT owns Farmers, the Los Angeles-based insurance company BAT
acquired late last year for $5.2 billion.
   Anglo Group said Wednesday in a letter to insurance
commissioners in the nine states where Farmers does busines it had
proposed three trustees for the voting trust that would hold
Farmers until its sale.
   Holyake _ made up of Anglo-French financier Sir James Goldsmith,
British investor Jacob Rothschild, Australian investor Kerry Packer
and other investors _ has said it would sell Farmers if its BAT
acquisition goes through.
   The sale would be subject to the approval of the state insurance
commissioners, and under the proposal, the trustees would oversee
management of the company in the interim.
   Holyake has filed nine lawsuits seeking to take the bid's
insurance aspects away from state regulators and place them in
federal court.
   The three proposed trustees are Daniel J. Evans, a former U.S.
senator from Washington; Shirley M. Hufstedler, a lawyer and former
U.S. education secretary; and David M. Sherwood, former president
of the Prudential Insurance Co. of America and currently president
of the New York Insurance Exchange.
   ``The appointment of these individuals, completely independent
of Anglo and Holyake and any related parties, will serve to
underscore the independence we propose for Farmers,'' Anglo Group
Chairman Albert J. Dunlap said.
   Former U.S. Treasury Secretary William E. Simon was quoted in
the Wall Street Journal on Wednesday as saying he is a potential
buyer for Farmers.
   Simon, who leads an independent investor group that has been
involved in several leveraged buyouts, also emerged as an equity
investor in the BAT bid.
</TEXT>
