<DOCNO> AP890810-0200 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 0233EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-AirlineTakeovers Bjt   08-10 0802</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Airline Takeovers, Bjt,0830</SECOND>
<HEAD>Airline Industry Gripped by Takeover Fever</HEAD>
<HEAD>Graphic under AIRMERGE in GraphicsNet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The seeds sown by deregulation of the U.S.
airline industry are bearing fruit, as a renewed takeover frenzy
could bring a major reshaping of the business, experts say.
   Many industry watchers believe intense competition spawned by
the easing of regulations in 1978 has made some carriers highly
desirable properties and turned others into desperate seekers of
merger partners.
   The results are likely to be further consolidation, although a
number of experts don't expect ticket prices to jump radically as a
result in the near future.
   ``Things are exciting at this point,'' said Louis Marckesano, an
airline analyst for the investment firm Janney Montgomery Scott
Inc. in Philadelphia. ``Now we've seen the domino effect as it goes
through each of the (airlines).''
   Within the past week:
   _United Airlines parent UAL Corp. received a buyout proposal
from investor Marvin Davis, and troubled Pan Am Corp. indicated it
also might be interested in merging with UAL.
   _A Pittsburgh-based manufacturing company revealed it owned 6.6
percent of Midway Airlines and might consider a takeover of the
Chicago-based regional carrier.
   _An investor group completed its $4 billion buyout of Northwest
Airlines parent NWA Inc.
   _Frequently rumored takeover target USAir Group Inc. completed
its merger with Piedmont and separately sold a major stake to
``white knight'' investor Warren Buffett.
   The latest trend comes after a lull following an earlier merger
wave sparked by deregulation. That wave saw a severe consolidation
of the industry, as big carriers such as NWA, Texas Air Corp.,
Delta Air Lines Inc. and Trans World Airlines Inc. swallowed up
such airlines as People Express, Republic, Ozark and Western in
order to meet the competition of the newly wide open markets.
   Now, successful airlines such as Northwest and United have
become hot properties stalked by big-time investors, unions and
rival airlines.
   On the other hand, those considered victims of deregulation,
such as Pan Am and Eastern, have been forced to change course in
order to survive.
   Financially weak Pan Am, for example, has said it needs to merge
with another carrier to survive. The company unsuccessfully
proposed a merger with NWA, and Pan Am Chairman Thomas Plaskett
said Wednesday the carrier would now consider making a bid for UAL.
   Eastern, rocked by a strike that forced it to seek bankruptcy
court protection, has undertaken a plan to reorganize as a smaller,
more efficient carrier. Eastern is owned by Texas Air.
   The takeover frenzy comes against a backdrop of increasingly
restive airline unions. Eastern Airlines pilots, Machinists union
members and flight attendants have entered the sixth month of a
strike, and there are rumblings of a possible walkout against
Northwest by its 5,000 pilots, who have been without a contract for
2{ years.
   The unions, dipping into their pension funds, also have jumped
on the takeover bandwagon. Pilots at United made a $4.5 billion bid
for the airline in early 1987 and recently indicated they remained
interested in some form of ownership. And the 20,000-member
Machinists union local at Northwest was one of the suitors for NWA.
   Would-be airline buyers must reckon with a government regulatory
policy that has so far proven more stringent under the Bush
administration than under the Reagan White House.
   Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner has indicated the
government might not look kindly on airline buyouts that load up
the companies with new debt. For example, he has expressed concern
that the acquisition of NWA might have a ``substantial adverse
impact'' on NWA's financial structure, by among other things,
jacking up its debt to about $3.7 billion.
   Skinner also has warned that the government would closely
scrutinize the possible competitive impact of the sales of assets
such as routes.
   ``It looks as though we have a real secretary of transportation
now,'' said economist Alfred E. Kahn, former head of the defunct
Civil Aeronautics Board and widely regarded as the main architect
of airline deregulation. Kahn had been critical of what he saw as
an overly lenient policy toward mergers under the Reagan
administration.
   After the latest takeover wave, the industry could look
radically different and even more consolidated, analysts say.
   Marckesano said many mid-sized carriers such as Midway, which
compete with the majors and the tiny commuter lines, are facing
turbulent times and could be swallowed up.
   But consolidation isn't expected to raise fares, which have been
steadily rising in recent months amid strong passenger traffic and
may have peaked for the near term, analysts say.
   A rare summer air fare war broke out last week, as several major
carriers matched a weekend discount program begun by Continental
Airlines.
   ``Fares obviously had jumped very substantially ... The carriers
are clearly beginning to encounter resistance,'' Kahn said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
