<DOCNO> AP890810-0201 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 0251EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Hooker-Bankruptcy     08-10 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hooker-Bankruptcy,0521</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parent Of Bonwit Teller, B. Altman Chains Files for Bankruptcy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bonwit Teller and B. Altman department store
chains and their parent company, L.J. Hooker Corp., have filed for
bankruptcy court protection, citing debt problems that caused
concern among the chains' suppliers.
   But several other Hooker subsidiaries were not included in the
filing late Wednesday in U.S. Bankruptcy Court in New York, a
company representative said.
   L.J. Hooker said it has retained the management firm Sigoloff
and Associates to run the company during the Chapter 11 bankruptcy
proceedings. The firm has rehabilitated a number of troubled
companies, L.J. Hooker said.
   L.J. Hooker is a subsidiary of Hooker Corp., an Australian
company with major U.S. retail and real-estate development
interests. For several months the the parent company has
experienced severe financial problems, and in late July it said it
was turning its operations over to a court-appointed liquidator in
Australia.
   Hooker blamed its troubles on sluggish U.S. consumer spending,
high Australian interest rates and exchange rate fluctuations.
   In a statement Wednesday, Sanford Sigoloff of the management
firm said the bankruptcy filing would allow L.J. Hooker to
restructure and repay debts, which total about $1.2 billion.
Sigoloff is a former chairman of the Wickes Cos. Inc., a retailing
and manufacturing company.
   Hooker said the bankruptcy filing was prompted by the inability
to reach an agreement with lenders to refinance its unsecured debt.
   The statement said several Hooker developments, including Retail
Projects of South Carolina, and store chains, including Birmingham,
Ala.,-based Parisian Department Stores and Houston-based Sakowitz,
were not included in the bankruptcy filing.
   David McAdam of Sitrick and Company, a public relations firm
representing Hooker, said late Wednesday that it will be ``business
as usual'' for holdings that are part of the filing.
   ``They will continue to build or sell whatever it is they build
or sell,'' McAdam said. ``It just puts a freeze on all previous
creditors and gives the company breathing space to reorganize and
go forward.
   ``If they were nailing boards a week ago, they'll be nailing
boards tomorrow,'' he said.
   McAdam said employees will be paid as usual at Hooker
subsidiaries included in the bankruptcy filing.
   Sigoloff said it is unclear what steps will be taken in the
reorganization.
   ``It is important for everyone to understand that Chapter 11
does not mean we are going to close all of the operations of the
corporation or that all Hooker employees are going to lose their
jobs,'' Sigoloff said.
   ``Daily operations will continue as usual, stores will remain
open, and transactions which occur in the ordinary course of
business will go on just before the filing,'' he said.
   Under Chapter 11, a company obtains a federal court order that
frees it from the threat of creditors' lawsuits until it can
develop a plan to put its finances in order. While the
reorganization proceeds, the activities of management must be
approved by the court. The ultimate reorganization plan must be
accepted by a majority of the creditors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
