<DOCNO> AP890810-0202 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 0809EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-UAL Bjt   08-10 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UAL, Bjt,0599</SECOND>
<HEAD>UAL Corp. Says It's Too Early to Decide on Takeover Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES WEBB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Los Angeles investor Marvin Davis says he's
encouraged by UAL Corp.'s noncommittal response to his $5.21
billion takeover bid _ a move that apparently leaves the company
open to other offers.
   Following a special meeting Wednesday that lasted into the
night, the UAL board of directors said it was ``premature'' to make
a decision on what it called Davis' ``highly conditional proposal''
to buy the company for $240 a share.
   It was the first time UAL, the suburban Chicago-based parent of
United Airlines, disclosed the value of the offer, which would
total about $5.21 billion based on UAL's 21.7 million shares
outstanding.
   Davis responded with a brief statement through his company,
Davis Corp., that said, ``We were encouraged by the board's
response and look forward to meeting with the company and its
representatives as soon as possible.''
   Bids from other investors eyeing UAL are likely to follow,
analysts said.
   ``The overture has thrust the company into play, obviously, and
there's really no turning back,'' said Timothy Pettee, an airline
industry analyst with Merril Lynch Capital Markets. ``The company
has got to pursue some ... financial transaction that maintains the
current stock prices.''
   In composite New York Stock Exchange trading Wednesday, UAL
stock surged $24.62{ to close at $243.87{ a share amid rumors that
Davis' bid was worth $240 a share. UAL shares have leaped more than
$100 in the past year.
   After a nearly six-hour meeting, the UAL board issued a short
statement Wednesday night saying it had determined that ``while it
was premature to make a decision as to whether a sale of the
company to Mr. Davis or any other party at the present time would
be appropriate, it was desirable to explore all possible financial
and strategic alternatives'' including remaining independent.
   ``It has always been and continues to be the desire of the board
to promote the long-term growth of United Airlines as a major U.S.
air carrier,'' UAL Chairman Stephen M. Wolf said in the statement.
   Wolf said the board would take into account the interests of its
shareholders, customers and employees ``in any decisions on its
future operations, growth and ownership.''
   Spokesmen for Davis and UAL refused to elaborate on their
statements. They would not say whether a meeting had been arranged
between the parties or what the next step might be.
   UAL is an attractive takeover target because it owns 80 percent
of its 408-jet fleet, which can be sold to finance debt from a
takeover.
   The nation's second-largest carrier, behind American Airlines,
also has a vast route network in the Pacific, the world's
fastest-growing air-travel market.
   But Merrill Lynch's Pettee said Davis is not necessarily a
strong suitor.
   ``Davis is playing the stock market and he's playing it very
adroitly,'' Pettee said. ``He hasn't given any indication that he
is serious about taking over the company, judging by his actions
with NWA.''
   Davis, who owns a considerable portion of UAL stock, reaped $30
million on his unsuccessful attempt to takeover Northwest Airline's
parent, NWA Inc., earlier this year. A group led by Los Angeles
investor Alfred Checchi acquired NWA for $3.65 billion.
   One possible scenario for UAL, according to Wall Street
observers, is that management, employees and the company's largest
shareholder, Saul Steinberg, will join forces in a leveraged buyout.
   Steinberg and Wolf are longtime business associates and friends.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
