<FIRST>r f BC-Coca-Cola-NewZealand     08-10 0180</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Coca-Cola-New Zealand,0188</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coca-Cola to Acquire New Zealand's Largest Soft Drink Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Coca-Cola Company plans to acquire Oasis
Industries Ltd., New Zealand's largest soft drinks company and
Coca-Cola bottler, for a price in excess of about $130 million.
   Coca-Cola, in a joint venture with C-C Bottlers Limited of
Adelaide, Australia, is to acquire the company for 225 million in
New Zealand dollars.
   Oasis Industries will continue to bottle Coca-Cola products in a
large part of New Zealand. Oasis also will continue to sell
Schweppes' branded products under its licensing arrangement with
Schweppes International and Oasis' own brands.
   A statement from Coca-Cola said the joint venture bottling
company will be managed by C-C Bottlers Limited.
   ``This joint venture represents a further commitment by The
Coca-Cola Company to the development of its soft drink business in
the South Pacific,'' said John Hunter, president of The Coca-Cola
Company's Pacific Group.
   The acquisition took effect Wednesday.
   Lion Nathan Ltd., the parent company of Oasis, recently
announced plans to divest its soft drinks interests to concentrate
on brewing and retailing.
