<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Gain Sligtly Ahead of Crop Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures were mostly higher
early today on the Chicago Board of Trade as traders staked out
their positions or took to the sidelines ahead of an Agriculture
Department crop report.
   The report, scheduled for release in Washington at 3 p.m. EDT,
will doubtless project substantially larger corn and soybean
harvests than last year, when drought cut deeply into the crops.
   The early gains in the soybean market also reflected perceptions
that the Soviet Union recently bought soybean meal from Brazil,
analysts said.
   Some soybean buying also was linked to worries about the
relatively dry weather so far this month in the Midwest, where
soybean pollination is well under way and weekly showers are needed
to keep the process moving along.
   In early trading, wheat was { cent lower to 1 cent higher with
the contract for delivery in September at $3.95{ a bushel; corn was
{ cent to 1} cents higher with September at $2.24} a bushel; oats
were 1 cent to 1{ cents higher with September at $1.37{ a bushel;
soybeans were 2 cents to 8 cents higher with August at $6.02 a
bushel.
   Cattle futures were broadly mixed while pork futures were mostly
lower in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .07 cent lower to 1 cent higher with August at
74.60 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent to .20 cent lower
with August at 84.80 cents a pound; hogs were .15 cent lower to .13
cent higher with August at 46.67 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .02 cent to .22 cent lower with August at 24.90 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled mixed on Wednesday while pork futures
retreated.
</TEXT>
