<FIRST>r f PM-DaysInn 1stLd-Writethru f0037 08-10 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Days Inn, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0037,0485</SECOND>
<HEAD>Company Agrees to Buy Days Inn</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 6th graf pvs, `Days' sales ...,' with 2 grafs to include
1984 purchase price and size of hotel chain.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A unit of Reliance Group Holdings Inc. said it
has agreed to sell Atlanta-based Days Inns Corp. to the hotel
chain's largest franchise, Tollman-Hundley hotels.
   Under terms of the deal, Tollman-Hundley would pay $90 million
in cash and assume $675 million in debt.
   Brian T. Martin, a spokesman for Reliance Group Holdings, owner
of the limited partnership Reliance Capital Group, said Wednesday
that all that remains to close the deal is for Tollman-Hundley to
arrange financing.
   ``We have a willing buyer and a willing seller,'' Martin said.
``Assuming financing, there is every reason to believe the deal
will go forward.''
   Michael A. Leven, Days' president and chief operating officer,
had said several months ago that the company was for sale. He noted
that the business of Reliance, whose chairman is Wall Street
financier Saul Steinberg, is investments, not hotel operating.
   Days' sales last year amounted to $1 billion. The chain operates
858 hotels and has 522 others under construction.
   Reliance bought the chain in 1984 from the Cecil B. Day family
for $615 million.
   Leven said Wednesday that Monty D. Hundley, a partner of
Tollman-Hundley, assured him that Days' headquarters would remain
in Atlanta with the company's entire management team intact.
   ``He asked me if I'd stay and I said only if we stayed in
Atlanta,'' Leven said. Hundley is largely responsible for Leven
being named Days' president.
   Shortly after Reliance acquired Days in 1984, Hundley
recommended Leven for the job. The two men were introduced by a
mutual business acquaintance. Leven was hired by Chairman and Chief
Executive Officer Henry A. Silverman, who is also president of
Reliance Capital.
   Leven said Silverman would stay with Reliance and resign from
Days.
   He said he was confident that financing would be arranged. He
said Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in New York is serving as
Tollman-Hundley's investment banker.
   ``They are hotel people very committed to the Days Inn system,''
Leven said of Tollman-Hundley. ``I feel that if this purchase goes
through, it will remove once and for all the spectre of being sold.
We will be able to continue the direction of the company without
the fear of a new owner coming in and changing things.''
   ``We just want to see them do more of the same,'' said Hundley.
``The people running the company are doing a heck of a job, and
we'd like to see them continue.''
   Drexel next week would review the terms of the proposed
transaction. If the firm approves, it would then line up financing.
Usually the process takes 30 to 60 days.
   Tollman-Hundley owns 129 hotels, including 48 Days Inns.
</TEXT>
