<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 1232EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-ReynoldsTobacco-Layoffs     08-10 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Reynolds Tobacco-Layoffs,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>RJR Nabisco's Tobacco Unit Cutting 1,600 Jobs</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. (AP) _ R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co. will cut
1,640 jobs as part of a restructuring of the company's North
Carolina operations, an executive of the RJR Nabisco Inc. division
announced Thursday.
   ``We're adjusting our size and changing our structure to match
today's level of business and become a stronger, more competitive
company,'' said R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Chairman James Johnston.
``These have been difficult and painful decisions.''
   Of the layoffs, 825 are salaried and 700 are hourly, while
another 115 are temporary and part-time positions. The company said
employees would be notified Thursday.
   ``The U.S. tobacco industry has been experiencing a slow decline
for several years,'' Johnston said. ``In our case, consumer market
share has been declining gradually and our cigarette production has
exceeded consumer sales.''
   Regular and full-time employees will receive severance pay and
continued benefits for at least eight months. Most salaried
employees will be released immediately, although some will remain
for several months to allow for an orderly transition, Johnston
said. Most hourly employees will be released from mid-August
through mid-October.
   Employees who are 50 and older and whose age and years of
service total 70 or more will be eligible for immediate, unreduced
retirement benefits.
   After the layoffs, R.J. Reynolds Tobacco will have 12,500
employees, including just under 10,000 in its Winston-Salem-area
operation.
   The Winston-Salem, N.C.-based company also is reducing the
number of outside contractors, mainly computer programmers, by 140.
   Its corporate parent, RJR Nabisco, has been in the process of
streamlining its operations since it was bought out for $25 billion
last year by the investment firm Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
