<FIRST>r f BC-EmployeeAbuse     08-10 0354</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Employee Abuse,0366</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Former Shuwa Employees Allege Abuse at Hands of Execs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two former employees of Shuwa Investments
Corp. accused executives of the huge real estate unit of Japan's
Shuwa Corp. of beating and verbally abusing them and sexually
harassing one of them.
   Accountant Hajime Tanioka alleged in a Superior Court suit filed
last week and amended Wednesday that he was repeatedly assaulted by
Executive Vice President Takeshi Shiratori and President Takaji
Kobayashi of the Los Angeles-based firm.
   Tanioka alleges that Kobayashi, son of the parent company's
founder, struck him with a telephone and calculator, punched him in
the stomach and threw a set of keys at him when Kobayashi learned
that Tanioka was seeing a former employee.
   Tanioka further alleges that Kobayashi also struck him on the
head with a book while the accountant was recovering from an eye
injury after Tanioka refused to work overtime.
   The suit also alleges that Shiratori hit the accountant with a
ruler and rolled up newspapers and magazines. Tanioka left the firm
in 1987, said his attorney, J. Patrick Maginnis.
   In a suit filed late last year in Superior Court, a former
company secretary says she was assaulted and sexually harassed by
Vice President Kiichiro Kobayashi, the cousin of Takaji Kobayashi.
   Dawn Marie Stover alleges that Kiirchiro Kobayashi fondled and
ogled her and made sexual suggestions. The suit also alleges that
Kiichiro Kobayashi hit, slapped, pinched and struck Ms. Stover with
rulers and other objects.
   Kiichiro Kobayashi denied the allegations in Stover's suit and
in turn accused her of beating him and berating him with derogatory
and racist epithets. Ms. Stover quit in 1988.
   Shuwa Investments lawyer Craig B. Jorgensen said he had not seen
the suit against Tanioka, but added, ``We expect to deny the
charges and defend it vigorously.''
   Takaji Kobayashi declined to comment. Kiichiro Kobayashi and
Shiratori did not return telephone messages.
   Shuwa Investments has bought large, well-known commercial
properties in the United States, including the Arco Towers in Los
Angeles, the ABC Building in New York and the former U.S. News &amp;
World Report headquarters in Washington.
</TEXT>
