<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 1314EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Oil     08-10 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Oil,0533</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shell Posts 60 Percent Profit Jump, BP Reports 34 Percent Gain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Royal Dutch-Shell Group of Companies and
British Petroleum Co. PLC reported sharply higher second-quarter
profits Thursday due to higher crude oil prices and gains in
refining and petrochemicals.
   Royal Dutch-Shell, based in The Hague, the Netherlands, and in
London, said its after-tax profit soared 60 percent to 1.01 billion
pounds, or $1.65 billion, from 633 million pounds, or $1.03
billion, in the same period a year ago. Royal Dutch-Shell does not
give consolidated per share figures.
   Revenue in the three-month period totaled 16 billion pounds, up
18 percent from 13.6 billion pounds in the comparable 1988 period.
   London-based British Petroleum, which owns Cleveland-based
Standard Oil Co., said its second-quarter net income rose 34
percent to 477 million pounds, or 9 pence _ 15 cents _ a share,
compared with 357 million pounds, or 5.9 pence _ 10 cents _ a
share, in the same period a year ago.
   Revenue rose about 15 percent to 7.39 billion pounds from 6.45
billion pounds.
   Both companies' financial statements are based on British
accounting methods and cannot be directly compared to those of most
American companies. Inventories are valued on the basis of first in
first out (FIFO), instead of the typical American system of last in
first out (LIFO).
   The companies call earnings calculated by the FIFO method
historical cost earnings. Those calculated by the LIFO method are
called ``current cost'' results.
   On a current cost basis, Royal Dutch-Shell's net income rose 38
percent to 912 million pounds from 660 million pounds.
   Earnings per share for Royal Dutch Petroleum Co., the Dutch arm
which controls 60 percent of the company, amounted to 4.22
guilders, or $1.98, compared with 2.65 guilders, or $1.24.
   Per-share earnings for Shell Transport and Trading Co. PLC, the
British arm which controls 40 percent of the group, rose to 11.1
pence a share from 7 pence a share.
   The companies attributed the gains to higher crude oil prices, a
more favorable dollar exchange rate and improved refining margins.
   For the first six months of the year, Royal Dutch Shell's net
income rose 57 percent to 2.29 billion pounds from 1.46 billion
pounds in the first half of last year.
   On a current cost basis, first-half earnings came to 2.02
billion pounds, up 29.5 percent from 1.56 billion pounds.
   Revenue in the first six months totaled 30.3 billion pounds, an
11.4 percent gain from 27.2 billion pounds a year earlier.
   On the current cost basis, British Petroleum's net income rose
15 percent to 371 million pounds from 323 million pounds.
   For the first six months of the year, British Petroleum said its
net income spurted 76 percent to 1.09 billion pounds, or 19.3 pence
a share, from 620 million pounds, or 10.3 pence a share, in the
comparable period a year ago.
   Current cost earnings came to 752 million pounds, up 3 percent
from 731 million pounds.
   BP's first-half revenue rose 9 percent to 14 billion pounds from
12.9 billion pounds a year ago.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
