<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Stocks 1stLd-Writethru f0032 08-10 0156</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0032,0161</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares Fall as Buying Interest Wanes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices fell on London's Stock Exchange
Thursday, as buying interest waned.
   The market started weaker but recovered momentum around midday
after a batch of supportive earnings reports and speculative buying
interest on a handful of stocks.
   However, fear that Wall Street would open weaker deterred
investors and encouraged some profit-taking. The descent was
accentuated by market makers trimming prices in an effort to spark
buying interest.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index ended down
13.1 points, or 0.6 percent, at 2,347.3.
   The Financial Times 30-share index closed down 10.6 points at
1,961.4. The Financial Times 500-share index fell 6.99 points to
close at 1,322.93.
   Volume came to a fairly buoyant 574.5 million shares, up from
520.9 million shares Wednesday.
   By London's close, the Dow Jones industrial average had
recovered from opening lows and was up 1.89 points at 2,687.97.
</TEXT>
