<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 1441EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-LTV     08-10 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-LTV,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>LTV's Divestitures Send Earnings Down 75.5 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   LTV Corp., three years into one of the nation's
largest bankruptcies, said Thursday its second-quarter earnings
fell 75.5 percent, in part because of allowances for discontinued
steel and aircraft operations.
   The steelmaker and defense contractor reported that its net
profit for the quarter ended June 30 dropped to $30.3 million, or
18 cents a share, from $123.9 million, or 89 cents a share, in the
same quarter last year.
   Second-quarter revenue tumbled to $1.66 billion from $2.06
billion a year earlier.
   LTV said the revenue decline reflects the June 1988 sale of its
Warren, Ohio, steel plant and exclusion of 1989 results for the
steel bar division, which is to be sold.
   The company blamed its earnings decline on a $50 million charge
for estimated cost increases in various aircraft components, a
$43.7 million decline in steel operating income because of the
reduction of those operations, and a $30 million special charge for
canceling construction of a flexible composite center for
production of advanced aircraft components.
   The 1988 second quarter included a $30 million special charge
for costs of discontinuing medium and heavy military truck business.
   ``The major disappointment of the (latest) quarter was a loss
reported for LTV's aircraft products group, caused primarily by $50
million of charges related to performance on commercial aircraft
programs and projected cost increases in fixed-price development
programs for military aircraft,'' said LTV Chairman Raymond A. Hay.
   For the first half of the year, net profit was $106.9 million,
or 73 cents a share, compared with a net loss of $2.01 billion a
year earlier.
   First-half sales fell to $3.28 billion from $3.94 billion a year
earlier.
   The 1988 first half included a $2.26 billion charge because of a
change in accounting for pension fund obligations.
   LTV said Wednesday it had reached agreement with its major
private creditor over the size of its claim against LTV.
   LTV said Cyprus Minerals Co., a mining company based in Denver,
had agreed that it had a $505 million claim against LTV instead of
the original $1.7 billion it was seeking.
   The size of the claim will be used in determining how Cyprus
Minerals will share in the proceeds from the bankruptcy proceeding.
   The government agency which insures pension funds has the
largest outstanding claim against LTV, claiming that the company
owes more than $2 billion for three underfunded pension funds.
   LTV, which has been under bankruptcy protection for three years,
has until Nov. 8 to propose a reorganization plan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
