<DOCNO> AP890810-0222 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 1426EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     08-10 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0275</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices were widely mixed today in another
session dominated by takeover news and rumors.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 10.24 to 2,696.32
by 2 p.m. on Wall Street.
   But losers outnumbered gainers by about 7 to 6 in nationwide
trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 660 up, 778
down and 501 unchanged.
   Analysts said the market in general suffered a bit of a letdown
following its inability to make a decisive move past the 2,700
level in the Dow Jones industrial average over the past few days.
   They also noted concern about a recent upswing in interest rates.
   Heavy activity persisted, however, in stocks reported or rumored
to be takeover targets.
   UAL, which said it would explore a wide range of options in
light of a takeover bid from investor Marvin Davis, climbed 9[ to
253. The stock ended last week at 164{.
   Among other prominent airline issues, AMR gained 1 to 77~ and
Delta Air Lines was up ] at 79}.
   Paramount Communications, widely discussed as a possible
acquisition target, moved up } to 62~.
   Elsewhere, Procter &amp; Gamble jumped 4~ to 123[, accounting for a
substantial amount of the Dow Jones industrials' gain. The company
reported higher quarterly earnings.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
slipped .09 to 193.11. At the American Stock Excchange, the market
value index was down .05 at 381.10.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 133.09 million shares with two
hours to go.
