<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 1435EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern Bjt   08-10 0792</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern, Bjt,0816</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pilot Crossovers Increase After Leadership Discusses Ending Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A trickle of picket-line crossovers has become a
steady stream since the Eastern Airlines pilots' leadership
discussed ending their 5-month-old strike, sources said Thursday,
boosting management efforts to rebuild without the unions.
   In meetings beginning Sunday, striking pilots resoundingly
rejected proposals to go back to work. However, sources who didn't
want to be identified said the number of pilots crossing the picket
lines neared 600, up from 200 at the strike's beginning on March 4
and from 385 a week ago.
   Pilots union spokesman Ron Cole said that number ``sounds
inflated,'' but he agreed crossovers have increased.
   ``I wouldn't call it dissension (in the union),'' Cole said. ``I
think people are making their individual choices based on economic
hardships after being on strike 5{ months.''
   Cole suggested that the returning pilots won't work well with
newly hired pilots, mixing newly returned veterans with recruits
will cause safety problems, and that many recruits will leave
Eastern because they are losing company-promised rapid advancement
to the veterans.
   Sources familiar with the pilots returning to work this week
said some have expressed disaffection with the union leadership and
belief the strike has been doomed.
   The leadership of Eastern's Air Line Pilots Association met
Thursday in Washington to discuss strategy and review the series of
overwhelming votes this week for continuing the strike.
   Company spokesman Robin Matell said Eastern has stopped
releasing the number of crossovers.
   ``We just decided not to go with a daily box score, as a company
policy decision during a period of meetings the pilots have held
around the country,'' Matell said. ``There are a number of pilots
returning, but we really would like to see how things shake out in
the next several days.''
   Matell added there's no question Eastern is well on track to
meeting its goal of 1,700 pilots by year's end.
   The company has said it has graduated some 300 newly hired
pilots from training and has nearly 800 pilots in training, which
lasts six to eight weeks.
   Machinists union leader Charles Bryan declined comment Thursday
on the pilots' situation. Earlier this week, Machinists senior
general chairman Wally Haber called the pilots ``the backbone of
the strike.''
   The pilots' solidarity with the Machinists, who struck after 18
months of federal mediation, stunned Eastern management, which
hoped to keep flying without the Machinists. With only 200 of the
3,600 pilots flying, Eastern struggled to fly 10 percent of its
pre-strike schedule of nearly 1,100 flights daily and filed for
Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization March 9.
   A rebuilding plan proposed to Eastern's creditors envisions an
airline two-thirds its pre-strike size flying 800 daily flights.
Eastern expects to increase its daily schedule from 350 to 390
flights on Aug. 15, and reach 800 by year's end. Eastern had to
lease planes and pilot crews from sister carrier Continental
Airlines this month.
   The unions, including striking flight attendants, predicted
Eastern couldn't rebuild without them and are backing a buyout bid
by Chicago businessman Joseph Ritchie, which has been spurned by
Eastern's parent Texas Air Corp.
   However, local and national pilots union leaders last week
raised the possibility of ending the strike as a way to protect
jobs and union strength. Most members reacted bitterly to the
suggestion, after months of pledges never again to work for Texas
Air Chairman Frank Lorenzo.
   ``The troops are very, very upset. The Eastern pilots are
absolutely livid about the thought of going back to work,'' said a
pilots union activist who asked not to be identified.
   Eastern ALPA Chairman Jack Bavis reportedly told his members in
Miami Sunday night they should consider ending the strike.
   ``If he (Bavis) is advocating capitulation in any way, he is
representing a distinct minority view,'' said John Anderson, an
ALPA spokesman in New York. ``There aren't that many jobs to go
back to if we capitulate to Frank Lorenzo. We'd be going back to
unsafe cockpits.''
   Eastern says it wouldn't have jobs for all the striking pilots
if they returned because it won't lay off the newly hired pilots.
Union officials have indicated they believe pilots returning from a
strike must be given their jobs back over recruits still in
training.
   Meanwhile, the pilots union leadership is trying to rally its
troops with plans Saturday to build ``the longest moving picket
line in U.S. history'' in a march beginning in Miami and continuing
up the East Coast.
   ``It really can be viewed as the thread of continuity for all
the activities that are going on,'' Cole said. He added that the
demonstration, including rallies in cities along the way, will
culminate in the Labor Day parade in New York.
</TEXT>
