<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 1542EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Psychiatrist-InsiderTrading     08-10 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Psychiatrist-Insider Trading,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Psychiatrist Pleads Innocent To Insider Trading Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A New York psychiatrist pleaded innocent
Thursday to charges that he used inside information from a patient
to make a profitable stock deal.
   Robert Howard Willis, 55, entered his plea at his arraignment in
U.S. District Court in Manhattan on an indictment that charges him
with 46 counts of securities and mail fraud.
   U.S. Magistrate Naomi R. Buchwald released Willis on his own
recognizance and ordered him to surrender his passport.
   The indictment, filed July 26, alleged that Willis received
non-public information during the course of a patient consultation
about an attempt by Sanford I. Weill, the former chief executive
officer of Shearson, Loeb Rhoades, to become head of BankAmerica
Corp.
   The unidentified woman patient discussed the matter with Willis
because if Weill was successful, it could have caused ``substantial
upheaval'' in the personal life of the patient and her husband, the
indictment stated.
   Using the information, Willis allegedly bought $171,130.50 worth
of BankAmerica stock between Jan. 14, 1986, and Feb. 6, 1986.
   The indictment alleged he sold the stock Feb. 21, 1986, after a
public announcement about Weill's attempt to become a BankAmerica
executive, making a profit of $27,475 for himself and family
members.
   Weill, who now heads Primerica Corp., was unsuccessful in his
bid to head BankAmerica. Neither Weill or BankAmerica was charged
with any wrongdoing.
   Willis, of Tenafly, N.J., has an office in Manhattan.
   He was charged with 23 counts of securities fraud and 23 counts
of mail fraud. If convicted, he faces up to five years in prison
and a $250,000 fine on each of the 46 counts.
</TEXT>
