<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 1620EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-Corvette Adv13   08-10 0742</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Corvette, Adv 13,0771</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday Aug. 13 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Next Generation of 'Vette: GM's Answer to the Ferrari Crowd</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. Chairman Roger B. Smith is
among the first in line for one. Aerobics instructor Abbie Miller
of St. Paul, Minn., has her order in. Former South Dakota Gov. Bill
Janklow says no thanks.
   They're talking about the newest generation of the Chevrolet
Corvette, the ZR-1 with an engine that puts more punch into
America's original two-seat muscle car than ever before.
   Detroit's automotive press has been gushing praise for the car,
calling it GM's high-tech answer to the Porsche and Ferrari without
their higher pricetags.
   But don't expect to see thousands of ZR-1s screaming down the
interstates at top speed with youthful joyriders at the wheel.
Chevrolet marketing experts anticipate buyers will be predominantly
college-educated males in their 40s with household incomes of at
least $100,000.
   With a production schedule of 3,000 for the 1990 model year and
a price between $50,000 and $60,000, the car ZR-1 is aimed at
luring at least some would-be customers of the European luxury
performance cars.
   ``We've clearly got enough interest in this thing to sell out
this year once we set the price and get on with it,'' said
Chevrolet spokesman Ralph Kramer.
   The final price is to be determined late this month, when the
ZR-1 begins rolling off the assembly line in Bowling Green, Ky.
   Its 5.7-liter, 32-valve, V-8 engine with 375 horsepower can
propel the car from 0 to 60 mph in 4.2 seconds, less time than it
takes a phone to ring three times.
   The car also comes with a special switch that shuts off half the
valves, commonly called a ``valet key'' that temporarily tames the
monster engine and prevents hot-dogging car jockeys from roaring
around the parking lot.
   The ZR-1 doesn't have the most horsepower of any assembly-line
production Corvette _ a 1967 model with 435 horsepower did _ but it
does have the highest top speed of any Corvette at about 180 mph.
It has fuel economy ratings of 16 mpg in city driving and 25 mpg on
the highway, good enough to avoid the federal government's
``gas-guzzler'' tax.
   It's the latest in a long line of Corvettes, dating to the
original 300 produced in 1953. Since then, more than 900,000 have
been made and they've created a cult with its own magazines, clubs
and rallies devoted to the car's ground-hugging bullet appearance.
   ``I guess it's the excitement, it's like a dream car,'' said
Mrs. Miller, 49, who owns two other Corvettes and has had her order
in for a ZR-1 since July 24.
   As head of GM, Smith gets first dibs. He's had his order in
since late last year.
   The ZR-1 originally was planned as a 1989 car, but engineering
and marketing decisions pushed the introduction back to this month,
making it a 1990 in the automotive industry's calendar year.
   Despite the car's power, highway patrol officers evidently
aren't too worried about an outbreak of ZR-1 speed-mania.
   ``I think that irresponsible people can't afford that car, and
those people who can afford it aren't likely to risk their
investment by driving dangerously on the highway,'' he said.
``Aside from that, regardless of how fast they are, they aren't
faster than a radio.''
   Janklow, governor of South Dakota from 1978-86, is one Corvette
owner who's had some experience with law enforcement officers on
highways. He owns a 1969 T-top 427 Corvette, a car he's unafraid to
push to its limit.
   ``I was notorious for my speeding,'' said Janklow, who has
received about 100 speeding tickets. ``It's just a great
automobile. It's America's one unique touch of freedom.''
   He talks enthusiastically about his 1969 Corvette, but the ZR-1
evidently packs too much muscle for him _ Janklow said he doesn't
plan to buy one.
   Even Joe Pike, a retired Chevrolet merchandising manager and
former editor of the Corvette News magazine, said he has some
reservations about the newest model's power.
   ``I don't think there's half of 1 percent of the people who buy
that car who are capable of driving it,'' he said. ``I don't think
I could drive it anymore even if you could find a place to drive it.
   ``It's the kind of car that belongs on the Autobahn in
Germany.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday Aug. 13 and thereafter</NOTE>
