<DOCNO> AP890810-0227 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 1552EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-TartCherries     08-10 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tart Cherries,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tart Cherry Crop Below Estimates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAIGE St. JOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Association Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRAVERSE CITY, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's tart cherry crop is
coming in below estimates because of frost kills and delayed
ripening in Michigan, marketers said Thursday.
   Government forecasters had predicted Michigan would grow 190
million pounds of a total of 261 million pounds of tart cherries to
be produced in the United States this year.
   Instead, the Michigan crop now being harvested looks to be as
low as 160 million pounds, even less than last year's
drought-stunted crop, said Phil Korson of the Cherry Marketing
Institute in Okemos.
   Not all of the drop is from spring crop damage. Korson said 1989
crop estimates from the U.S. Department of Agriculture likely were
too high.
   Michigan ordinarily produces more than three-fourths of the
nation's tart cherries. The smaller crop should not affect
consumers, who see tart cherries in pie fillings and baked goods,
Korson said.
   ``I don't think we're looking at a shortage. We're looking at
stable prices, really,'' he said.
   Processors are getting about 49 cents a pound for tart cherries,
the same as last year when a drought cut Michigan production to 180
million pounds, Korson said.
   Uneven ripening from a cool spring, immature fruit because of a
fungus that denuded many trees and bruised fruit from high winds
have caused widespread quality problems.
   ``I would say in every producing area, some of the crop couldn't
find a market,'' said John Minnema, president of Cherry Central
Cooperative Inc., in Traverse City. ``It's unusual for that to be
so widespread.''
   A full crop would have pushed national cherry production 24
million pounds ahead of what Korson said the market could handle,
and that would have driven prices down. Cherry growers already
complain it costs more to produce their fruit than they can get for
it.
   Many growers have cut back on pruning, mowing and spraying to
save money. That has further reduced production, said Norman
Veliquette, president of the Great Lakes Packing Co. in Antrim
County. ``Growers have cut agricultural practices to the bone,'' he
said.
   A late frost in the heart of Michigan cherry country this spring
killed enough blossoms that Gov. James Blanchard declared a farm
disaster in four counties so growers there can apply for federal
aid.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890810-0228 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 1632EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-CorvettePlant Adv13   08-10 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Corvette Plant, Adv 13,0538</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday Aug. 13 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bowling Green Plant Produces World's Corvettes</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Corvette</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBBIE NEWBY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOWLING GREEN, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jack Taylor has a saying: You don't
drive a Corvette, you wear it.
   ``If you've ever sat in one, you kind of have that feeling,''
said Taylor, director of manufacturing engineering at the General
Motors Corp. Corvette plant at Bowling Green. ``It's a statement of
people's success in life.''
   Taylor calls his 1966 blue Corvette ``an adult pacifier.''
   The cars, introduced to America in 1953, pacify such well-known
adults as Mike Love of the Beach Boys; members of the singing group
Alabama, who own four; basketball great Michael Jordan and
entertainer Sammy Davis Jr.
   The car also is the choice of such renowned speedsters as Al
Unser, Mario Andretti and Chuck Yeager. Signed photographs of their
Corvettes hang on walls in the plant's visitors' area and the snack
bar.
   This year, Chevrolet will make 26,411 cars at the only plant
that assembles the Corvette, America's first two-seat sports car.
Of these, 3,000 will be the souped up ZR-1 model.
   Corvette assembly moved to Bowling Green from St. Louis in
August 1979. The first car rolled off the Kentucky line in 1981.
The 1-million-square-foot plant, about the size of 22 football
fields, houses more than a mile of railroad track and 7{ miles of
conveyor track.
   About 1,250 workers and 65 robots produce 14 cars an hour _ a
piddling line speed in a world where many factories crank out a car
a minute.
   ``We want to make our quality the best it can be,'' said Jim
Case, a trim utility auditor. ``A person who owns a Corvette is
proud of his car. He knows everybody looks at it and wants one.''
   The price of Corvette is pushing it farther from reach.
   The standard coupe now sells for about $34,000; the convertible
for $40,000. The ZR-1, which begins production later this month,
will cost $50,000 to $60,000.
   Nonetheless, the Corvette plant tour is popular, even among
people who could never afford to buy the car. Jane Bowlin, a GM
spokeswoman, said about 40,000 people toured the plant last year,
making it one of Kentucky's most crowded tourist attractions.
   The plant also is a shrine among Corvette owners. Some leave
their calling cards.
   Corvette club patches fill a display case outside the visitors'
area. They're from the Thunder Basin Corvettes in Gillette, Wyo.;
the Vette Set from Decatur, Ill., and the Flood City Corvettes from
Johnstown, Pa.
   ``Some people take their vacation to come here,'' Mrs. Bowlin
said, pointing out patches from Hawaii, Switzerland and Sweden.
   Inside the Corvette plant, some things are done a little
differently from others.
   During the painting process, the outside of the car is covered
in plastic wrap and workers apply a flat black paint to hidden and
hard-to-reach parts, including the firewall and the inside of the
hood.
   ``We want to cover all the places only Corvette nuts would
look,'' paint supervisor Bob Breeding said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Sunday Aug. 13 and thereafter</NOTE>
</DOC>
