<FIRST>r f BC-InsiderTrading     08-10 0184</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Insider Trading,0191</SECOND>
<HEAD>Orange County Exec Faces Inside-Trade Charge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Orange County executive has been charged
with making more than $11,000 for himself, a friend and his
mother-in-law through illegal insider trading.
   The civil suit, filed in federal court here by the Securities
and Exchange Commission, accuses Hadson Corp. executive Dennis W.
Evans of buying 2,000 shares of Ultrasystems of Irvine the day
before the company announced it was merging with Oklahoma-based
Hadson.
   Evans, 37, of Mission Viejo also tipped off a friend and his
mother-in-law, who bought 1,800 shares, according to the suit,
which was filed Monday. Neither of them is charged.
   The value of the three individuals' combined shares rose by
$11,115 after the deal was announced Oct. 30, 1987, the suit says.
   The SEC charges that Evans, controller of Ultrasystems' defense
and space subsidiary, was privy to numerous discussions and
meetings about the Hadson merger.
   Through a secretary, Evans declined to discuss the suit
Thursday. Ultrasystems issued a statement saying Evans denied any
wrongdoing and noted that the company itself was not named in the
complaint.
</TEXT>
