<HEAD>Crop Futures Close Mostly Higher Ahead of USDA Report</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, ``The report ... the crops,'' with 2 grafs to
UPDATE with USDA crop projections; picks up 6th graf: ``At the ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices closed moderately higher
while grain futures finished mostly higher Thursday on the Chicago
Board of Trade in subdued trading ahead of an Agriculture
Department crop report.
   Firmer cash markets supported the futures, along with signs of
increased export demand for U.S. corn.
   But analysts said most of the buying reflected position-evening
by traders seeking to reduce their exposure to potential price
swings resulting from the crop report.
   ``People are just kind of waiting to see what we've got,'' Dale
Gustafson, an analyst with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc., said before
the report's release.
   The report, released in Washington at 3 p.m. EDT, after the
market's close, projected a 24 percent increase in the soybean
harvest and a 49 percent larger corn harvest than last year, when
drought cut deeply into the crops.
   The corn and soybean numbers were slightly lower than traders
had expected and could prompt buying of futures contracts on Friday.
   At the close, wheat was 2{ cents lower to 1 cent higher with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.96 a bushel; corn was
unchanged to 1} cents higher with September at $2.24} a bushel;
oats were 1\ cents to 1} cents higher with September at $1.37} a
bushel; soybeans were 3{ cents to 9{ cents higher with August at
$6.03{ a bushel.
</TEXT>
