<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 2037EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-AutoElectronics     08-10 0191</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Auto Electronics,0199</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ford Exec Sees $2,000 Worth of Electronics in Cars of Late 1990s</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TRAVERSE CITY, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   By the late 1990s, cars will have
$2,000 worth of electronics in them, far more than the $900 or so
now, a Ford Motor Co. executive said Thursday.
   ``Our planning is geared toward this eventuality when electronic
systems control all vehicle functional systems,'' said Frank E.
Macher, general manager of the Ford Electronics Division.
   Today, electronics control such components as fuel consumption,
engine cooling and braking in some cars, and the time needed to
develop these electronic systems is shrinking.
   While much of future vehicles may be controlled by electronics,
consumers may be turning away from a plethora of gadgets, Chrysler
Corp.'s design chief said earlier this week.
   Thomas Gale, a Chrysler vice president, said in an interview at
the company's headquarters in Highland Park, Mich., that the
explosion in electronics has produced cars that are complex to
operate and mind-boggling options.
   Gale said Chrysler's new cars of the mid-1990s probably will be
simpler with fewer options offered.
   Macher spoke at a management seminar sponsored by the University
of Michigan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
