<SECOND>BC-Earns-Retail,0229</SECOND>
<HEAD>May Department Stores Posts 24 Percent Profit Gain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   May Department Stores Co., one of the largest
retailers in the United States, Thursday reported a 24 percent
increase in its second-quarter profit.
   For the quarter ended July 29, the retailer had after-tax
earnings of $78 million, or 55 cents per share, up from $63
million, or 42 cents a share, from the same period a year earlier.
   Revenue for the three months increased to $2.04 billion, as
compared with $2 billion for the same period last year.
   The company said the earnings included figures from its discount
segment, 120 Caldor stores and 73 Venture stores, which it
considers to be discontinued operations because of plans announced
June 27 to sell those units. Those discount stores contributed $7
million in profit in the second quarter.
   Earnings for the first half were $141 million, or $1 per share,
on revenue of $4 billion, up from earnings of $125 million, or 83
cents per share, on revenue of $3.6 billion in the first six months
of 1988.
   At the end of the second quarter, the company operated 3,092
stores, including three new department stores and 37 new Payless
ShoeSource stores. Department store operations include Lord &amp;
Taylor and 13 other regional department store chains located
throughout the country.
