<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     08-10 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0498</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher in U.S. Trading</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished higher in domestic dealings
Thursday after putting in a mixed performance overseas.
   Gold prices were mostly higher. On the Commodity Exchange in New
York, gold bullion for current delivery rose 40 cents to close at
$367.30 a troy ounce. Republic National Bank of New York quoted a
late bid for gold at $366 an ounce, unchanged from Wednesday's late
bid.
   Trading was lackluster overseas and in early U.S. dealings amid
anticipation of Friday's reports on producer prices and retail
sales figures for July.
   But technical factors triggered successive waves of buying that
drove the dollar higher across the board at home.
   Adding to the buying enthusiasm was another runup on Wall
Street, where the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials closed above
the 2,700 mark, said Scott Horwitz, a vice president at the Bank of
Boston's New York office.
   Volume was moderate. Lou Calvello, a trader at Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc., noted that there was ``not a lot of depth to the
market. People are waiting for the economic numbers to give them
direction.''
   A rumor swept through the market that the producer price index
would slip by as much as 0.4 percent, contrary to initial estimates
of a rise of as much as 0.2 percent.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar rose 0.20 yen to a closing 139.05 yen. Later in
London, it was quoted at 139.10 yen. In New York, the dollar rose
to 139.80 yen, from 138.95 yen on Wednesday.
   In London, the dollar fell against the pound. The pound rose to
$1.6280 from $1.6170 late Wednesday. In New York, the pound fell
against the dollar, to $1.6188 from Wednesday's $1.6225.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Wednesday's rates: 1.9055 West German marks, up from 1.8935; 1.6395
Swiss francs, up from 1.6315; 6.4415 French francs, up from 6.4000;
1,372.00 Italian lire, up from 1,361.50, and 1.1711 Canadian
dollars, up from 1.1710.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe compared with late Wednesday's
rates: 1.8905 West German marks, down from 1.9000; 1.6325 Swiss
francs, down from 1.6350; 6.3955 French francs, down from 6.4050;
2.1275 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1440; 1,356.75 Italian lire,
down from 1,364.40; 1.1722 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1710.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $365.75 dollars a troy
ounce, unchanged from late Wednesday. In the afternoon, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $366.25.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $366.35, up from $365.00 late
Wednesday. Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.18 to close at a bid
$367.06.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.16 a troy
ounce, up from Wednesday's $5.15. On New York's Comex, silver
bullion for current delivery rose to $5.163 a troy ounce from
$5.155.
</TEXT>
