<SECOND>AM-Earns-Procter &amp; Gamble,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>Procter &amp; Gamble Reports Increased Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Procter &amp; Gamble Co.'s top managers said
Thursday they are pleased with higher profits and sales during the
past fiscal year, but concerned about increasing competition in
global markets during the 1990s.
   For the fourth quarter, the Cincinnati-based comsumer products
manufacturer had worldwide sales of $5.4 billion, a 9 percent
increase from the nearly $5 billion of a year earlier. Quarterly
net earnings were $171 million, a 22 percent increase from $140
million a year ago. Earnings per share were 99 cents, up from 82
cents.
   The company reported an 11 percent increase in worldwide sales
and an 18 percent increase in earnings for its fiscal year ended
June 30.
   Global sales totaled $21.4 billion compared with $19.3 billion
the previous year, while net earnings increased to $1.2 billion
from $1.02 billion in 1988. Earnings per common share totaled
$7.12, up from $5.96 the previous year.
   P&amp;G said its fourth-quarter earnings this year were reduced by a
$78 million after-tax provision to cover costs of closing a Chicago
plant and certain departments at other U.S. plants.
   P&amp;G paid dividends of $3 per common share for the fiscal year, a
25-cent increase from last year. In February, the annual rate of
dividend payment was increased to $3.20, marking the 33rd
consecutive year of increased dividend payments.
   The company makes and sells laundry and cleaning products,
personal-care products including pharmaceuticals, food and beverage
items and other products for commercial use.
