<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 2036EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-CEOSurvey     08-10 0243</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-CEO Survey,0252</SECOND>
<HEAD>CEOs Think Federal Budget Deficit Is Serious</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A majority of the nation's top executives polled
recently say the federal budget deficit is a serious problem and
advocate higher taxes on tobacco and alcohol, according to a report
released Thursday.
   The Conference Board said 87 percent of the 400 chief executives
who participated in its survey characterized the deficit as at
least a serious problem, while nearly half labeled it a very
serious problem.
   About 90 percent of the executives think higher excise taxes on
tobacco and alcohol would be a good source of new revenue.
   More than 80 percent called for substantial cutbacks in farm
supports, foreign aid and national defense. Roughly half called for
small cuts in current spending levels for Social Security, Medicare
and benefits for children, the unemployed and veterans, while a
third opposed any trimming of those areas.
   Some 80 percent of the executives proposed cuts in welfare
spending, with roughly a third recommending large cuts.
   ``While excise taxes get fairly high marks, there are distinctly
mixed feelings about the benefits of a major change in the U.S. tax
system,'' said Preston Townley, chief executive of the Conference
Board.
   According to the survey, 42 percent of the executives favor a
value-added tax while 35 percent oppose it. Among other findings,
70 percent oppose boosting the personal income tax rate, and over
74 percent say thumbs down to higher corporate income taxes.
</TEXT>
