<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     08-10 0202</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0209</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy futures finished higher on the New York
Mercantile Exchange Thursday as the market shook off the lethargy
of recent days and made some of its best gains.
   The September contract for West Texas Intermediate, the
benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil, rose 38 cents to $18.59 a barrel
after rising 9 cents in Wednesday's session. The October contract
gained 32 cents Thursday to close at $18.29.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, September
unleaded gasoline rose 0.85 cent to 51.43 cents a gallon and
heating oil for September delivery advanced 0.78 cent to 50.21
cents a gallon. Refined products for delivery later in the year
showed smaller gains.
   Energy brokers said reports of tighter crude oil supplies and
improved refining margins in Europe helped push prices up.
   A report that British Petroleum Co. PLC might discontinue spot
sales of Alaska North Slope oil also helped buoy prices.
   ``A lot of people on the West Coast swap Alaska North Slope oil
for WTI,'' said Jack Unger, trader with Merrill Lynch Energy
Futures. ``Now that might not be available so they have to grab for
crude to put in their refineries.''
</TEXT>
