<SECOND>AM-Money Funds, 1st Ld-Writethru,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>Money Funds Rose $1.24 Billion in Latest Week</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 3 grafs to ADD that funds hit record and CORRECT
previous record; picks up 4th graf, The Investment .... Interest rate figures
reported by Donoghue's Money Fund Report are for week ended Tuesday. All
other figures are for the week ended Wednesday.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the nation's 463 money market mutual
funds rose $1.24 billion to a record total in the latest week, the
Investment Company Institute said Thursday.
   The rise, to $338.35 billion in the seven-day period ended
Wednesday, followed a revised $4.32 billion increase in the funds'
assets the previous week, according to the Washington-based mutual
fund trade group.
   The revised total of $337.11 billion in the week ended Aug. 2
had been the previous highest total.
   The Investment Company Institute said that in the latest week,
assets of 227 general purpose funds rose $676.8 million to $107
billion, assets of 95 broker-dealer funds increased $1.52 billion
to $144.81 billion, and assets of 141 institutional funds fell $954
million to $86.53 billion.
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds fell in
the week ended Tuesday to 8.33 percent from 8.47 percent the
previous week, according to Donoghue's Money Fund Report, a trade
journal based in Holliston, Mass.
   The 30-day average yield fell to 8.53 percent from 8.64 percent,
Donoghue's said.
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was
41 days, down from 42 days, Donoghue's said.
   Separately, the newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of
100 leading commercial banks, savings and loan assocations and
savings banks in the nation's 10 largest markets showed the
effective annual yield available on money market accounts rose to
6.47 percent as of Wednesday from 6.45 percent a week earlier.
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective
annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super
NOW accounts, fell to 5.11 percent from 5.12 percent.
   Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 8.27
percent on six-month certificates of deposit, down from 8.32 the
previous week. Yields were 8.25 percent on 1-year CDs, down from
8.32 percent; 8.17 percent on 2{-year CDs, down from 8.23 percent;
and 8.16 percent on 5-year CDs, down from 8.21 percent.
</TEXT>
