<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     08-10 0692</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0717</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Report Seen Stemming Slide In Corn, Soybean Prices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A government report projecting smaller corn and soybean harvests
than grain traders had expected will likely boost futures prices,
ending a month-long decline in the markets for those commodities,
analysts said Thursday.
   Grain and soybean futures advanced modestly Thursday on the
Chicago Board of Trade before the Agriculture Department crop
report was released, and much stronger gains were predicted for
Friday.
   On other markets, coffee futures prices fell sharply; energy
futures rose; precious metals were higher; and livestock and meat
futures were mixed.
   In Chicago, wheat settled 2 cents lower to } cent higher with
the contract for delivery in September at $3.95} a bushel; corn was
\ cent to 2 cents higher with September at $2.25 a bushel; oats
were 1\ cents to 1{ cents higher with September at $1.37{ a bushel;
soybeans were 3 cents to 9\ cents higher with August at $6.03\ a
bushel.
   The crop report covered a variety of agricultural commodities,
but futures traders in Chicago were most interested in the corn and
soybean numbers because supplies of those important commodities
were hit especially hard by last year's drought.
   The USDA projected a corn harvest of 7.35 billion bushels, 49
percent greater than last year's 4.92 billion-bushel crop. The
agency projected a soybean harvest of 1.91 billion bushels, 24
percent above last year's harvest of 1.54 billion bushels.
   Traders were anticipating projections for a 53 percent increase
in corn production and a 26 percent larger soybean crop.
   The difference between the market's expectations and the USDA
numbers alone would probably be enough to spark a wave of buying
Friday. But analysts predicted a bigger reaction based on
indications that most speculators were positioned to profit from
falling prices.
   ``I think this is going to unnerve these guys and blow them out
of the water,'' said Dale Gustafson, an analyst in Chicago with
Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   He predicted opening gains of up to 20 cents a bushel in the
soybean market and 8 cents a bushel in the corn market.
   The USDA projected production of all wheat at 2.04 billion
bushels, up 13 percent from the 1988 harvest of 1.81 billion
bushels.
   Coffee futures sank on New York's Coffee, Sugar &amp; Cocoa Exchange
amid renewed aggressiveness on the part of producers seeking to
increase their share of the recently deregulated market.
   Esther Eskanasy, an analyst with Cargill Investor Services Inc.,
said Colombia, the world's second-largest producer, had dropped its
offering prices by 2 cents a pound on Thursday.
   Coffee prices already are at 13{-year lows near 80 cents a pound.
   Analyst Kim Badenhop of Merrill Lynch Capital Markets Inc., said
prices were likely to fall further.
   ``We're looking at something like 76 cents or so as possiblity
on the downside and fundamentally I can't argue with that,'' he
said.
   Coffee settled 2.36 cents to 2.75 cents lower with September at
79.97 cents a pound.
   Energy futures prices climbed on the New York Mercantile
Exchange, partly on technical factors and partly on optimism
generated by the Energy Department's weekly supply report, which
showed lower-than-expected stocks of crude oil and gasoline.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 20 cents to 38 cents
higher with September at $18.59 a barrel; heating oil was .58 cent
to .78 cent higher with September at 50.21 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .75 cent to 1.30 cents higher with September at 51.43
cents a gallon.
   On New York's Commodity Exchange, gold settled 20 cents to 40
cents higher with August at $367.30 a troy ounce; silver was 0.8
cent to 0.9 cent higher with September at $5.193 a troy ounce.
   Live cattle futures finished .17 cent lower to .45 cent higher
on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange with August at 74.67 cents a
pound; feeder cattle were .23 cent lower to .05 cent higher with
August at 84.67 cents a pound; hogs were .45 cent lower to .15 cent
higher with August at 46.60 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.42 cent lower to .20 cent higher with August at 24.50 cents a
pound.
</TEXT>
