<FIRST>r f AM-Mexico-Inflation     08-10 0160</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Inflation,0168</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mexico's Monthly Inflation Rate Lowest This Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The July monthly consumer price rise in
Mexico _ 1.0 percent _ was the lowest so far this year, according
to Thursday news reports.
   Mexico City newspapers reported that the Consumer Price Index,
released by the Banco de Mexico, showed a 16.8 percent inflation
rate for the 12-month period ended in July.
   The central bank report said July's inflation was the lowest of
the year and that the 12-month rate is the lowest since December
1978.
   The rates ``continue a downward trend in annualized inflation
which started in February 1988,'' the report said.
   In February 1988 the government began a wage-price freeze to
tame inflation. In July, President Carlos Salinas de Gortari
renewed the pact until March 31, 1990.
   The government took the steps to curb inflation that reached a
record 159.2 percent in 1987. Consumer prices rose by 51.7 percent
in 1988 under the plan.
</TEXT>
