<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 2221EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-CaterpillarExecutive     08-10 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Caterpillar Executive,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>CEO Who Saved Caterpillar to Retire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George A. Schaefer, who led Caterpillar Inc.
to record sales and profits after absorbing nearly $1 billion in
losses in three years, is retiring next June as chairman and chief
executive officer.
   Schaefer, who describes himself as an ``old bookkeeper,'' told a
group of Caterpillar executives last month he will retire shortly
after he turns 62 on June 13, three years shy of Caterpillar's
mandatory retirement age.
   Caterpillar spokesman Gil Nolde told the Journal Star of Peoria
that Schaefer had always planned to retire at age 62, although he
never revealed his plans publicly. Schaefer was out of town
Thursday and unavailable for comment.
   Schaefer announced his decision early to give the board of
directors plenty of opportunity to consider a replacement, Nolde
said.
   When Schaefer took the helm of Caterpillar in 1985, the company
was in a sea of red ink. It lost $953 million from 1982 to 1984 and
slashed its workforce 40 percent worldwide, from a peak of 88,000
to 53,000. Nine plants were closed.
   Under Schaefer, Caterpillar put together $624 million in profits
the next three years and in 1988 posted the highest sales and
profits in the company's 64-year history. Caterpillar earned $616
million in 1988 on sales of $8.18 billion.
   The company also launched an ambitious $1.2 billion plan to
automate all 36 million square feet of Caterpillar factory space.
   Caterpillar has improved its relations with its unionized
workers. After a devastating seven-month strike by 20,000 United
Auto Workers members in 1982-83, Caterpillar has successfully
negotiated two new labor contracts without a strike.
   The dramatic rebound of the nation's largest manufacturer of
earth-moving equipment led industry analyst John Stark, editor and
publisher of Stark's Off-Highway Ledger, to call Schaefer
``probably the best manager the construction machinery industry has
ever had.''
   Schaefer is a Covington, Ky., native who joined Caterpillar in
1951 upon graduation from St. Louis University as an auditor and
accountant.
</TEXT>
