<FIRST>r f AM-MackLayoffs     08-10 0154</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mack Layoffs,0159</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mack Trucks To Slow Production At Four Plants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HAGERSTOWN, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A downturn in the heavy-duty truck market
is triggering layoffs and production slowdowns at four Mack Trucks
Inc. plants in Maryland, South Carolina, Pennsylvania and Canada, a
company spokesman said Thursday.
   The company expects to announce next week how the production
cutbacks will affect Mack employees at plants in Hagerstown,
Winnsboro, S.C., Macungie, Pa., and Oakville, Ontario.
   Company officials do not know how long the layoffs would last or
how many there will be, but market conditions were expected to
remain soft through the end of the year, said James Santanasto,
manager of public relations for Mack Trucks, based in Allentown, Pa.
   James Williams, president of United Auto Workers Local 171 in
Hagerstown, said he did not want to speculate on how many workers
would be furloughed, but said he thought it would be at least 200
workers.
