<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 1935EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommoditiesProbe 1stLd-Writethru   08-10 0627</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodities Probe, 1st Ld-Writethru,0647</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two More Traders Plead Guilty in Commodities Scams</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHERI T. PRASSO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Swiss franc traders pleaded guilty Thursday
and a third pleaded innocent to charges stemming from an undercover
FBI probe of fraudulent trading at the world's largest commodities
markets.
   William Walsh, 23, and Mark Fuhrman, 39, traders in the Swiss
franc pit at the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, each pleaded guilty
to one count of wire fraud and one count of making pre-arranged
trades in violation of the federal Commodities Exchange Act.
   A third indicted trader, Robert Mosky, 33, pleaded innocent
before U.S. District Judge Ann C. Williams to charges of
racketeering conspiracy, 26 counts of mail and wire fraud and 37
counts of violating the exchange act.
   A federal grand jury indicted 46 people Aug. 2 for trading
activities at the Merc or the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Later Thursday, the Board of Trade announced its members had
voted to more than triple the in-house fine for each rule
violation, from $75,000 to $250,000, spokesman Mark Prout said.
   ``We wanted to demonstrate that (members) are serious about
maintaining the integrity of these markets,'' Prout said. ``It
should act as quite a deterrent.''
   Five of those indicted, including Walsh and Fuhrman, have so far
agreed to plead guilty and cooperate with prosecutors. Most charges
allege schemes in which traders pocketed profits from trades made
for customers while passing their own losses on to customers.
   Walsh and Fuhrman admitted in plea agreements that their actions
were part of an ongoing pattern of illegal transactions at the
Merc. Both implicated Mosky and agreed to testify against him.
   ``On October 13, 1988, I entered in a pre-arranged trade with
(undercover FBI agent) Randy Jackson...designed to limit my tax
liability and at the same time receive cash back at a later date,''
a downcast Walsh told the judge.
   ``At the time you engaged in this act you knew it was wrong?''
Ms. Williams asked.
   ``Yes,'' Walsh replied.
   FBI agent Randy Jannett, who used the name ``Randy Jackson'' as
an alias during the undercover probe, looked on from the back of
the court as the pleas were entered.
   Walsh said he earned $1,450 in unreported income from two trades
with the agent, one of which was executed for the firm Shearson
Lehman Hutton. The confirmation of the trades through electronic
wire communication resulted in the wire fraud charge.
   On the following day, Walsh said, he sold ``Jackson'' Swiss
franc contracts at a better price than he could have gotten in an
open-market trade and Jackson returned 70 percent of the profit.
   Fuhrman said he made a pre-arranged trade with the undercover
agent on Dec. 15, 1988 and received $1,465 from him in profit. On
another occasion, Fuhrman said, he helped another unidentified
trader earn $5,000 by filling a customer order from the Dean Witter
Reynolds brokerage firm at a higher price than the market would
have dictated.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney James Fleissner said Fuhrman did the
trader a favor in hopes of getting a good turn later.
   Fuhrman agreed and said he knew what he did was illegal.
   Walsh and Fuhrman face prison terms of up to six years and fines
of up to $350,000, but Fleissner said their cooperation would be
considered. They also could face disciplinary action from the
Internal Revenue Service and the Commodities Futures Trading
Commission.
   Both were released on $4,500 personal recognizance bonds.
   Mosky also was released under those terms but agreed that if he
sells his seat on the exchange, he must keep the proceeds in escrow
pending the outcome of the trial.
   So far, 12 traders from the Japanese yen pit at the Merc have
pleaded innocent and three have pleaded guilty.
</TEXT>
