<FIRST>u f BC-DaysInn     08-10 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Days Inn,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Company Agrees to Buy Days Inn, Newspaper Reports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A New York hotel company has agreed to buy
Atlanta-based Days Inn if a financing deal for the budget motel
chain can be arranged, a newspaper reported.
   The Atlanta Journal-Constitution reported in its Thursday
editions that the agreement calls for Tollman-Hundley Hotels, one
of Days Inns' largest franchisees, to buy Days Inn from Reliance
Group Holdings in a deal worth $765 million.
   Reliance, a New York-based investment firm, bought Days Inn from
the Cecil B. Day family for $615 million in 1984 but never intended
to be a long-term owner of the chain.
   Under the agreement, the newspaper reported, the hotels'
management would be retained and the headquarters would remain in
Atlanta.
   ``We just want to see them do more of the same,'' said Monty D.
Hundley of Tollman-Hundley. ``The people running the company are
doing a heck of a job, and we'd like to see them continue.''
   Days Inn bills itself as the third-largest hotel chain in the
world, with 858 hotels in operation and 472 under development.
   Days Inn President Michael A. Leven said he hopes the company
will become the second-largest hotel chain by 1993, doubling in
size to surpass Holiday Inn.
   Leven said Wednesday he believes Tollman-Hundley will be
supportive of expansion efforts.
   ``They are hotel people very committed to the Days Inn system,''
he said.
   Tollman-Hundley company owns 129 hotels, including 48 Days Inns.
</TEXT>
