<FILEID>AP-NR-08-10-89 2357EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Drexel-LincolnSavings     08-10 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Drexel-Lincoln Savings,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: Regulators Probing Lincoln-Drexel Ties</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators are investigating
whether Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. and the former owner of Lincoln
Savings &amp; Loan manipulated the thrift for their own benefit,
according to a published report.
   The Federal Home Loan Bank Board and the Federal Deposit
Insurance Corp. are examining the relationship between American
Continental Corp. and Drexel as part of an investigation of
Lincoln's collapse, The Orange County Register reported in
Thursday's editions.
   The federal agencies now jointly manage Irvine, Calif.-based
Lincoln, which was seized by federal regulators on April 14.
   The bank board has blamed Phoenix-based American Continental's
business practices for Lincoln's insolvency, which may cost U.S.
taxpayers more than $2 billion to protect insured depositors.
   American Continental entered bankruptcy April 13. That move is
is likely to cost more than $200 million to 23,000 Californians who
own uninsured corporate notes sold by Lincoln branches.
   The Register, based in Santa Ana, said it had obtained a
memorandum indicating that regulators are examining:
   _New York-based Drexel's purchase of more than 10 percent of
American Continental stock without telling savings and loan
regulators.
   _American Continental's employee stock ownership plan, which
bought the stake back from the investment firm for $12 million.
ESOP purchases of stock from various insiders have been criticized
by the bank board and holders of the uninsured notes as a way for
insiders to dump the stock at artificially high prices.
   _Drexel letters supporting the value of stock in another company
that Lincoln held. Those shares were then passed from Lincoln to
its parent company, which made a $9 million profit, according to
the memorandum.
   No individual Drexel employees were cited in the memorandum and
it is unclear how many Drexel traders were involved in transactions
with American Continental, the Register said.
   American Continental defended the arrangement. ``There was
absolutely nothing wrong,'' said American Continental attorney Mel
McDonald.
   Drexel spokesman Steve Anreder declined to comment on the firm's
ties to American Continental.
   Drexel has agreed to plead guilty to felonies and pay a $650
million fine to settle unrelated financial fraud charges with the
government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
